{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines", "text_new": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in the Philippines}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Philippine English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines\n| map1            = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in the Philippines.svg\n| legend1         = {{center|Map of provinces (including Metro Manila) with confirmed COVID-19 cases (as of April 16){{refn|group=map note|name=PHmapnote|Breakdown of confirmed cases is according to the [http://www.doh.gov.ph/covid19tracker COVID-19 Case Tracker] of the Department of Health (DOH). Take note that the map may not reflect all affected localities. The methodology on how patients with confirmed COVID-19 infection are recorded in a particular locality in the tracker is unclear and may vary. The source also notes that ''25% of the province-level data are still undergoing validation''.<br /><br />\nThe DOH only tracks cases per province, component localities of Metro Manila, and select independent cities.\n{{bulleted list\n|Other independent cities's cases are grouped together with their geographically associated provinces (e.g [[Puerto Princesa]] with [[Palawan]]).\n|[[Cotabato City]]'s cases are still considered as cases under the [[Soccsksargen]] region despite being part of Bangsamoro since the city has not yet formally been turned over to the Bangsamoro regional government. For the purpose of the map, its cases are considered part of [[Maguindanao]].\n}}<br />\nSee [[#Affected regions|Affected regions]] section below for a more comprehensive list of affected localities.}}}}\n{{legend|#3a0000|500+ confirmed}}\n{{legend|#510000|100\u2013499 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#900000|71\u201399 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#c80200|51\u201370 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#ee7070|21\u201350 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#ffC0C0|1\u201320 confirmed}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = Philippines\n| first_case      = [[Manila]]\n| arrival_date    = January 30, 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=30|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| active_cases    = \n| confirmed_cases = 6,087\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = \n| recovery_cases  = 516\n| deaths          = 397\n| territories     = \n| website         = {{ubl|{{URL|http://www.covid19.gov.ph}}|{{URL|https://www.doh.gov.ph/covid19tracker}}}}\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread to the [[Philippines]] on January 30, 2020, when the first case of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) was confirmed in [[Metro Manila]]. It involved a 38-year-old Chinese woman who was confined in the [[San Lazaro Hospital, Manila|San Lazaro Hospital]] in [[Manila]]. The second case was confirmed on February 2, that of a 44-year-old Chinese man who died a day earlier, which was also the first confirmed death from the disease outside mainland China.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ramzy|first=Austin|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/02/world/asia/philippines-coronavirus-china.html|title=Philippines Reports First Coronavirus Death Outside China|date=February 2, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live|last2=May|first2=Tiffany}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/250815-coronavirus-what-we-know-about-first-death-outside-china|title=Coronavirus: What we know about first death outside China|date=February 2, 2020|work=Rappler|access-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live|agency=Agence France-Presse}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/02/02/20/coronavirus-what-we-know-about-first-death-outside-china|title=Coronavirus: What we know about first death outside China|date=February 2, 2020|work=ABS-CBN News|access-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live|agency=Agence France-Presse}}</ref> The first case of someone without travel history abroad was confirmed on March 5, a 62-year-old male who frequented a Muslim prayer hall in [[San Juan, Metro Manila]], raising suspicions that a community transmission of COVID-19 is already underway in the Philippines. The man's wife was confirmed to have contracted COVID-19 on March 7, which was also the first local transmission to be confirmed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/6/san-juan-muslim-prayer-hall-coronavirus.html|title=San Juan prayer hall frequented by coronavirus patient temporarily closed|publisher=CNN Philippines|website=cnnphilippines.com|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/03/06/20/greenhills-mall-implements-precautionary-measures-vs-coronavirus|title=Greenhills Mall implements 'precautionary measures' vs coronavirus|work=ABS-CBN News|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Manually update this at the end of the Philippine working day, as the DOH gives updates after 4 pm, local time-->As of April 18, 2020, there have been 6,087 confirmed cases of the disease in the country. Out of these cases, 516 recoveries and 397 deaths were recorded. The Philippines has conducted 56,048 tests as of April 17, including repeat tests, and have tested over 49,613 individuals.<ref name=\"COVID-19 tracker\">{{cite web|url=https://www.doh.gov.ph/covid19tracker |title=COVID-19 Tracker |website=doh.gov.ph |publisher=[[Department of Health (Philippines)|Department of Health]] |url-status=live |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://endcov.ph/dashboard/|title=COVID-19|last=|first=|date=March 27, 2020|website=COVID-19|publisher=University of the Philippines 2020|url-status=live|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/multimedia/infographic/03/17/20/tracking-covid-19-cases-in-the-philippines|title=Tracking COVID-19 cases in the Philippines|date=|work=ABS-CBN News|accessdate=April 11, 2020|url-status=live|publisher=ABS-CBN Investigative and Research Group}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/specials/content/137/covid-19-dashboard/|title=COVID-19 Dashboard: Summary of Confirmed Coronavirus Disease 2019 Cases in the Philippines|date=|work=GMA News Online|access-date=April 11, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.inquirer.net/novel-coronavirus-update|title=Novel Coronavirus Update|date=|work=Inquirer|accessdate=April 11, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On April 17, the Philippines became the second most affected country in [[Southeast Asia]], after being surpassed by [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Indonesia|Indonesia]];<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/overseas/04/17/20/indonesia-overtakes-ph-with-highest-number-of-coronavirus-cases-in-southeast-asia |title=Indonesia overtakes PH with highest number of coronavirus cases in Southeast Asia |date=April 17, 2020 |work=[[ABS-CBN News]] |access-date=April 17, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> the country however, for a brief period, was the most affected country in the region after surpassing [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Malaysia|Malaysia]] on April 14.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/04/13/world/asia/13reuters-health-coronavirus-malaysia.html/|title=Malaysia Reports 134 New Coronavirus Cases, One New Death|publisher=New York Times|work=Reuters|date=April 13, 2020|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> The largest single-day increase in the number of confirmed cases was on March 31, when 538 new cases were announced.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/732050/philippines-covid-19-cases-now-2-084-deaths-rise-to-88/story/|title=Philippines' COVID-19 cases now 2,084; deaths rise to 88|first=Julia Mari|last=Ornedo|work=GMA News|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> Meanwhile, the smallest single-day increase since the last week of March was on April 4, when only 76 new cases were announced. All of the [[Regions of the Philippines|country's 17 regions]] have recorded at least a case.\n\nThe [[Research Institute for Tropical Medicine]] (RITM) in [[Muntinlupa]], Metro Manila, is the medical facility where suspected cases are being tested for COVID-19 since January 30, 2020. Before that date, confirmatory tests were made abroad. Currently, sixteen sub-national laboratories (in Metro Manila, Baguio, Bicol, Cebu, Davao, and Iloilo) are also conducting testings while several laboratories are still undergoing proficiency testing before use.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1250910/fwd-doh-more-laboratories-expected-to-be-opened-for-covid-19-testing-within-the-week|title=DOH: More COVID-19 testing labs expected to open|first=Daphne|last=Galvez|publisher=Philippine Daily Inquirer|website=inquirer.net|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1098214|title=Private labs for Covid-19 testing to open this week|first=Ma. Teresa|last=Montemayor|publisher=Philippine News Agency|website=png.gov.ph|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{main|Timeline of the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Philippines medical cases chart}}===January\u2013February 2020 \u2013 first cases===\nThe Philippines reported its first suspected case of COVID-19 in January 2020. The case was that of a 5-year-old boy in Cebu, who arrived in the country in January 12 with his mother.<ref name=firstsuspected>{{cite news |last1=Crisostomo |first1=Sheila |title=DOH probing Philippines' 1st suspected case of coronavirus |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/01/22/1986773/doh-probing-philippines-1st-suspected-case-coronavirus |accessdate=April 15, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=January 22, 2020}}</ref> At that time, the Philippines has no capability to conduct tests to confirm suspected COVID-19 cases.<ref name=\"whyncovgma\">{{cite news |title=Why nCoV fatality's infection was confirmed later than Philippines' first case |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/724652/why-ncov-fatality-s-infection-was-confirmed-later-than-philippines-first-case/story/ |accessdate=February 3, 2020 |work=GMA News |date=February 3, 2020 |quote=\"Since we (RITM) already had the capability for testing Thursday last week, we decided to test the sample of the other PUIs sent to us,\" RITM director Dr. Celia Carlos said in a separate press briefing in Malaca\u00f1ang. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203155225/https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/724652/why-ncov-fatality-s-infection-was-confirmed-later-than-philippines-first-case/story/ |archive-date=February 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"ritmnow\">{{cite news |last1=Panganiban-Perez |first1=Tina |title=RITM now running nCoV tests \u2013 DOH spox |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/724343/ritm-now-running-ncov-tests-doh-spox/story/ |accessdate=February 2, 2020 |work=GMA News |date=January 31, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202155447/https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/724343/ritm-now-running-ncov-tests-doh-spox/story/ |archive-date=February 2, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The boy tested positive for \"non-specific pancoronavirus assay\" by the [[Research Institute for Tropical Medicine]] (RITM) in Muntinlupa, and samples from the boy were sent to the Victorian Infectious Disease Reference Laboratory in Melbourne, Australia for confirmatory testing to determine the specific coronavirus strain.<ref name=firstsuspected/> The boy tested negative for COVID-19 but several suspected cases were reported in various parts of the country.<ref name=\"dohtracks\">{{cite news |last1=Arcilla |first1=Jan |title=DoH tracks suspected new cases of 2019-nCoV |url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/01/26/news/national/doh-tracks-suspected-new-cases-of-2019-ncov/677378/ |accessdate=April 15, 2020 |work=Manila Times |date=January 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe RITM developed capability to conduct confirmatory tests for COVID-19 in response to the emergence of suspected COVID-19 cases. It started conducting confirmatory tests on January 30.<ref name=\"whyncovgma\"/><ref name=\"ritmnow\"/>\n\nThe first case of COVID-19 in the Philippines was confirmed on the same day. The diagnosed patient was a 38-year-old Chinese woman from [[Wuhan]], the origin of the disease, who had arrived in [[Manila]] from Hong Kong on January 21.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news |title=Philippines confirms first case of new coronavirus |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/01/30/20/philippines-confirms-first-case-of-new-coronavirus |accessdate=January 30, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=January 30, 2020}}</ref> She was admitted to the [[San Lazaro Hospital, Manila|San Lazaro Hospital]] in Manila<ref name=\"companion\">{{cite news |last1=Magsino |first1=Dona |title=Companion of first nCoV patient in Philippines also at San Lazaro \u2014DOH |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/724311/companion-of-first-ncov-patient-in-philippines-also-at-san-lazaro-doh/story/ |accessdate=January 31, 2020 |work=GMA News |date=January 31, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131073955/https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/724311/companion-of-first-ncov-patient-in-philippines-also-at-san-lazaro-doh/story/ |archive-date=January 31, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> on January 25 after she sought a consultation due to a mild cough. At the time of the confirmation announcement, the Chinese woman was already [[asymptomatic]].<ref name=\"phconfirms\"/>\n\nThe second case was confirmed on February 2, a 44-year-old Chinese male who was the companion of the first case. His death on February 1 was the first recorded outside China. He suffered from [[coinfection]] with [[influenza]] and ''[[Streptococcus pneumoniae]]''.<ref name=\":01\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/first-coronavirus-death-outside-china-reported-philippines-n1128371|title=First coronavirus death outside China reported in Philippines\n|date=February 2, 2020|website=NBC News|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn February 5, the DOH confirmed a third case in a 60-year-old Chinese woman who flew into [[Cebu City]] from Hong Kong on January 20 before she traveled to [[Bohol]] where she consulted a doctor at a private hospital on January 22, due to fever and [[rhinitis]]. Samples taken from the patient on January 24 returned a negative result, but the DOH was notified on February 3 that samples taken from the patient on January 23 tested positive for the virus. The patient upon recovery on January 31 was allowed to go home to China.<ref name=\"doh3rd\">{{cite web|url=https://www.doh.gov.ph/doh-press-release/doh-confirms-3rd-2019-nCoV-ARD-case-in-PH|title=DOH confirms 3rd 2019-nCoV ARD Case iN PH|last=|first=|date=February 5, 2020|website=Department of Health (Philippines)|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205081612/https://www.doh.gov.ph/doh-press-release/doh-confirms-3rd-2019-nCoV-ARD-case-in-PH|archive-date=February 5, 2020|accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===March 2020 \u2013 early spread===\nAfter a month of reporting no new cases, on March 6, the DOH announced two cases consisting of two Filipinos. One is a 48-year-old man with a travel history to Japan, returning on February 25 and reported symptoms on March 3.<ref name=\"DOHNC\">{{cite news |last1=Punzalan |first1=Jamaine |title=Philippines' new coronavirus cases now at 5, including potential local transmission |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/06/20/new-coronavirus-case-in-philippines-possible-local-transmission |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref> The other is a 60-year-old man with a history of hypertension and diabetes who experienced symptoms on February 25 and was admitted to a hospital on March 1 when he experienced pneumonia. He had last visited a Muslim prayer hall in [[San Juan, Metro Manila|San Juan]].<ref name=\"DOHNC\"/> The DOH confirmed that the fifth case had no travel history outside the Philippines and is, therefore, the first case of local transmission. A sixth case was later confirmed, that of a 59-year-old woman who is the wife of the fifth case.<ref name=\"codered\">{{cite news |title=CODE RED: Philippines' coronavirus cases rise to 6, DOH confirms local transmission |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/07/20/code-red-philippines-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-6-doh-confirms-local-transmission |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> Since then, the Department of Health recorded a continuous increase in the number of COVID-19 cases in the country.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/731898/philippines-records-1546-covid-19-cases-78-deaths/story/|title=Philippines' COVID-19 death toll rises to 78; cases soar to 1,546|first=Julia Mari|last=Ornedo|publisher=GMA News|website=gmanetwork.com|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeveral measures were imposed to mitigate the spread of the disease in the country, including bans on travel to [[mainland China]], [[Hong Kong]], [[Macau]], and [[South Korea]]. On March 7, 2020, the [[Department of Health (Philippines)|Department of Health]] (DOH) raised its \"Code Red Sub-Level 1,\" with a recommendation to the [[President of the Philippines]] to impose a \"public health emergency\" authorizing the DOH to mobilize resources for the procurement of safety gear and the imposition of preventive quarantine measures.<ref name=\"phconfirms\">{{cite news|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/728715/doh-recommends-declaration-of-public-health-emergency-after-covid-19-local-transmission/story/|title=DOH recommends declaration of public health emergency after COVID-19 local transmission|date=March 7, 2020|accessdate=March 7, 2020|url-status=live|publisher=GMA News Online}}</ref> On March 9, President [[Rodrigo Duterte]] issued Proclamation No. 922, declaring the country under a state of public health emergency.<ref name=\"phe\">{{cite news|last=Parrocha|first=Azer|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1095955|title=State of public health emergency declared in PH|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 9, 2020|url-status=live|publisher=Philippine News Agency}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, President Duterte declared \"Code Red Sub-Level 2,\" issuing a partial lockdown<!-- common term for 'community quarantine' --> on Metro Manila to prevent a nationwide spread of COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/729459/code-red-sub-level-2-duterte-announces-tougher-measures-vs-covid-19-threat/story/|title=Code Red Sub-Level 2: Duterte announces 'community quarantine' vs. COVID-19|date=March 12, 2020|publisher=GMA News Online|url-status=live|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/12/COVID-19-Metro-Manila-restrictions-Philippines.html|title=Duterte declares lockdown of Metro Manila for 30 days due to COVID-19|date=March 12, 2020|publisher=[[CNN Philippines]]|url-status=live|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The lockdowns were expanded on March 16, placing the entirety of [[Luzon]] under an \"[[2020 Luzon enhanced community quarantine|enhanced community quarantine]]\" or a total lockdown.<ref name=\"luzon lockdown\">{{cite news|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/729875/duterte-orders-lockdown-of-entire-luzon-due-to-covid-19-threat/story/|title=Duterte orders lockdown of entire Luzon due to COVID-19 threat|first=Virgil|last=Lopez|publisher=GMA News|website=gmanetwork com|date=March 16, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref> Other local governments outside Luzon followed [[2020 Philippine community quarantines|in implementing similar lockdowns]]. On March 17, President Duterte issued Proclamation No. 929, declaring the Philippines under a [[State of emergency|state of calamity]] for a tentative period of six months.<ref name=\"state of calamity\">{{cite news|last1=Kabiling|first1=Genalyn|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/17/duterte-declares-state-of-calamity-over-ph-for-next-6-months-amid-rise-in-covid-19-cases/|title=Duterte declares state of calamity over PH for next 6 months amid rise in COVID-19 cases|date=March 17, 2020|work=[[Manila Bulletin]]|accessdate=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAdditional facilities started to conduct confirmatory testing. On March 20, four facilities namely the Southern Philippines Medical Center in Davao City, Vicente Sotto Memorial Medical Center in Cebu City, Baguio General Hospital and Medical Center in Benguet, and San Lazaro Hospital in Manila began conducting tests as well augmenting the RITM.<ref name=howcovidtesting>{{cite news |last1=Modesto |first1=Catherine |title=How COVID-19 testing is conducted in PH |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/20/coronavirus-testing-in-philippines.html |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Other facilities began operations as well in the following days.\n\nOn March 25, the President signed the [[Bayanihan to Heal as One Act]], which gave him additional powers to handle the outbreak.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tomacruz|first=Sofia|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/255718-duterte-signs-law-granting-special-powers-coronavirus-outbreak|title=Duterte signs law granting himself special powers to address coronavirus outbreak|date=March 25, 2020|work=Rappler|accessdate=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Duterte signs\">{{cite news|last=Aguilar|first=Krissy|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1247988/duterte-signs-law-granting-him-special-powers-vs-covid-19|title=Duterte signs law on special powers vs COVID-19|date=March 25, 2020|work=Inquirer|access-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===April 2020===\nLuzon's Enhanced Community Quarantine (ECQ) originally set to end on April 14 was extended to the end of the month. The table below gives the date when the number of DOH's confirmed cases reaches a new thousand:\n\n{| class =\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\" \n|-\n! Date !! Number of<br> confirmed cases\n|-\n| Mar 28 || 1075\n|-\n| Mar 31 || 2084\n|-\n| Apr 04 || 3094\n|-\n| Apr 09 || 4076\n|-\n| Apr 14 || 5223\n|-\n| Apr 18 || 6087\n|}\n\nAs one can see, there are about 1000 new cases every 4-5 days. Without the ECQ, it is uncertain whether the infection rate will increase, decrease, or remain the same.\n\n== Cases ==\n=== Summary ===\nThe table below are the 217 confirmed cases chronologically recorded from January 30 up to March 19. Note that not all patients were admitted for hospitalization; some with mild condition were isolated and instead placed under home quarantine protocol. However, with the lack of data coming from the Department of Health in who of the patients that tested positive were really admitted to a medical facility or who were made to be placed under the home quarantine protocol, all patients' status in this table are classified to be ''admitted'' unless stated otherwise. Also with the lack of available information in what kind of transmission of the disease the patients' have contracted, all with ''for validation'' label stated in the data gathered from the official COVID-19 tracker are presumed to have been infected via ''local'' transmission; while all patients with history of travel from abroad are presumed to have ''imported'' the disease, unless proven to have been infected via ''local'' transmission. For the ''facility of admission or consultation'' and ''local residence'' columns with ''for validation'' data, such indicates that no data were provided by the Department of Health.\n\nFurther, those patients with no traceable infection connection shall be deemed as infected from an ''unknown source of infection'' (as stated in the notes).\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Philippines medical cases summary}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==== Notable cases ====\n<!-- Entries here MUST have Wikipedia pages. Per [[WP:NOTE]]. -->\nThree incumbent and two former [[Senate of the Philippines|Senators of the Philippines]] have contracted COVID-19. On March 16, Senate Majority Leader [[Juan Miguel Zubiri]] confirmed that he tested positive for COVID-19, although he claimed he was asymptomatic.<ref name=\"Zubiri\">{{cite news |last1=Lalu |first1=Gabriel Pabico |title=Senator Zubiri tests positive for COVID-19 |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1243160/senator-zubiri-tests-positive-for-covid-19-total-lockdown-covid19ph |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 25, Senator [[Koko Pimentel]] announced that he had also tested positive for COVID-19.<ref name=\"Pimentel\">{{cite news |last1=Cabico |first1=Gaea Katreena |title=Pimentel becomes second senator to test positive for COVID-19 |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/25/2003350/pimentel-becomes-second-senator-test-positive-covid-19 |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The following day, Senator [[Sonny Angara]] became the third senator to announce his COVID-19 diagnosis after yielding a positive result.<ref name=\"Angara\">{{cite news |last1=Ramos |first1=Christia Marie |title=BREAKING: Senator Angara positive for COVID-19 |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1248773/breaking-senator-angara-positive-for-covid-19 |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> On March 31, former Senator [[Bongbong Marcos]] also tested positive for COVID-19 after receiving his March 28 test results from the Research Institute for Tropical Medicine (RITM).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/732076/bongbong-marcos-positive-for-covid-19/story/|title=Bongbong Marcos positive for COVID-19|first=Joahna Lei|last=Casilao|work=GMA News|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> Marcos said that he felt unwell upon returning from a trip to [[Spain]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Relativo |first1=James |title=Kumpirmado: Bongbong Marcos positibo sa COVID-19 |url=https://www.philstar.com/pilipino-star-ngayon/bansa/2020/03/31/2004618/kumpirmado-bongbong-marcos-positibo-sa-covid-19 |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=March 31, 2020 |language=Filipino}}</ref> Another former Senator, [[Heherson Alvarez]], and his wife were reported to be in critical condition after contracting the virus.<ref name=\"Virata, Alvarez\">{{cite news |last1=Tupas |first1=Emmanuel |last2=Felipe |first2=Cecille Suerte |last3=Flores |first3=Helen |last4=Villanueva |first4=Rhodina |last5=Santos |first5=Rudy |title=A\u00f1o, Bongbong, Virata test positive |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/04/01/2004777/ao-bongbong-virata-test-positive |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> \n\nAmong the Cabinet of the President Rodrigo Duterte's administration, Interior Secretary [[Eduardo A\u00f1o]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Talabong|first1=Rambo|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/256561-dilg-secretary-eduardo-ano-tests-positive-coronavirus|title=DILG Secretary Eduardo A\u00f1o tests positive for coronavirus|date=March 31, 2020|work=Rappler|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>and Education Secretary [[Leonor Briones]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/733341/deped-chief-briones-tests-positive-for-covid-19/story/|title=DepEd chief Briones tests positive for COVID-19|work=GMA News|date=April 9, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> were confirmed to have tested positive for COVID-19. [[Armed Forces of the Philippines]] [[Chief of Staff of the Armed Forces of the Philippines|Chief of Staff]] Gen. [[Felimon Santos Jr.|Felimon Santos, Jr.]] also tested positive for COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sadongdong|first=Martin|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/27/afp-chief-of-staff-tests-positive-for-covid-19/|title=AFP Chief of Staff tests positive for COVID-19|date=March 27, 2020|work=Manila Bulletin|access-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 31, former [[Prime Minister of the Philippines|Prime Minister]] and Finance Secretary [[Cesar Virata]] was reported to have been admitted to the intensive care unit of [[St. Luke's Medical Center \u2013 Global City]] due to a stroke and pneumonia. Virata was later confirmed to have the virus.<ref name=\"Virata, Alvarez\"/>\n\nOn March 25, [[Rizal]] Governor [[Rebecca Ynares]] announced that she had contracted the virus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cinco |first1=Maricar |title=Rizal Governor Ynares tests positive for COVID-19 |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1248492/rizal-governor-ynares-tests-positive-for-covid-19 |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nActor [[Christopher de Leon]]<ref name=\"de Leon\">{{cite news|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/showbiz/chikaminute/730126/istopher-de-leon-confirms-he-has-covid-19/story/|title=Christopher De Leon confirms he has COVID-19|date=March 17, 2020|work=GMA News Online|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref> and actresses [[Iza Calzado]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Malig|first=Kaela|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/showbiz/chikaminute/731682/iza-calzado-confirmed-positive-for-covid-19/story/|title=Iza Calzado confirmed positive for COVID-19|date=March 28, 2020|work=GMA News Online|access-date=March 28, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>, and [[Sylvia Sanchez]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/entertainment/03/31/20/sylvia-sanchez-husband-test-positive-for-covid-19|title=Sylvia Sanchez, husband test positive for COVID-19|work=ABS-CBN News|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> and were also confirmed to be COVID-positive. [[GMA Network]] journalist [[Howie Severino]] also contracted COVID-19 and recovered.<ref>{{cite news|last=Severino|first=Howie|title=I am Patient 2828|date=April 7, 2020|work=GMA News|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/specials/content/140/howie-severino-i-am-covid-19-patient-2828/|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\nProfessor [[Aileen Baviera]], a former dean of the [[University of the Philippines Asian Center]] and a leading expert on China, died on March 21 at San Lazaro Hospital in Manila due to severe pneumonia caused by COVID-19. She died before seeing the test result that should have confirmed if COVID-19 was the main cause of her death.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Esguerra|first=Christian|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/21/20/leading-ph-expert-on-china-succumbs-to-suspected-covid-19|title=Leading PH expert on China succumbs to suspected COVID-19|date=March 21, 2020|work=ABS-CBN News|accessdate=March 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Cases of Filipino expatriates ====\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable floatright <!---mw-collapsible--->\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:90%; width:40%; clear:right; margin:0 0 0.5em 1em;\"\n|+ Confirmed cases of Filipino nationals outside the Philippines\n! scope=\"col\" | Region{{efn|group=OF|name=of5|The Department of Foreign Affairs' data did not provide a breakdown of cases by country; instead cases were consolidated by region.}}\n! scope=\"col\" | {{abbr|Cases|Confirmed cases}}\n! scope=\"col\" | {{abbr|Treat.|Under treatment}}\n! scope=\"col\" | {{abbr|Recov.|Recovered or Discharged}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Deaths\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | '''Asia-Pacific'''{{efn|group=OF|name=of1|Recorded from 12 countries.}}\n| 272\n| 111\n| 160\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | '''Middle East & Africa'''{{efn|group=OF|name=of2|Recorded from 12 countries.}}\n| 152\n| 141\n| 4\n| 7\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | '''Americas'''{{efn|group=OF|name=of3|Recorded from 4 countries, including those identified on ''[[2020 coronavirus outbreak on the Grand Princess|Grand Princess]]''.}}\n| 177\n| 50\n| 62\n| 65\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | '''Europe'''{{efn|group=OF|name=of4|Recorded from 13 countries.}}\n| 236\n| 181\n| 22\n| 33\n|- class=\"sortbottom\" style=\"font-weight:700; background-color:#eaecf0;\"\n! scope=\"row\" | '''Total'''\n| 837\n| 483\n| 248\n| 106\n|- class=\"sortbottom\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| scope=\"row\" colspan=\"5\" | Data updated as of April 17, 2020 (From the DFA).<ref name=advisory>{{Cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/dfaphl/photos/a.1578521805635981/1600131706808324/?type=3&theater |title=Number of COVID-19 Cases Among Filipinos Abroad |date=April 17, 2020 |publisher=[[Facebook]] |work=[[Department of Foreign Affairs (Philippines)|Department of Foreign Affairs]] |access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n|- class=\"sortbottom\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n| scope=\"row\" colspan=\"5\" | '''Notes''' {{notelist|group=OF}}\n|-\n|}\nThe [[Department of Foreign Affairs (Philippines)|Department of Foreign Affairs]] (DFA) relays information regarding the number of Filipino nationals abroad to have contracted COVID-19.<ref name=advisory/> The DFA keeps an official tally of confirmed Filipino COVID-19 cases per region instead of by country. As of April 4, there are a total of 517 Filipinos abroad confirmed to have contracted COVID-19.<ref name=advisory/> The  first confirmed case of a Filipino national outside the Philippines was announced by the DFA on February 5, 2020\u2014that of a crew member of the ''[[Diamond Princess (ship)|Diamond Princess]]'' cruise ship quarantined off the coast of [[Yokohama]], Japan.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite news |last=Mabasa |first=Roy |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/02/05/dfa-confirms-1st-case-of-filipino-positive-for-ncov/ |title=DFA confirms 1st case of Filipino positive for nCoV |date=February 10, 2020 |work=[[Manila Bulletin]] |access-date=February 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn Asia, outside the ''Diamond Princess'', at least one Filipino case has been confirmed in [[Brunei]],<ref name=bruneiindia>{{cite news |title=2 Filipinos test positive for COVID-19 in Brunei, India |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/22/DFA-Filipinos-test-positive-for-coronavirus-Brunei-India.html |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> [[Japan]],<ref name=\"GMA0315\">{{cite web | url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/pinoyabroad/news/729801/120-overseas-filipinos-infected-with-covid-19-doh/story | title=120 overseas Filipinos infected with COVID-19 \u2013 DOH}}</ref> [[Hong Kong]],<ref name=\"MAR4news\">{{Cite news |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/overseas/03/04/20/another-ofw-in-hong-kong-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-dfa-official |title=Another OFW in Hong Kong tests positive for coronavirus: DFA official |date=March 4, 2020 |work=[[ABS-CBN News]] |access-date=March 10, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[India]],<ref name=bruneiindia/> [[Malaysia]],<ref name=tabligh>{{cite news |last1=Cabrera |first1=Ferdinandh |title=19 Filipino tablighs positive for COVID-19 quarantined in Malaysia |url=https://www.mindanews.com/top-stories/2020/03/19-filipino-tablighs-positive-for-covid-19-quarantined-in-malaysia/ |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=MindaNews |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> [[Kuwait]],<ref>{{cite web | url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/19/Filipino-domestic-worker-tests-positive-COVID-19-Kuwait.html | title=Filipino domestic helper tests positive for COVID-19 in Kuwait}}</ref> [[Lebanon]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/09/2-filipinos-positive-for-covid-19-in-lebanon |title=DFA: 2 Filipinos positive for COVID-19 in Lebanon \u00bb Manila Bulletin News |publisher=News.mb.com.ph |date= |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> [[Singapore]],<ref>{{Cite news |last=Tan |first=Trisha |url=https://filipinotimes.net/uncategorized/2020/02/23/breaking-dfa-confirms-first-filipino-positive-case-covid-19-singapore |title=DFA confirms first case of Filipino positive of COVID-19 in Singapore |date=February 23, 2020 |access-date=February 27, 2020 |work=The Filipino Times}}</ref> and [[United Arab Emirates]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Santos |first=Eimor |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/2/8/filipino-novel-coronavirus-UAE.html |title=Filipino in UAE tests positive for novel coronavirus |publisher=cnnphilippines.com |date=February 8, 2020 |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> One notable case in Asia was that of Philippine ambassador to [[Lebanon]], [[Bernardita Catalla]], who died on April 2 in [[Beirut]] due to complications from COVID-19 and chronic respiratory problems.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Barakat |first1=Mahmoud |title=Philippines' ambassador to Lebanon dies of coronavirus |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/philippines-ambassador-to-lebanon-dies-of-coronavirus/1789064 |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |agency=Anadolu Agency |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFollowing an international [[tabligh]] convention held from February 7 to March 1, 2020, at the Jamek Sri Petaling mosque near [[Kuala Lumpur]], Malaysia, the DFA reported that 19 Filipinos who attended the convention tested positive and were quarantined in Malaysia. Two others managed to return to the Philippines and later tested positive by Philippine health authorities.<ref name=tabligh/>\n\nIn Europe, at least one Filipino case has been confirmed in [[France]],<ref name=\"ortiz2020\">{{cite news |last1=Tomacruz |first1=Sofia |title=PH Council for Foreign Relations president Alan Ortiz dies of coronavirus |url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/255528-alan-ortiz-death-coronavirus-march-23-2020?fbclid=IwAR1TWyo_IimwrE3tBbyAm9v5iDtfpt5t-qZ83Ukxt5HkEOCC-Ojm-VeFUlw |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |publisher=[[Rappler]] |date=March 23, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Greece]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cabico |first1=Gaea Katreena |title=Filipino tests positive for COVID-19 in Greece |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/18/2001925/filipino-tests-positive-covid-19-greece |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> and [[Switzerland]].<ref name=\"Pinay Swiss\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bomboradyo.com/pinay-mula-sa-italy-na-nagpositibo-ng-covid-19-naka-quarantine-sa-isang-hospital-sa-switzerland/ |title=Pinay mula sa Italy na nagpositibo ng Covid-19, naka-quarantine sa isang hospital sa Switzerland |date=March 10, 2020 |work=[[Bombo Radyo Philippines]] |access-date=March 10, 2020 |language=Filipino |trans-title=Filipina from Italy positive for Covid-19, quarantined at a hospital in Switzerland}}</ref> On March 23, Philippine Council for Foreign Relations President Alan Ortiz died in Paris, France.<ref name=\"ortiz2020\"/>\n\nIn the United States, it was confirmed that six Filipinos aboard the ''[[Grand Princess]]'' cruise ship, which docked in [[Oakland, California]], for quarantine, had contracted the virus.<ref name=\"MVGP\">{{cite news |title=Six Filipinos on quarantined cruise ship in US test positive for COVID-19 |url=https://www.cnn.ph/news/2020/3/11/Filipinos-Grand-Princess-COVID-19-coronavirus.html |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>  On March 13, a Filipino working in New York as a diplomat with the [[Philippines and the United Nations|Philippines' UN mission]] was confirmed to be positive for the virus, which led to the entire mission at [[Philippine Center]] being disinfected and closed for the day.<ref>{{cite news |title=Diplomat from Philippines first known coronavirus case at UN in New York |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/world/coronavirus-un-diplomat-new-york-philippines-us-covid-19-12533952 |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |agency=Reuters |via=CNA |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Foreign cases with travel history in the Philippines ====\n{{update section|date=April 2020}}\nCases abroad involving foreigners with travel history in the Philippines has been noted in the early stages of the pandemic in the country. The first three recorded cases involving an Australian, a Japanese, and a Taiwanese national had a history of visiting the Philippines in February 2020. Though it was not confirmed if they have contracted the virus while in the Philippines. There has been speculation that there has been undetected local transmission in the country already with the fifth confirmed case in the country involving a Filipino national with no travel history abroad confirmed in early March 2020.<ref name=\"morequestions\">{{cite news |last1=Malasig |first1=Jeline |title=More questions raised as foreigners with travel history to Philippines test positive for COVID-19 |url=https://www.interaksyon.com/politics-issues/2020/03/06/163652/more-questions-raised-as-foreigners-with-travel-history-to-philippines-test-positive-for-covid-19/ |accessdate=April 15, 2020 |work=InterAksyon |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doh.gov.ph/doh-press-release/DOH-REPORTS-1-COVID-DEATH-AND-3-NEW-CASES |title=DOH REPORTS 1 COVID DEATH AND 3 NEW CASES &#124; Department of Health website |publisher=Doh.gov.ph |date= |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/13/coronavirus-philippines-australia.html |title = Two people who visited PH tested positive for COVID-19 in Australia}}</ref> There have been 12 confirmed cases of foreign nationals who went to the Philippines as of {{date||MDY}}.\n\n=== By demographic ===\nThe oldest person to have recovered from COVID-19 in the Philippines (as of March 31) is reportedly an 83-year-old woman from [[Santa Rosa, Laguna]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Garcia |first1=Maria Angelica |title=83-yr-old lola is oldest to recover from COVID-19 in Philippines |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/regions/732100/83-yr-old-lola-is-oldest-to-recover-from-covid-19-in-philippines/story/?just_in |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> while the youngest patient to die due to complications from the disease (as of April 14) was a 29 days old infant from the province of Batangas.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/04/14/2007299/29-day-old-baby-philippines-youngest-covid-19-fatality |title=29-day-old baby is Philippines' youngest COVID-19 fatality |date=April 14, 2020 |work=[[Philippine Star]] |access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of April 17, the DOH reported that there had been 766 healthcare personnel infected by COVID-19, a three-fold increase from the last week's bulletin. Out of these cases, 339 doctors and 242 nurses had already tested positive. Also of the 339 infected doctors, 22 have already succumbed from the said disease.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/4/17/over-700-health-workers-infected.html |title=Over 700 healthcare workers, including 339 doctors, have contracted COVID-19, DOH says |date=April 17, 2020 |work=[[CNN Philippines]] |access-date=April 17, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== By region ===\n<!-- Please arrange alphabetically except the National Capital Region (Metro Manila) --> \n[[File:COVID-19 pandemic cases in the Philippines by region.svg|thumb|Map of regions with confirmed (red) COVID-19 cases (as of April 16){{refn|group=map note|name=PHmapnote2|Breakdown of confirmed cases by region is according to the [http://www.doh.gov.ph/covid19tracker COVID-19 Case Tracker] of the Department of Health (DOH). Cases in [[Cotabato City]], a part of [[Bangsamoro]], under the [[Soccsksargen]] region since the city has not yet formally been turned over to the Bangsamoro regional government.}}\n{{legend|#3a0000|500+ confirmed}}\n{{legend|#510000|100\u2013499 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#900000|71\u201399 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#c80200|51\u201370 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#ee7070|21\u201350 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#ffC0C0|1\u201320 confirmed}}]]\n\n==== National Capital Region ====\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Metro Manila}}\n\n==== Bangsamoro ====\nThe first case overall in [[Mindanao]] is a resident of [[Lanao del Sur]] who went home from [[San Juan, Metro Manila|San Juan]], [[Metro Manila]]. The case was that of a 54-year-old man who was admitted at the Adventist Medical Center in his home province and was referred to the Northern Mindanao Medical Center on March 8, a health facility outside the region in [[Cagayan de Oro]] after he is suspected to have COVID-19. The case was confirmed on March 11. The man had no known travel history abroad and was suspected to have contracted the disease while he was in Metro Manila.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Timonera |first1=Bobby |title=Mindanao's first COVID-19 case went home to Lanao Sur before admission in Iligan hospital and later CDO |url=https://www.mindanews.com/top-stories/2020/03/mindanaos-first-covid-19-case-went-home-to-lanao-sur-before-admission-in-iligan-hospital-and-later-cdo/ |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=MindaNews |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Bicol Region ====\nThe DOH announced the first three cases in the Bicol Region on March 27. The cases were that of two male patients (50 and 53 years old) confined at the Bicol Regional Training Hospital in Daraga, Albay and a 48-year-old female from Naga, Camarines Sur.<ref name=bicolfirst/> From March 28 to April 1, the DOH reported 4 more cases, totalling 7 cases.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.rappler.com/nation/256258-doh-bicol-bares-fourth-coronavirus-case-march-28-2020|title= DOH Bicol reports 1 new case}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/01/20/bicol-confirms-3-new-cases-of-covid-19-bringing-total-to-7|title= Bicol confirms one new cases of COVID-19 bringing total to 7}}</ref> On April 2, 2020, the DOH reported one new case and first three recoveries all from the province of Albay, totalling 10 cases.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n<!-- ==== Cagayan Valley ==== -->\n==== Calabarzon ====\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Calabarzon}}\nThe first confirmed COVID-19 case in [[Calabarzon]] is a resident of [[Cainta, Rizal]] who frequented a Muslim prayer hall in San Juan, Metro Manila.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/7/cainta-rizal-coronavirus-philippines.html|title=Cainta, Rizal steps up coronavirus measures amid confirmed case|first=Elmor|last=Santos|work=CNN Philippines|date=March 7, 2020|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> The individual's case is also the first confirmed local transmission of COVID-19 in the country.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/12/2000450/doh-first-local-transmission-wife-among-three-new-covid-19-deaths|title=First local COVID-19 transmission case, wife among 3 new deaths in Philippines|first=Ratziel|last=San Juan|work=The Philippine Star|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> The patient's wife also contracted the disease.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://tribune.net.ph/index.php/2020/03/13/cainta-couple-die-from-covid-19/|title=Cainta couple dies from COVID-19|first=Neil|last=Alcober|work=Daily Tribune|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Caraga ====\nThe first confirmed COVID-19 case in Caraga was confirmed on April 6. It involved a 68-year-old patient from [[Butuan]] that recently traveled to Metro Manila. The patient was admitted to the Caraga Regional Hospital.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/06/20/caraga-confirms-first-covid-19-case|title=Caraga confirms first COVID-19 case|work=ABS-CBN News|date=April 6, 2020|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Cordillera Administrative Region ====\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Cordillera Administrative Region}}\n\n==== Central Luzon ====\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Central Luzon}}\nThe first three cases in the Central Luzon region was confirmed by the DOH on March 11. Two of them are repatriates quarantined at [[New Clark City]] in Capas, Tarlac and the third patient is a resident of San Jose del Monte, Bulacan who was admitted to a hospital in Caloocan, Metro Manila.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/03/12/news/regions/doh-confirms-3-covid-19-cases-in-central-luzon/702417/|title=DoH confirms 3 Covid-19 cases in Central Luzon|first=Frederick|last=Silverio|work=The Manila Times|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Central Visayas ====\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Central Visayas}}\n\n==== Davao Region ====\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Davao Region}}\nAll provinces, except [[Davao Occidental]] has at least one confirmed COVID-19 case. Davao City also has reported confirmed cases. Davao Region's first case was that of a 21-year-old female resident of [[Pantukan, Davao de Oro]] who had a travel history to the United Kingdom and Manila. The patient arrived in Davao City in February 29 and was placed in isolation at a health facility on March 9 after undergoing consultation for a cough. The following day, the patient was referred to a Davao Regional Medical Center in [[Tagum]].<ref name=davaoregionfirstcaserecovers>{{cite news |last1=Colina |first1=Antonio IV |title=Davao region's first COVID-19 patient recovers, discharged from hospital |url=https://www.mindanews.com/top-stories/2020/03/davao-regions-first-covid-19-patient-recovers-discharged-from-hospital/ |accessdate=April 11, 2020 |work=MindaNews |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeveral cases across Mindanao, not just in the Davao Region, has been linked to cockfighting derby held in March 2020 in Matina, Davao City.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mindanews.com/top-stories/2020/04/another-covid-19-case-in-northcot-also-attended-the-matina-gallera-derby/|title=Another COVID-19 case in NorthCot also attended the Matina Gallera derby|first=Malu|last=Cadelina-Manar|work=Mindanews|date=April 10, 2020|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Six of eleven confirmed COVID-19 deaths in the Davao Region as April 6 is attributed to the Matina cluster.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mindanews.com/top-stories/2020/04/6-of-11-deaths-in-davao-region-traced-to-cockpit-derby-contact-tracing-has-not-reached-even-a-third1/|title=6 of 11 COVID-19 deaths in Davao region traced to cockpit derby; contact tracing has not reached \"even a third\"|first=Carolyn|last=Arguilas|work=Mindanews|date=April 7, 2020|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Eastern Visayas ====\nThe first case recorded in Eastern Visayas was a 51-year-old woman from [[Catarman, Northern Samar]]. She was admitted to a referral hospital in [[Tacloban]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Eastern Visayas' 1st coronavirus patient discharged |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/01/20/eastern-visayas-1st-coronavirus-patient-discharged |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref> The second case was a 63-year-old man from [[Calbayog]], [[Samar]] who was also admitted to a hospital in Tacloban.<ref name=secondcaseWV>{{cite news |title=DOH confirms 2nd Covid-19 case in Eastern Visayas |url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1098319 |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |agency=Philippine News Agency |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> The first cases confirmed due to local transmission were two local government employees in [[Tarangnan]], Samar. The two were in contact with the second case.<ref name=twosamar>{{cite news |last1=Meniano |first1=Sarwell |title=2 Samar hospital workers catch coronavirus |url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1099041 |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Ilocos Region ==== \n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Ilocos Region}}\nThe spread of COVID-19 to the Ilocos Region was confirmed on March 20. The first three cases considered to be that of the Ilocos Region involved: 77-year-old man who died at the same day his COVID-19 infection was confirmed, and the two other cases were that of two local politicians of [[Caba, La Union]] Mayor Philip Caesar Crispino and his wife, Councilor Donna Crispino. The councilor is noted to have a previous travel history to Metro Manila and began manifesting symptoms on March 2.<ref name=\"dohconfirms\">{{cite news |last1=Dilim |first1=Joanne Namnama |title=DOH confirms 3 positive cases of COVID-19 in Region 1 |url=https://pia.gov.ph/news/articles/1036823 |accessdate=April 17, 2020 |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Mimaropa ====\nThe first COVID-19 case in Mimaropa was confirmed on March 20.<ref>{{cite news |title=The official statement from DOH-CHD Mimaropa regarding the first confirmed case of COVID-19 in the region. |url=https://twitter.com/pia_mimaropa/status/1241267471543177216 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=Twitter |agency=Philippine Information Agency - Mimaropa |publisher=Department of Health - Mimaropa |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> The case involved a 26-year-old male Australian tourist in [[Palawan]] who had already left the province at the time of confirmation. The tourist arrived in Manila on March 5 before taking a flight to Puerto Princesa. The man stayed for five days in a resort in [[San Vicente, Palawan|San Vicente]] prior to seeking medical consultation after he exhibited symptoms. He was brought to the Palawan Provincial Hospital in Puerto Princesa for sample collection for testing on March 14. The tourist managed to secure clearance after two days to take a \"mercy flight\" to get out of the province to Clark after his fever subsided.<ref>{{cite news |title=Palawan records first coronavirus case |url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/255349-palawan-records-first-coronavirus-case |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=Rappler |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n<!-- ==== Northern Mindanao ==== -->\n<!-- ==== Soccsksargen ==== -->\n==== Western Visayas ====\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Western Visayas}}\nWestern Visayas confirmed its first case on March 20. The case was that of a 56-year-old man in Bacolod who has a history of travelling to the United Kingdom and Metro Manila. The man arrived in Negros Occidental on February 29 and has fully recovered by March 31.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bacolod man, Western Visayas' first COVID-19 case, now fully recovered |url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/256453-man-bacolod-western-visayas-first-coronavirus-covid-19-case-fully-recovered-march-30-2020 |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |work=Rappler |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> The first recorded death in the region that of a 62-year-old female in Bacolod occurred on March 31. The following day, cases of local transmission was confirmed in Bacolod and the municipalities of Guimbal and Lambunao in Iloilo province. As of April 1, all component local government units except Antique and Guimaras have confirmed at least one case of COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nicavera |first1=Erwin |title=Western Visayas health officials confirm local transmission in Bacolod City |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/regions/732287/western-visayas-health-officials-confirm-local-transmission-in-bacolod-city/story/ |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |work=GMA News |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n<!-- ==== Zamboanga Peninsula ==== -->\n\n=== Suspected cases ===\nThe DOH previously used the designation \"[[Patient Under Investigation|patients under investigation]]\" (PUIs) and \"persons under monitoring\" (PUMs) to manage suspected and confirmed cases. PUIs involved individuals who had a travel history to Wuhan but by February 3, the DOH has expanded the scope of PUIs to include individuals who had a travel history to any part of China.<ref name=\"COVID-19 tracker\"/> Persons under monitoring are asymptomatic individuals with known history of exposure to another person with confirmed COVID-19 infection.<ref name=\"asymptomaticexcluded\">{{cite news |last1=San Juan |first1=Ratziel |title=Asymptomatic cases excluded in DOH's new COVID-19 classifications |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/04/11/2006613/asymptomatic-cases-excluded-dohs-new-covid-19-classifications |accessdate=April 11, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn April 11, the DOH revised its terminology for PUIs; \"suspect\" and \"probable\" cases. Suspect cases involves individuals exhibiting flu-like symptoms and has a history of travel to areas with reported local transmission within 14 days prior the manifestation of their symptoms. Someone with fever, cough or shortness of breath who is above 60 years old, pregnant, with other underlying illness, or a health worker could also be considered as a \"suspect\" case. Patients admitted to a hospital due to severe symptoms caused by an undetermined lung disease could also be tagged as a \"suspect\" case. \"Probable\" cases involves persons who underwent testing with results that needs further validation, and those who were tested, but whose test were not facilitated in an official laboratory for an reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR) test.<ref name=\"DOHnewclassification\">{{cite news |title=DOH issues new classification for patients checked for Covid-19 |url=https://www.sunstar.com.ph/article/1852069 |accessdate=April 11, 2020 |work=Sun Star |date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe usage of the PUM designation was discontinued. It was reasoned that it is assumed that the general public has been exposed to COVID-19 due to local or community transmission already ongoing in several parts of the Philippines.<ref name=\"asymptomaticexcluded\"/>\n\n== Statistics ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Philippines medical cases}}\n{{clear}}\n\n== Management ==\n\n===Treatment and remedy===\n[[File:Algorithm for Triage of Patients with Possible COVID-19 Infection in Health Care Facilities (as of March 10, 2020).jpg|thumb|Algorithm for the [[triage]] of patients with possible COVID-19 infection in health care facilities (as of March 10, 2020)]]\nThe Philippine Council on Health Research and Development of the [[Department of Science and Technology (Philippines)|Department of Science and Technology]] (PCHRD-DOST) on February 7 plans to distribute an undisclosed \"functional food\" to help individuals with COVID-19 infection to combat the disease within a month. A \"functional food\" is described by the PCHRD-DOST as similar to how the herb locally known as ''[[tawa-tawa]]'' is used as a remedy against [[dengue]]. The undisclosed functional food is already used for other diseases and is not a drug that requires registration with the FDA.<ref name=\"functionalfood\">{{cite news |last1=Resurreccion |first1=Lyn |title=PHL 'functional food' vs COVID-19 available soon |url=https://businessmirror.com.ph/2020/02/20/phl-functional-food-vs-covid-19-available-soon/ |accessdate=February 22, 2020 |work=BusinessMirror |date=February 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe PCHRD-DOST as part of the government's interagency committee proposed funding for screening for antibodies against COVID-19 in blood specimens collected from COVID-19 PUIs in the Philippines to help contribute to international efforts to understand the disease.<ref name=\"functionalfood\"/> The DOST on April 2 announced that it is seeking collaboration with other countries such as China, Russia, South Korea, Taiwan, and the United Kingdom on endeavors related to COVID-19 vaccine development.<ref>{{cite news |last=Nazario|first=Dhel|title=DOST open to COVID-19 vaccine development collaboration with other countries |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/04/02/dost-open-to-covid-19-vaccine-development-collaboration-with-other-countries/ |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nRussian Ambassador to the Philippines Igor Khovaev announced that the Russian government is offering to donate to Filipino officials a Russian-developed [[over-the-counter drug]] called ''Cicloferon'' claimed to have cured the symptoms of COVID-19 on Russian patients. The FDA and DOH have classified the said drug as treatment rather than cure.<ref name=russiacure>{{cite news |last1=Newman |first1=Minerva |title=Russia offers PH cure for COVID-19 |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/12/russia-offers-ph-cure-for-covid-19/ |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile. even they see these as \"promising\" medicines that are still on trial, DOH warned against the use of drugs that are not yet approved by FDA in treating coronavirus, like ''Fapiravir (Avigan)'', ''Chloroquine'', ''Hydroxychloroquine'', ''Azithromycin'', ''Losartan'', ''Remdesivir'', ''Kaletra'', and other drug cocktails, stating that those might have adverse side-effects, especially if not supervised by healthcare professionals.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/730790/doh-warns-against-using-antimalarial-drug-chloroquine-vs-covid-19/story/|title=DOH warns against using antimalarial drug chloroquine vs. COVID-19|date=March 22, 2020|work=GMA News Online|access-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Imperial|first=Athena|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BgOrBEaSaDU|title=Gamot sa High-blood, Malaria, at HIV, Tinitingnan kung mabisa kontra-COVID; DOH, May babala sa paggamit ng mga ito (1:33:12-1:36:24)|date=March 24, 2020|work=GMA News (YouTube Channel)|access-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Philippine General Hospital is also exploring the [[blood transfusion|transfusion of blood]] sourced from recovered patients as a possible treatment for COVID-19. The hospital has pointed out that blood, specifically its [[Plasma (blood)|plasma]], from recovered patients contains [[antibodies]] which were produced by the body to specifically respond against the [[SARS-CoV-2]] virus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Aguilar |first1=Krissy |title=Duterte asks recovered COVID-19 patients to donate bloo |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1256239/duterte-calls-on-recovered-covid-19-patients-to-donate-blood |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Philippines, with at least 45 other countries, is joining the World Health Organization's [[Solidarity Trial]] to study the effectivity of certain drugs in treating COVID-19 patients. Dr. Marissa Alejandrija of the Philippine Society of Microbiology and Infectious Disease is the Philippines' representative in the study with Health Undersecretary Maria Rosario Vergeire as the official liaison of the DOH in the multinational study.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Galvez |first1=Daphne |title=PH to join WHO's 'solidarity trial' for COVID-19 cure|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1253037/ph-to-join-whos-solidarity-trial-for-covid-19-cure |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Hospital admission policy===\n[[File:Philippine General Hospital COVID-19 ward.jpg|thumb|A ward dedicated for COVID-19 patients at the [[Philippine General Hospital]].]]\nThe DOH has issued a reminder, that Level 2 and 3 hospitals cannot deny admittance of people suspected or confirmed to have COVID-19 infection and refusal of admission is a \"violation of the signed Performance Commitment and shall be dealt with by the [[Philippine Health Insurance Corporation|PhilHealth]] accordingly\". The department said that Level 2 and 3 hospitals can accommodate individuals with mild COVID-19 symptoms while individuals in a serious or critical condition may be transferred to one of the DOH's three referral hospitals; the RITM, [[Lung Center of the Philippines]] in Quezon City and the [[San Lazaro Hospital, Manila|San Lazaro Hospital]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Duque warns hospitals against refusing patients linked to COVID-19 |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/728888/duque-warns-hospitals-against-refusing-patients-linked-to-covid-19/story/ |accessdate=March 10, 2020 |work=GMA Network |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, the DOH announced a revision on their protocol on hospital admission for COVID-19 positive patients. A week prior, the DOH has began sending both asymptomatic patients and individuals with mild symptoms back on their homes for quarantine and continued health monitoring until they have been deemed recovered. Priority are given to high-risk patients or those with severe symptoms for hospital admission.<ref>{{cite news |title=DOH revises hospital admission rules for COVID-19 patients |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/16/Hospital-admission-coronavirus.html |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Disease testing ===\n{{more information|COVID-19 testing}}\n\n==== Testing facilities ====\n{{Location map+ | Philippines\n| width   = 250\n| caption = COVID-19 testing centers in the Philippines (outside Metro Manila)\n| places  =\n  {{Location map~ | Philippines\n  | lat_deg = 16.41\n  | lon_deg = 120.59\n  | label   = [[Baguio General Hospital and Medical Center|BGHMC]]\n  }}\n  {{Location map~ | Philippines\n  | lat_deg = 7.07\n  | lon_deg = 125.6\n  | label   = [[Southern Philippines Medical Center|SPMC]]\n  | position = right\n  }}\n  {{Location map~ | Philippines\n  | lat_deg = 10.3\n  | lon_deg = 123.9\n  | label   = [[Vicente Sotto Memorial Medical Center|VSMMC]]\n  | position = bottom\n  }}\n  {{Location map~ | Philippines\n  | lat_deg = 10.72\n  | lon_deg = 122.57\n  | label   = {{abbr|WVMC|Western Visayas Medical Center}}\n  | position = top\n  }}\n  {{Location map~ | Philippines\n  | lat_deg = 13.13\n  | lon_deg = 123.73\n  | label   = {{abbr|BPHL|Bicol Public Health Laboratory}}\n  | position = right\n  }}\n}}\n{{Location map+ | Metro Manila\n| width   = 250\n| caption = COVID-19 testing centers in Metro Manila\n| places  =\n  {{Location map~ | Metro Manila\n  | lat_deg = 14.40\n  | lon_deg = 121.03\n  | label   = [[Research Institute for Tropical Medicine|RITM]]\n  | position = right\n  | mark = Green pog.svg\n  }}\n  {{Location map~ | Metro Manila\n  | lat_deg = 14.61\n  | lon_deg = 120.98\n  | label   = [[San Lazaro Hospital, Manila|SLH]]\n  | position = left\n  }}\n  {{Location map~ | Metro Manila\n  | lat_deg = 14.58\n  | lon_deg = 120.98\n  | label   = [[University of the Philippines Manila|UP]]\u2013[[National Institutes of Health (Philippines)|NIH]]\n  | position = right\n  }}\n  {{Location map~ | Metro Manila\n  | lat_deg = 14.64\n  | lon_deg = 121.04\n  | label   = [[Lung Center of the Philippines|LCP]]\n  | position = right\n  }}\n  {{Location map~ | Metro Manila\n  | lat_deg = 14.62\n  | lon_deg = 121.02\n  | label   = [[St. Luke's Medical Center \u2013 Quezon City|SLMC\u2013QC]]\n  | position = bottom\n  }}\n}}\n\nBefore January 30, there were no medical facilities in the country that can confirm cases of the virus.<ref name=\"whyncovgma\"/><ref name=\"ritmnow\"/> Before that date, the [[Research Institute for Tropical Medicine]] (RITM) in [[Muntinlupa]] conducted preliminary tests on suspected cases to determine if they are infected with a coronavirus but could not detect the new strain on patients.<ref name=\"eightph\">{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/01/28/1988394/doh-probes-8-cases-suspected-ncov|title=DOH probes 8 cases of suspected nCoV|first=Sheila Crisostomo,Alexis|last=Romero|website=The Philippine Star|access-date=February 8, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127231143/https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/01/28/1988394/doh-probes-8-cases-suspected-ncov|archive-date=January 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Samples from suspected cases with confirmed coronavirus infection had to be sent abroad to the Victorian Infectious Diseases Reference Laboratory in [[Melbourne]], Australia, for confirmatory testing specifically for [[SARS-CoV-2]] strain.<ref name=\"phacquires\">{{cite news |title=PH acquires confirmatory test kits for novel coronavirus |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/1/29/Novel-coronavirus-confirmatory-test-kits-primers-RITM.html |accessdate=January 29, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=January 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129070157/https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/1/29/Novel-coronavirus-confirmatory-test-kits-primers-RITM.html |archive-date=January 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn response to the pandemic following a cleared suspected case, the RITM began the process of acquiring [[Primer (molecular biology)|primers]] and [[reagent]]s to conduct confirmatory tests in the country.<ref name=\"philStarPhilippinesDenyingVisas\"/> On January 29, it was announced that the RITM has acquired confirmatory kits to be able to test cases in the country. A laboratory for the confirmatory test<ref name=\"phacquires\"/> became operational on January 30.<ref name=\"whyncovgma\"/>\n\nThe RITM is also training personnel of four sub-national reference labs of the DOH to help them develop capability to test samples from \"patients under investigation\" (PUIs). These laboratories are at the [[San Lazaro Hospital, Manila|San Lazaro Hospital]] in [[Manila]], the [[Baguio General Hospital and Medical Center|Baguio General Hospital]] in [[Baguio]], the Vicente Sotto Memorial Medical Center in [[Cebu City]], and the [[Southern Philippines Medical Center]] in [[Davao City]]. The DOH has also allowed private health facilities to seek testing accreditation.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sabillo |first1=Kristine |title=Philippines works to expand COVID-19 testing centers outside of capital |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/02/12/20/philippines-works-to-expand-covid-19-testing-centers-outside-of-capital |accessdate=February 12, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=February 12, 2020}}</ref> By March 20, the four health facilities had started testing.<ref name=howcovidtesting/>\n\nThe DOH requires health facilities to undergo an evaluation to be accredited for COVID-19 testing. The five stages of the evaluation are as follows:<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rita |first1=Joviland |title=DOH releases list of hospitals eyed as future laboratories for COVID-19 testing |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/731987/doh-releases-list-of-hospitals-eyed-as-future-laboratories-for-covid-19-testing/story/ |accessdate=April 5, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> \n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"margin:auto; text-align:left; font-size:90%; width:auto;\"\n|+ COVID-19 testing facilities accreditation levels\n! colspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" width=\"30%\" | Stage\n! scope=\"col\" | Description\n|-\n| Stage 1\n| ''self-assessment stage''\n| The administration of the facilities shall conduct an assessment of the facility and its staff \"based on accessibility, design, use of [[laboratory safety]] equipment (including [[personal protective equipment]]), records and documentation, and personnel practices and training.\" As of March 31, 43 facilities across the country have satisfied this stage but not any higher.\n|-\n| Stage 2\n| ''validation stage''\n| The DOH sends officials to verify the self-assessment conducted by the administration of the facilities. As of April 4, 17 facilities have satisfied this stage but not any higher.\n|-\n| Stage 3\n| ''personnel training stage''\n| The DOH conducts a three-day [[training and development]] course at the RITM for personnel who will operate the laboratory. \n|-\n| Stage 4\n| ''proficiency testing stage''\n| Facilities that have reached this stage are eligible to accept samples for COVID-19 testing. \n|-\n|  Stage 5\n| ''full-scale implementation stage''\n| Facilities must test five positive samples to be verified by the RITM. Once verified, the facility is certified and permitted by the DOH to conduct a full-scale sample testing for COVID-19 cases. As of April 18, 17 facilities (aside from the RITM) have satisfied this stage.\n|}\n\n;Operational testing facilities\n* [[Armed Forces of the Philippines Medical Center]] \u2013 [[Quezon City]]\n* [[Baguio General Hospital and Medical Center]] \u2013 [[Baguio]]\n* Bicol Regional Diagnostic and Reference Laboratory \u2013 [[Legazpi, Albay|Legazpi]]\n* [[Chinese General Hospital and Medical Center|Chinese General Hospital]] - [[Manila]]\n* Detoxicare Molecular Diagnostics Laboratory \u2013 [[Mandaluyong]]\n* [[Lung Center of the Philippines]] \u2013 Quezon City\n* [[Makati Medical Center]] \u2013 [[Makati]]\n* [[National Institutes of Health (Philippines)|National Institutes of Health]] \u2013 Manila\n* [[Philippine Red Cross]] \u2013 Mandaluyong\n* [[Research Institute for Tropical Medicine]] \u2013 [[Muntinlupa]]\n* [[San Lazaro Hospital, Manila|San Lazaro Hospital]] \u2013 Manila\n* [[St. Luke's Medical Center \u2013 Global City|St. Luke's Medical Center]] \u2013 Taguig\n* [[St. Luke's Medical Center \u2013 Quezon City|St. Luke's Medical Center]] \u2013 Quezon City\n* [[Southern Philippines Medical Center]] \u2013 [[Davao City]]\n* [[The Medical City]] \u2013 [[Pasig]]\n* [[Vicente Sotto Memorial Medical Center]] \u2013 [[Cebu City]]\n* Western Visayas Medical Center \u2013 [[Iloilo City]]\n\nA testing site is also being planned at the Eastern Visayas Regional Medical Center in [[Tacloban]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sabalza |first1=Gerico |title=DOH eyes Covid-19 testing lab in Eastern Visayas |url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1097589 |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |agency=Philippine News Agency |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThere are also initiatives from local government units to set up their testing centers including Marikina and Muntinlupa.<ref name=marikinadohdefers>{{cite news |last1=Servallos |first1=Neil Jayson |title=DOH defers COVID testing in Marikina |url=https://www.philstar.com/nation/2020/03/24/2002972/doh-defers-covid-testing-marikina |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"muntinlupatesting\">{{cite news |last1=Hicap |first1=Jonathan |title=Muntinlupa wants to establish own COVID-19 testing center |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/24/muntinlupa-wants-to-establish-own-covid-19-testing-center/ |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The Marikina city government procured 3,000 testing kits locally developed by the National Institutes of Health at the [[University of the Philippines]]\u2013[[National Institutes of Health (Philippines)|National Institutes of Health]] (UP\u2013NIH). Marikina's facility is set to open on April 21 (Tuesday) after the issuance of accreditation by the health department.<ref>{{cite news|title=Duque impressed by Marikina COVID-19 testing facility: 'One of the best I've seen'|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/734534/duque-impressed-by-marikina-covid-19-testing-facility-one-of-the-best-i-ve-seen/story/ |accessdate=April 18, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=April 17, 2020}}</ref> Muntinlupa plans to set up a testing site at the Ospital ng Muntinlupa also subject to DOH's approval.<ref name=\"muntinlupatesting\"/>\n\n====Testing rates====\n\nAs of April 17, the Philippines has conducted a total of 56,048 tests, including repeat tests, and have tested over 49,613 individuals.<ref name=\"COVID-19 tracker\" />\n\nEarlier, on March 9, 2020, a total of 2,000 tests has been conducted at a rate of 200 to 250 people accommodated by tests per day.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Magtulis |first1=Prinz |title=With only 250 people tested a day, Philippine health sector appears ill-prepared for COVID-19 |url=https://www.philstar.com/business/2020/03/09/1999444/only-250-people-tested-day-philippine-health-sector-appears-ill-prepared-covid-19 |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> The testing capacity of the Philippine government has been expanded by late March 2020. As of March 23, the RITM alone can test 600 people per day, other laboratories except for the facility of San Lazaro Hospital can do 100 tests, while San Lazaro Hospital can do 50 tests per day.<ref name=dohsends100k>{{cite news |title=DOH sends 100,000 test kits to RITM, testing centers nationwide |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/23/Coronavirus-Philippines-test-kits-testing-centers.html |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> There has been a slowing down of the turnout of test results. By March 27, the release of test results conducted at the RITM takes five to seven days due to backlog, but the Institute is committed to reducing the turnaround back to two to three days.<ref>{{cite news |title=COVID-19 test results from RITM out in 5 to 7 days, but not for long, DOH says |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/27/COVID-19-test-results-from-RITM-out-in-5-to-7-days,-but-not-for-long,-DOH-says.html |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 27, 2020}}</ref> The DOH announced that the country will conduct targeted mass testing on April 14, which will be administered strictly for susceptible, probable, and high-risk patients, such as health workers, expectant mothers, and patients with other medical conditions. By April, targeted mass testing is now possible in the Philippines given the improving capacity of the country's accredited laboratories.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Peralta |first1=Janine |title='Mass testing' for suspected COVID-19 cases, high-risk patients only |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/4/4/mass-testing-for-puis-pums-high-risk-patients.html |accessdate=April 5, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMass testing has been conducted elsewhere in the country. The first localized targeted mass testing began in [[Valenzuela, Metro Manila|Valenzuela]] on April 11.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cerrudo |first1=Aileen |title=Valenzuela City to begin mass testing for COVID-19 on April 11 |url=https://untvweb.com/news/valenzuela-city-to-begin-mass-testing-for-covid-19-on-april-11/ |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=UNTV |date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> It was followed by the [[Manila|City of Manila]], [[Quezon City]], [[Muntinlupa]] and the [[Cavite|Cavite Province]] on April 14.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Crisostomo |first1=Shiela |title=COVID mass testing begins in Metro Manila today |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/04/14/2007170/covid-mass-testing-begins-metro-manila-today |accessdate=April 14, 2020 |work=[[Philippine Star|PhilStar Global]] |website= |date=April 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ramos |first1=Mariejo S. |last2=Valenzuela |first2=Nikka G. |title=Mass testing in Metro Manila under way |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1257199/mass-testing-in-metro-under-way |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |work=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer|Inquirer.net]] |date=April 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/04/14/muntinlupa-starts-covid-19-mass-testing-of-puis/?__cf_chl_jschl_tk__=d348ec7394fd9f29cf3961870fa281919cad3616-1587261452-0-AWGhh7XLoHp1yAJOtVV61XDixfeQlptrL1onF0fylXthtS4dfSny-zMsSjCa_X0Iiimj9y0gAMhZZsdLb1PKe7An8Q3323XbEGhlO7TvHvk_rTlBjswpxtpJMueStIIM_3UeGh7Disw6cOeu73ppElI7h1WZbuthRBUockPHZ8q0Ji5nwNb0xyxKTmux6RE6RlEZcqJXCSDIJfb8hAxdHLivsLpV7nTpZgNl5iz8Hi5TDB_JTQy5OiSyossxrPrSFHH7oDmZixe2YTPxeTlun3ZO5xEqnaQbPghaZgXewzm9f1XDZfl7NrrWQwvUJqbVMdT6rD6Lgjj-LkypaRpdfZex_jeAs89U_juljOr2oQDI |title=Muntinlupa starts COVID-19 mass testing of PUIs |publisher=[[Manila Bulletin]] |last1=Hicap |first1=Jonathan |date=April 14, 2020 |accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Cavite opens COVID-19 testing center, starts mass testing |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/4/14/cavite-testing-center-mass-testing-covid-19.html |accessdate=April 19, 2020 |work=[[CNN Philippines]] |date=April 14, 2020}}</ref> It will be followed by [[Makati]] on April 30.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ong |first1=Ghio |title=Makati eyes free COVID-19 mass testing |url=https://www.philstar.com/nation/2020/04/17/2007815/makati-eyes-free-covid-19-mass-testing |accessdate=April 19, 2020 |work=[[Philippine Star|PhilStar Global]] |date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Testing kits ====\nA testing kit for the virus was announced on February 4 to have been developed by the UP-NIH.<ref>{{cite news |title=UP develops test kit for novel coronavirus |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/2/5/UP-National-Institutes-of-Health-develops-test-kit-coronavirus.html |accessdate=February 5, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=February 5, 2020}}</ref> The kit was developed two weeks before the announcement and was subject to evaluation by the DOH.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Baron |first1=Gabriela |title=University of the Philippines National Institute of Health |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/02/05/up-develops-test-kit-for-ncov/ |accessdate=February 10, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=February 5, 2020}}</ref> The equipment is a [[polymerase chain reaction]] testing kit and is to be produced by Manila HealthTek. The [[Food and Drug Administration (Philippines)|Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) gave the product a certificate of exemption on March 9 allowing it to be used under field validation until the testing kit receives validation from the [[World Health Organization]]. The testing kit is reportedly six times cheaper than its foreign counterparts.<ref name=\"dostfundedfda\">{{cite news |last1=Resurreccion |first1=Lyn |title=DOST-funded COVID test kit project clears FDA |url=https://businessmirror.com.ph/2020/03/11/dost-funded-covid-test-kit-project-clears-fda/ |accessdate=March 11, 2020 |work=BusinessMirror |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"cheaper\">{{cite news |title=UP-developed COVID-19 testing kit is 6 times cheaper than foreign counterparts |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/lifestyle/healthandwellness/729120/up-developed-covid-19-testing-kit-is-6-times-cheaper-than-foreign-counterparts/story/ |accessdate=March 11, 2020 |work=GMA News |date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe RITM on February 26, reportedly is purchasing 19,000 testing kits from a source abroad.<ref name=\"ritm19000\">{{cite news |last1=Marquez |first1=Consuelo |title=RITM to buy 19,000 kits to test repatriates in New Clark City \u2013 DOH |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1233749/ritm-to-buy-19000-kits-to-test-repatriates-in-new-clark-city-doh |accessdate=March 2, 2020 |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref> The number of testing kits by March 9 is around 2,000 from a high of 4,500 at an unspecified date. The government experienced a shortage of testing kits and has prioritized individuals exhibiting symptoms for testing.<ref>{{cite news |title=Virus Outbreak: Philippines' lack of test kits a concern |url=http://taipeitimes.com/News/world/archives/2020/03/11/2003732492 |accessdate=March 11, 2020 |work=Taipei Times |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe DOH announced on March 23, that it has distributed 100,000 testing kits to five operational testing facilities as well as the [[Lung Center of the Philippines]] in Quezon City.<ref name=dohsends100k/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"margin:auto; text-align:center; font-size:90%; width:auto;\"\n|+ [[Food and Drug Administration (Philippines)|Food and Drug Administration]]-approved COVID-19 test kits for commercial use (laboratory use) as of March 25, 2020<ref>{{cite web |title=List of Approved COVID-19 Test Kits for Commercial Use |url=https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1Dk8KjbCzk8g92HydWDRvg8K-ATp7gBez |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=Food and Drug Administration |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" | Product\n! scope=\"col\" | Manufacturer\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Nucleic acid detection kit for 2019 ncov\n| Shanghai GenoeDx Biotech (China)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Novel coronavirus 2019-ncov nucleic acid detection kit (Fluorescence PCR method)\n| Beijing Applied Biological (China)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | AllplexTM 2019-nCoV Assay\n| Seegene (South Korea)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Solgent DiaPlexQ Novel Coronavirus (2019-nCoV) Detection Kit\n| Solgent (South Korea)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Standard M nCoV Real-time Detection Kit\n| SD Biosensor (South Korea)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | A Star Fortitude Kit 2.0 (COVID-19 Real-Time RT-PCR TEST)\n| Accelerate Technologies (Singapore)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Tib Molbiol Lightmix Modular Wuhan CoV RdRP-GENE\n| rowspan=2| Tib Molbiol Syntheselabor (Germany)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Tib Molbiol Lightmix Modular SARS and Wuhan COV E-GENE\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Genesig Real-Time PCR Coronavirus (COVID-19) CE IVD Kit\n| [[Primerdesign]] (United Kingdom)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | BDDS - CerTest - SARS-CoV2 BD MAX assay (Severe Acute Syndrome-Associated Coronavirus IVDs [CT772])\n| Certest Biotech (Spain)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Biofire COVID-19 Test\n| Biofire Defense (United States)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2019-nCov Nucleic Acid-based Diagnostic Reagent Kit (Fluorescent PCR)\n| Sansure Biotech (China)\n|}\n\n====Testing criteria====\n<!---Please expand to document changes to the testing triage--->\n{{more information|2020 Philippine coronavirus testing controversy}}\n{{expand section|1=Department of Health's testing criteria|date=March 2020}}\n\nEarly COVID-19 testing in the Philippines was only limited to persons with travel history to countries with cases of local transmission and those with exposure to the individuals confirmed to have COVID-19. The testing protocols were revised sometime in mid-March 2020 to give priority to the testing of any individual with severe symptoms as well as to the elderly, pregnant and [[Immunocompromisation|immunocompromised]] persons with at least mild symptoms.<ref name=mayagainrevise>{{cite news |title=DOH may again revise COVID-19 testing protocols |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/24/doh-eyes-revision-coronavirus-testing-protocols.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn late March, some politicians and their relatives were reportedly tested for the virus despite not showing any symptoms, causing public backlash<!---Unhide once DOH guidelines change to allow testing of asymptomatic individuals at that time---> amidst a shortage of testing kits since it was against DOH guidelines to test asymptomatic individuals.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Calleja|first1=Joseph Peter|url=https://www.ucanews.com/news/covid-19-testing-for-vips-sparks-outrage-in-philippines/87517|title=Covid-19 testing for VIPs sparks outrage in Philippines|work=UCA News|accessdate=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The DOH responded to the public criticism by clarifying that, while there is \"no policy for VIP treatment\" with regard to testing for COVID-19 and that \"all specimens are being processed on a first-in, first-out basis,\" it \"extends courtesy\" to front line government officials, specifically those involved in national security and public health.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sabillo |first1=Kristine |title=DOH denies expedited COVID-19 testing for VIPs, only extends 'courtesy' to some officials |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/23/20/doh-denies-expedited-covid-19-testing-for-vips-only-extends-courtesy-to-some-officials |accessdate=April 6, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Some senators who were tested claim that they used an \"instant\" test kit not accredited by the DOH.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tan |first1=Lara |title=Health Dept. gives COVID-19 testing 'courtesy' to officials involved in nat'l security, public health |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/23/Senator-Tito-Sotto-coronavirus-COVID-19-test.html?fbclid=IwAR3Nm7FnDwFbJUL2Mu5F45Qst06ht3N_vUR7YTz9HfyzYQ2qeKhFKYcLAWU |accessdate=April 6, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, the DOH announced that it is planning to revise its COVID-19 testing guidelines again to allow people with mild symptoms to get tested due to increased testing capability and the stockpile of testing kits.<ref name=mayagainrevise/>\n\n== Impact ==\n{{further|Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n=== Economy ===\n{{see also|2020 stock market crash|Coronavirus recession}}\n[[File:Manila Supermarket Vendors with Acetate Full Face Shields COVID-19 2.jpg|thumb|A public market vendor in [[Manila]] wearing a [[cellulose acetate]] [[face shield]], March 25]]\nOn March 9, 2020, the [[Philippine Stock Exchange]] (PSE) index lost 457.77 points or 6.76%, [[Black Monday (2020)|its steepest decline]] since the [[financial crisis of 2007\u201308]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dumlao-Abadilla |first1=Doris |title=PH stocks see worst bloodbath in 12 years |url=https://business.inquirer.net/292148/ph-stocks-see-worst-bloodbath-in-12-years |accessdate=March 11, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> The following day, shares [[Stock market crash|plunged]] by 6.23% to {{Philippine peso|5,957.35|link=yes}} (US$117.54), settling below the 6,000 level benchmark and entering the [[bear market]] territory. The mining and oil industries were the most affected with a 9.05% drop, followed by [[Holding company|holding companies]] with a 6.93% drop. The PSE's [[trading curb|circuit breaker mechanism]] was invoked for the second time since the measure's introduction in 2008 halting trade for 15 minutes.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lopez |first1=Melissa |title=Local stocks plunge below 6,000 mark as COVID-19 now called a pandemic |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/business/2020/3/12/Local-stocks-below-6000-coronavirus.html?fbclid=IwAR1yoqJJUWZgSOZNCpG2kvcO1WZ-PWG6m6azJm-8eSEevdx1awNR3u9XilA |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[National Economic and Development Authority]] (NEDA) revised its economic growth outlook for the Philippines in 2020 from a 6.5% to 7.5% [[gross domestic product]] (GDP) growth registered in late 2019 to a 5.5% to 6.5% GDP growth, following the pandemic. The NEDA cited the decline in service exports, especially tourism. [[Moody's Analytics]] also reduced its GDP growth outlook for the country, from 5.9% in 2019 to 4.9% following the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Noble |first1=Luz Wendy |title=Economic growth may fall below 5% this year |url=https://www.bworldonline.com/economic-growth-may-fall-below-5-this-year/ |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |work=BusinessWorld |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe filing of income tax returns was extended to May 15 from April 15 by the [[Bureau of Internal Revenue (Philippines)|Bureau of Internal Revenue]].<ref>{{cite news |title=BIR moves tax filing deadline to May 15 due to COVID-19 |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/03/19/20/bir-moves-tax-filing-deadline-to-may-15-due-to-covid-19 |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Bangko Sentral ng Pilipinas]] (BSP) Governor [[Benjamin Diokno]] and NEDA Director-General [[Ernesto Pernia]] forecast that the [[Economy of the Philippines|Philippine economy]] would likely enter a [[recession]] in 2020 due to the effect of the pandemic. Diokno stated that, although the first quarter is likely to grow by 3% since the [[2020 Luzon enhanced community quarantine|Luzon-wide enhanced community quarantine]] only took effect near the end of the quarter, the second and third quarters would likely experience contractions in economic growth. However, the BSP forecasts that the [[inflation]] rate may lower to 2.4% in March from 2.6% in February and 2.9% in January due to a decrease in the [[price of oil]] from $85 to $30 per barrel as a result of the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Noble |first1=Luz Wendy |last2=Laforga |first2=Beatrice |title=PHL may go into recession \u2014 Diokno |url=https://www.bworldonline.com/phl-may-go-into-recession-diokno/ |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=BusinessWorld |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Employment ====\nThe [[Trade Union Congress of the Philippines]] estimates that around 7,000 people may lose jobs within the first half of 2020 due to the pandemic. This followed [[Philippine Airlines]]' decision to lay off 300 of its workers due to losses caused by the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |title=Labor group warns 7,000 workers may lose jobs due to coronavirus pandemic |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/1/coronavirus-job-losses-layoffs.html |accessdate=March 2, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 1, 2020}}</ref> [[Philippines AirAsia]] also dropped its plan to debut in the PSE within 2020 and decided to focus on expanding its domestic operations after a government ban on China and South Korea which threatened 30% of its revenue.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Camus |first1=Miguel |title=COVID-19 crisis puts AirAsia IPO plan on hold |url=https://business.inquirer.net/291622/covid-19-crisis-puts-airasia-ipo-plan-on-hold |accessdate=March 2, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 2, 2020}}</ref> Employees of [[Cebu Pacific]], the country's largest airline, compromised on a pay cut amounting to 10% to avoid layoffs.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cebu Pacific managers take pay cut to avoid COVID 19 layoffs |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/03/09/20/cebu-pacific-managers-take-pay-cut-to-avoid-covid-19-layoffs |accessdate=March 9, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> However, Cebu Pacific eventually laid off over 150 cabin crew personnel near the end of the first quarter as more countries and provinces in the Philippines implemented travel restrictions, affecting its flights.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lopez |first1=Melissa |title=Cebu Pacific lays off over 150 cabin crew amid COVID-19 travel restrictions |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/business/2020/3/16/Cebu-Pacific-layoffs.html?fbclid=IwAR2Hra5Ke9DzEK9wWwTnob02MuHAzj-qQAyr8hJh8eol3cuWJlhCifInISw |accessdate=March 29, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEconomists from the [[Ateneo de Manila University]] estimate that 57% of the country's workforce may be displaced within the end of the first quarter of 2020. It comprises around 15 million workers in Luzon that were laid off due to the enhanced community quarantine, around four million of whom are based in Metro Manila, as well as an estimated 4.3 million workers in [[Visayas]] and another 4.3 million in [[Mindanao]] that were laid off due to quarantine restrictions.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Valencia |first1=Czeriza |title=Luzon-wide ECQ displaced 15 million workers, Ateneo study shows |url=https://www.philstar.com/business/2020/04/05/2005488/luzon-wide-ecq-displaced-15-million-workers-ateneo-study-shows |accessdate=April 6, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Entertainment and media ====\n{{further|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on television}}\nThe DOH issued an advisory for the cancellation of large public events and mass gatherings, such as concerts, until further notice to minimize the risk of spreading the disease.<ref>{{cite web |title=Health Department warns Filipinos not to attend concerts, other public events to avoid coronavirus infection |url=https://coconuts.co/manila/news/health-department-warns-filipinos-not-to-attend-concerts-other-public-events-to-avoid-coronavirus-infection/ |website=Coconuts Manila |accessdate=March 8, 2020 |date=February 10, 2020}}</ref> This prompted several local and international artists to either cancel or postpone their scheduled concerts and fan meets.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ruiz|first=Marah |display-authors=etal|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/entertainment/showbiznews/news/12277/look-cancelled-and-postponed-concerts-shows-and-meet-and-greets-due-to-the-covid-19-scare/photo/155635/foo-fighters|title=UPDATED: Cancelled and Postponed Concerts, Shows and Meet and Greets Due to the COVID-19 Scare|date=March 27, 2020|work=GMA News Online|access-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/entertainment/2020/2/6/international-artist-events-Philippines-2020-canceled.html|title=LIST: PH events canceled due to novel coronavirus threat|date=February 6, 2020|work=CNN Philippines|access-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spot.ph/entertainment/movies-music-tv/81247/cancelled-postponed-concerts-manila-2020-a4373-20200304|title=Heads Up: These 2020 Concerts in Manila Have Been Canceled|last1=Rosales|first1=Clara|date=March 5, 2020|website=Spot.ph|accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nLocal television networks temporarily stopped admitting [[Studio audience|live audiences]] for their television shows, including variety shows ''[[Eat Bulaga!]]'' on [[GMA Network]] as well as ''[[It's Showtime (TV program)|It's Showtime]]'' and ''[[ASAP (TV program)|ASAP]]'' on [[ABS-CBN (TV network)|ABS-CBN]].<ref>{{cite news |title=No studio audience for 'It's Showtime,' 'ASAP,' to prevent coronavirus spread |url=https://www.rappler.com/entertainment/news/253932-no-live-studio-audience-its-showtime-asap-prevent-coronavirus-spread |accessdate=March 10, 2020 |work=Rappler |date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> On March 13, both ABS-CBN and GMA announced that they would suspend productions on their [[Philippine television drama|drama shows]] as well as other entertainment programs by March 15, replacing affected programs with reruns of previous series or extended newscast runs.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Anarcon |first1=James Patrick |title=ABS-CBN announces temporary lineup of primetime programs as teleseryes go on taping break |url=https://www.pep.ph/guide/tv/150068/abs-cbn-temporary-lineup-of-primetime-programs-a724-20200314?ref=home_featured_1 |website=Philippine Entertainment Portal |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Anarcon |first1=James Patrick |title=GMA-7 suspends production of teleseryes, entertainment shows to combat spread of COVID-19 |url=https://www.pep.ph/guide/tv/150072/gma-7-suspends-production-teleseryes-entertainment-shows-covid-19-a724-20200314?ref=home_featured_2 |website=Philippine Entertainment Portal |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 18, [[CNN Philippines]] was forced to go off air after an employee working at the Worldwide Corporate Center in [[Mandaluyong]], where the network's headquarters is situated, was confirmed to be positive with COVID-19. CNN Philippines continued its coverage via its online platforms and returned on air on March 23.<ref>{{cite news |title=CNN Philippines temporarily goes off air as building undergoes disinfection |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/18/CNN-Philippines-Worldwide-Corporate-Center-coronavirus-COVID-19-case.html |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBroadcast radio companies such as the [[Manila Broadcasting Company]], [[Aliw Broadcasting Corporation]], [[Radio Mindanao Network]], [[Bombo Radyo Philippines]], and broadcast members of the [[Kapisanan ng mga Brodkaster ng Pilipinas]] are also implementing their operations during the quarantine period; either shortening their broadcast hours and/or temporary suspension of regular programming \"in favor of special broadcasts\". On April 1, [[DZMM-AM|DZMM]] and its [[DZMM TeleRadyo|television counterpart]] suspended their regular programming after their entire personnel must undergo 14-day self-quarantine following their exposure to 2 PUIs; its programming was temporarily replaced with the hookup from the [[ABS-CBN News Channel]] until further notice.<ref>{{cite news |title=DZMM temporarily halts operations as personnel go on quarantine |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/4/2/dzmm-suspends-operations-quarantine-covid-19.html |accessdate=April 3, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Food service and supply ====\n{{further|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the food industry}}\n\nFollowing directives from the Philippine government, several fast food and restaurant chains suspended dine-in services and restricted operations to [[take-out]] and [[Food delivery|delivery]]. Following the Luzon-wide enhanced community quarantine, [[online food ordering]] services such as [[Grab (company)|GrabFood]] and [[Foodpanda]] temporarily halted but eventually resumed operations in Luzon during the quarantine period.<ref>{{cite news |title=Where to Order Food for Take Out and Delivery Amidst Enhanced Community Quarantine |url=https://primer.com.ph/blog/2020/03/19/where-to-order-food-for-take-out-and-delivery-amidst-enhanced-community-quarantine/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Philippine Primer |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeveral restaurants and coffee shops across the country offered free food and beverages to front line professionals involved in the pandemic, especially health care workers.<ref>{{cite news |title=These businesses are giving free stuff to health workers amid the COVID-19 threat |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/lifestyle/food/729699/these-businesses-are-giving-free-stuff-to-health-workers-amid-the-covid-19-threat/story/ |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Shops offer free coffee, food to healthcare workers amid coronavirus |url=https://www.rappler.com/move-ph/254516-shops-offer-free-food-health-workers-coronavirus |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |work=Rappler |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFood production and distribution slowed down during the pandemic, especially in Luzon, primarily due to the lack of financial assistance and inaccessibility of transportation resulting from community quarantine measures being implemented across numerous local governments. The delivery of fresh vegetables from the province of [[Benguet]], which supplies the country with over 80 percent of the country's highland vegetable requirements, was halted due to the implementation of an \"extreme enhanced\" community quarantine in [[La Trinidad, Benguet|La Trinidad]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Visaya |first1=Villamor Jr. |last2=Sotelo |first2=Yolanda |last3=Quitasol |first3=Kimberlie |last4=Lapniten |first4=Karlston |last5=Ramos |first5=Marlon |last6=Yap |first6=DJ |title=Food shortage looms amid quarantine |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1250716/food-shortage-looms-amid-quarantine |accessdate=April 4, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> Local government officials advised local [[Rice production in the Philippines|rice farmers]] to sell their harvests to them, assuring them that they would help distribute it to their respective communities amid the border restrictions.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Louis |first1=Jillian |title=Virus sparks food shortage in the Philippines |url=https://theaseanpost.com/article/virus-sparks-food-shortage-philippines |accessdate=April 4, 2020 |work=The ASEAN Post |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, [[Vietnam]] announced that it would reduce [[Rice production in Vietnam|its production]] and exportation of rice due to [[food security]] amid the pandemic. The Philippines, the largest importer of rice in the world, imports 25% of its rice from Vietnam. Agriculture Secretary [[William Dar]] assured that there would be \"no shortage of the staple during the duration of the enhanced community quarantine and beyond\" as \"harvest [is] already coming in.\" Dar also stated the [[Department of Agriculture (Philippines)|Department of Agriculture]]'s plans to initiate early planting in the [[Cagayan Valley]] and [[Central Luzon]], two of the largest [[Rice production in the Philippines|rice producers in the country]], ahead of the third quarter of 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Simeon |first1=Louise Maureen |title=Philippines rice inventory in peril as Vietnam reduces exports |url=https://www.philstar.com/business/2020/03/27/2003632/philippines-rice-inventory-peril-vietnam-reduces-exports |accessdate=April 4, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFish canneries in [[Zamboanga City]] announced that it would reduce the production of canned fish in the Philippines by 50\u201360% due to difficulties encountered following the implementation of a city-wide lockdown. Zamboanga City supplies 85% of [[canned fish]] in the country. The Industrial Group of Zamboanga reported that most of its workers experienced difficulties in reporting to work, despite the company offering free shuttle services, due to the wide presence of checkpoints across ''barangays''. Fish canneries in the city also had to reduce outputs due to the deliverers of fresh fish from [[Zamboanga Sibugay]] and [[Zamboanga del Norte]] experiencing difficulties in entering the city, as visitors are required to undergo a 14-day quarantine. This prompted most canneries to discourage  deliveries.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Alipala |first1=Julie |title=Fish canneries cut output by 50-60% |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1250676/fish-canneries-cut-output-by-50-60-percent |accessdate=April 4, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Medical supply ====\n{{further|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic related shortages}}\n\n[[File:Philippines Coronavirus 01.jpg|thumb|Cloth face masks draw the attention of customers at the Mu\u00f1oz Market in [[Quezon City]] due to the limited supply and higher price of [[surgical mask]]s.]]\nA shortage of medical masks was reported in various parts of the country due to concerns over the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |title=Filipinos on surgical mask frenzy mode as PH confirms first novel coronavirus case |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/1/31/filipinos-face-mask-frenzy-novel-coronavirus.html |accessdate=February 7, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=January 31, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131121952/https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/1/31/filipinos-face-mask-frenzy-novel-coronavirus.html |archive-date=January 31, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lalu |first1=Gabriel Pabico |title=Metro drugstores run out of masks, disinfectants as first nCoV case confirmed |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1222012/metro-drugstores-run-out-of-masks-disinfectants-as-first-coronavirus-case-confirmed |accessdate=February 7, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=January 30, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131134036/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1222012/metro-drugstores-run-out-of-masks-disinfectants-as-first-coronavirus-case-confirmed |archive-date=January 31, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> RITM director Celia Carlos urged the public against hoarding masks to ensure ample supply for medical workers directly dealing with patients suspected or confirmed to have COVID-19 infection.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Romero |first1=Alexis |title=Public urged not to hoard face masks needed by frontline health workers battling nCoV |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/02/03/1990089/public-urged-not-hoard-face-masks-needed-frontline-health-workers-battling-ncov |accessdate=February 7, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=February 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204150404/https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/02/03/1990089/public-urged-not-hoard-face-masks-needed-frontline-health-workers-battling-ncov |archive-date=February 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Department of Trade and Industry (Philippines)|Department of Trade and Industry]] (DTI), in cooperation with the [[Philippine National Police]], are acting against reports of traders hoarding face masks and selling said item at an overpriced rate.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Caliwan |first1=Christopher Lloyd |title=PNP to help vs. face masks hoarding |url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1092745 |accessdate=February 7, 2020 |agency=Philippine News Agency |date=February 3, 2020}}</ref> The DTI has also directed its Philippine International Trading Corp. to import 5 million masks from overseas. Medtecs International Corp. Ltd., the sole manufacturer of medical mask in the country, has committed to supply the government through the DTI.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Desiderio |first1=Louella |title=DTI orders imports of masks as local supply tightens |url=https://www.philstar.com/business/2020/02/04/1990114/dti-orders-imports-masks-local-supply-tightens |accessdate=February 7, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=February 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDoctors in the Philippines have deplored the shortages in [[personal protective equipment]] (PPE) amid the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Magsino |first1=Dona |title=PMA exec: No shortage of doctors in Philippines but PPEs lacking amid COVID-19 emergency |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/731172/pma-exec-no-shortage-of-doctors-in-philippines-but-ppes-lacking-amid-covid-19-emergency/story/ |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The office of Vice President [[Leni Robredo]] raised about {{Philippine peso|28.8 million}} ($564,551) to purchase 64,367 sets of PPE and donate it to front line health professionals across the country. The first batch consisted of 7,350 PPEs that were donated to 490 professionals in eight hospitals in Manila and Quezon City with COVID-19 cases.<ref>{{cite news |title=Robredo's office collects P17.3 million for coronavirus protective gear |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/17/20/robredos-office-collects-p173-million-for-coronavirus-protective-gear |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> By March 24, Robredo's office had delivered 23,475 sets of PPE to 62 medical facilities and communities across [[Metro Manila]], [[La Union]], and [[Quezon]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Antonio |first1=Raymund |title=62 more hospitals, medical centers get PPEs from office of the VP |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/25/62-more-hospitals-medical-centers-get-ppes-from-office-of-the-vp/ |accessdate=March 28, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> Robredo also partnered with fashion designer [[Mich Dulce]] to mass-produce PPEs that utilize locally sourced [[Taffeta]] fabric; the Vice President pledged to help donate the PPEs to medical professionals across the country.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Garcia |first1=Maria Angelica |title=OVP, fashion designer partners to start mass production of PPEs |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/731807/ovp-fashion-designer-partners-to-start-mass-production-of-ppes/story/ |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Retail ====\n[[File:NO FACE MASK, NO ENTRY.jpg|thumb|A public market in [[Angono]], [[Rizal]] implements a \"no face mask, no entry\" policy, March 24]]\nAccording to the Philippine Retailers Association, the \"total retail environment\" saw a decline of 30\u201350%. [[SM Investments]], the country's largest retailer, saw a decline of 10\u201320% in domestic sales.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Van |first1=Tong |title=Philippine retailers experiencing coronavirus-related sales slump |url=https://insideretail.asia/2020/02/20/philippine-retailers-experiencing-coronavirus-related-sales-slump/ |accessdate=February 20, 2020 |work=Inside Retail Asia |date=February 20, 2020}}</ref> Despite the decline, most retail stores that provide essential services, including supermarkets, convenience stores, hardware stores, and pharmacies, remained open across the country to sustain consumers while other establishments at malls closed down.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Desiderio |first1=Louella |last2=Gonzales |first2=Iris |last3=Cabrera |first3=Romina |title=Several malls close; supermarkets, banks, pharmacies open |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/16/2001272/several-malls-close-supermarkets-banks-pharmacies-open |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> Such retail stores, however, imposed strict [[social distancing]] measures with some supermarkets only allowing 50 customers inside at a time and placing stickers on the floor to indicate that customers must stand one meter apart from each other. Stores were also regularly disinfected and customers were required to undergo a temperature check before entering.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Garcia |first1=Maria Angelica |title=Supermarkets impose social distancing to curb COVID-19 |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/money/companies/730137/supermarkets-impose-social-distancing-to-curb-covid-19/story/ |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> In the [[Greater Manila Area]], several [[online grocer]]s continued to operate, but with limited delivery slots.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bigtas |first1=Jannielyn Ann |title=Online groceries to check out when you can't leave your house |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/lifestyle/shoppingandfashion/729842/online-groceries-to-check-out-when-you-can-t-leave-your-house/story/ |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> [[Panic buying]] and [[Hoarding (economics)|hoarding]] became rampant across the country, especially with essential goods such as food and sanitation products.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Robles |first1=Raissa |title=Coronavirus: panic buying in Manila, some flee to countryside as first Filipino fatality confirmed and cases rise to 49 |url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3074745/philippines-panic-buying-erupts-metro-manila-after |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |work=South China Morning Post |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The Philippine Amalgamated Supermarkets Association reported that the purchases of masks, alcohol, and other personal hygiene products in supermarkets across the country had already surged, urging the public against panic buying.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hilotin |first1=Jay |title=Panic buying, price gouging reported in Manila over coronavirus |url=https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/philippines/panic-buying-price-gouging-reported-in-manila-over-coronavirus-1.1583946282411 |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |work=Gulf News |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> \n\nEconomic think tank [[Fitch Ratings|Fitch Solutions]] forecasts that the consumer and retail sector, especially non-essential businesses, would be one of the hardest-hit sectors in the Philippines as it loses [[sales revenue]] for an entire month due to the Luzon enhanced community quarantine (Luzon accounts for 73% of the country's GDP). Fitch Solutions forecasts the [[household final consumption expenditure]] for the country in 2020 to expand by 6.7% year-over-year, which was adjusted from a \"pre-coronavirus projection\" for 2020 of 7% growth year-over-year.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gonzales |first1=Cathrine |title=Consumer and retail sector to bear the brunt of month-long ECQ, says think tank |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1252102/consumer-and-retail-sector-to-bear-the-brunt-of-month-long-ecq-according-to-think-tank |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Sports ====\n{{further|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\n[[File:Ninoy Aquino Stadium COVID-19 quarantine.jpg|thumb|Several sports facilities including the [[Ninoy Aquino Stadium]] of the [[Rizal Memorial Sports Complex]] were converted into temporary quarantine facilities for COVID-19 patients.]]\nSeveral ongoing sports leagues in the Philippines, such as the [[2019\u201320 ABL season|ASEAN Basketball League]], [[2019\u201320 MPBL season|Maharlika Pilipinas Basketball League]], [[2020 PBA season|Philippine Basketball Association]], [[National Basketball League (Philippines)|National Basketball League]], [[2020 Philippines Football League|Philippines Football League]],<ref>{{cite web |title=PFF And PFL Statement \u2013 Postponement Of Philippines Football League Season 2020 |url=http://pff.org.ph/2020/03/13/pff-and-pfl-statement-postponement-of-philippines-football-league-season-2020/ |publisher=Philippine Football Federation |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> [[2020 PSL season|Philippine Super Liga]], were suspended.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cabildo |first1=Leigh Nald |title=LIST: Philippine leagues suspended amid coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.rappler.com/sports/by-sport/other-sports/254350-list-philippine-leagues-suspended-coronavirus-outbreak?utm_medium=Social&utm_source=Twitter#Echobox=1584069791 |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=Rappler |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> Upcoming sporting competitions hosted by the country, specifically the [[2020 ASEAN Para Games]], the [[2020 Palarong Pambansa]] in [[Marikina]], and the [[Philippine National Games]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ayalin |first1=Adrian |title=Palarong Pambansa postponed due to COVID-19 threat |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/sports/03/09/20/palarong-pambansa-postponed-due-to-covid-19-threat |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> were postponed.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Villar |first1=Joey |title=NCAA succumbs to coronavirus scare, postpones all high school games |url=https://www.philstar.com/sports/2020/02/07/1991189/ncaa-succumbs-coronavirus-scare-postpones-all-high-school-games |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=February 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\nRegional qualification games involving Philippine national teams were likewise postponed; the [[2021 FIBA Asia Cup qualification]] home match of the [[Philippines men's national basketball team|Philippine men's national basketball team]] against [[Thailand national basketball team|Thailand]] scheduled for February 20 at the [[Smart Araneta Coliseum]] was rescheduled,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Terrado |first1=Jonas |title=FIBA officially postpones Gilas Pilipinas home match vs Thailand due to COVID-19 |url=https://sports.mb.com.ph/2020/02/14/fiba-officially-postpones-gilas-pilipinas-home-match-vs-thailand-due-to-coronavirus/ |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=February 14, 2020}}</ref> while [[FIFA]] and the [[Asian Football Confederation]] suspended the [[Philippines national football team|Philippine national football team]]'s three remaining matches in the [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Second Round|second round]] of [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (AFC)|qualification]] for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sevilla |first1=Jeremiah |title=Azkals' WC qualifying games canceled |url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/03/11/sports/football-times/azkals-wc-qualifying-games-canceled/702040/ |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=The Manila Times |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome games, however, pushed through but were played [[Behind closed doors (sport)|behind closed doors]] to prevent the spread of the virus amongst the audience. Before the suspension of the Philippine Super Liga, three matches in the [[2020 PSL Grand Prix Conference|PSL Grand Prix Conference]] on March 10 were played at an empty [[Filoil Flying V Centre]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Agcaoili |first1=Lance |title=PSL to hold games in empty arenas amid growing COVID-19 threat |url=https://www.spin.ph/volleyball/super-liga/psl-to-hold-games-in-empty-arenas-amid-growing-covid-19-threat-a2522-20200309 |website=Spin.ph |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> On March 11, local football team [[Ceres\u2013Negros F.C.]] played their [[2020 AFC Cup]] home match against [[Bali United F.C.]] behind closed doors at the [[Rizal Memorial Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tupas |first1=Cedelf |title=Ceres-Negros to play AFC Cup match vs Bali United in empty stadium |url=https://sports.inquirer.net/389000/ceres-negros-to-play-afc-cup-match-vs-bali-united-in-empty-stadium |accessdate=March 10, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nCancelled sports leagues and tournaments in the Philippines due to COVID-19 pandemic:\n* [[2020 ASEAN Para Games|ASEAN Para Games]] (March 20\u201328) \u2013 a [[Multi-sport event|multi-sport]] for differently-abled ASEAN athletes. This would be the second postponement of the games; initially postponed to March due to non-COVID-19 related concerns.\n* [[2020 Palarong Pambansa|Palarong Pambansa]] (May 1\u20139) \u2013 a national [[Multi-sport event|multi-sport]] event; postponed.\n* [[2020 Philippines Football League|Philippines Football League]] (opening on March 21) \u2013 tentatively delayed starting date to April 18.\n* [[2020 PBA Philippine Cup|PBA Philippine Cup]] (opening on March 8) \u2013 Had already progressed but suspended on March 10.<ref name=\"pbateams\">{{cite news |last1=Dalupang |first1=Denison Rey |title=PBA: Teams can't hold practices, scrimmages |url=https://sports.inquirer.net/389302/pba-teams-cant-hold-practices-scrimmages |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Tourism ====\n{{see also|List of events affected by the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:Philippine Airlines grounded planes COVID19.jpg|thumb|right|[[Philippine Airlines]] aircraft grounded at the [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport]] due to the Luzon enhanced community quarantine, March 25]]\nThe NEDA during a House of Representative committee hearing said that the coronavirus pandemic would incur a {{Philippine peso|22.7 billion}} ($448 million) monthly loss of tourism revenue and the impact of the pandemic could last around five to six months based from past experiences from the [[SARS outbreak|SARS]], [[2009 flu pandemic|H1N1]], and the [[2012 Middle East respiratory syndrome coronavirus outbreak|MERS outbreaks]]. Over 5,200 flights covering two months which was to be serviced by member airlines of the Air-Carriers Association of the Philippines was canceled.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Quismorio |first1=Ellson |title=PH to suffer P22.7-B losses monthly from COVID-19 scare, NEDA tells solons |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/02/12/ph-to-suffer-p22-7-b-losses-monthly-from-covid-19-scare-neda-tells-solons/ |accessdate=February 15, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=February 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[National Museum of the Philippines]] temporarily closed its complex in Manila and all branch museums throughout the country.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rappler.com/life-and-style/arts-and-culture/254436-national-museum-closes-to-public-coronavirus-fears|title=National Museum closes to the public 'until further notice' over coronavirus fears|work=Rappler|language=en|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 13, the National Parks Development Committee also closed [[Rizal Park]] and [[Paco Park]] until further notice while the [[Intramuros Administration]] closed several sites in [[Intramuros]], including [[Fort Santiago]], [[Museo de Intramuros]], and [[Casa Manila]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/13/rizal-park-intramuros-sites-temporarily-closed-amid-covid-19-spread|title=Rizal Park, Intramuros sites temporarily closed amid COVID-19 spread|work=Manila Bulletin News|language=en-US|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Philippine Shopping Festival, a nationwide mall sale event backed by the Department of Tourism originally scheduled on March 1\u201331 was postponed due to the COVID-19 pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |title=Philippines postpones nationwide mall sale amid coronavirus threat |url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/regional/2020/02/29/philippines-postpones-nationwide-mall-sale-amid-coronavirus-threat |accessdate=March 2, 2020 |work=The Star |date=February 29, 2020}}</ref> Several local festivals across the country were also either canceled or postponed due to the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic.\n\n=== Education ===\n{{further|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on education}}\n\n[[File:689Baliuag enhanced community quarantine 47.jpg|thumb|Gates of a public high school in [[Baliuag, Bulacan]] closed due to the suspension of classes.]]\nOn March 9, 2020, President [[Rodrigo Duterte]] suspended classes at all levels in Metro Manila until March 14, in response to the rise in confirmed cases of COVID-19 in the Philippines.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casas |first1=Willie |last2=Araja |first2=Rio |title=Duterte suspends classes in Metro Manila Until March 14 |url=https://manilastandard.net/mobile/article/319288 |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> Before that, [[Navotas]] Mayor [[Toby Tiangco]] had already suspended classes in the city as a preventive measure.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mendoza |first1=Red |title=Navotas suspends classes due to Covid-19 outbreak |url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/03/07/news/latest-stories/navotas-suspends-classes-due-to-covid-19-outbreak/700948/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=The Manila Times |date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> He also appealed to the [[Department of Education (Philippines)|Department of Education]] (DepEd) to pass all Navote\u00f1o students for the remainder of the academic year.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casilao |first1=Joahna Lei |title=Navotas mayor asks DepEd to pass all students; Duque says class suspension not a good idea now |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/728716/navotas-mayor-asks-deped-to-pass-all-students-duque-says-class-suspension-not-a-good-idea-now/story/?just_in |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> Some towns in [[Rizal]], namely [[Cainta]], [[Rodriguez, Rizal|Rodriguez]], [[San Mateo, Rizal|San Mateo]], and [[Taytay, Rizal|Taytay]], also suspended classes following confirmation of at least two cases in the province.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gapayao |first1=Kier Gideon Paolo |title=Prevention measures upped across Rizal Province as COVID-19 cases on the rise |url=https://pia.gov.ph/news/articles/1036051 |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |agency=Philippine Information Agency |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> Classes in Metro Manila were extended until April 14 when President Duterte placed the area under a partial lockdown on March 9. It was superseded on March 16 by the declaration of an enhanced community quarantine covering the wider [[Luzon]] island, which was later extended until April 30.<ref name=\"ECQ\"/> On March 16, the DepEd issued guidelines prohibiting public schools in areas with suspended classes from administering the [[final examination]]s for students and instead compute the final grades of students for the academic year based on \"their current academic standing.\" The DepEd also advised schools in areas without suspension to immediately administer final examinations within that week on a \"staggered basis\" and for teachers and students to observe social distancing measures.<ref>{{cite news |title=DepEd: No more final exams in public schools covered by community quarantine |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/16/DepEd-exams-coronavirus.html |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBefore the announcement of the enhanced community quarantine, the [[University of the Philippines Diliman]] announced on March 12 that it would implement [[Online learning in higher education|online learning]] alternatives for all its classes.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Colcol |first1=Erwin |title=UP Diliman's shift to online classes due to COVID-19 begins on Monday |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/729447/up-diliman-s-shift-to-online-classes-due-to-covid-19-threat-begins-on-monday/story/ |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The [[Commission on Higher Education (Philippines)|Commission on Higher Education]] (CHED) advised other institutions of [[higher education in the Philippines]] in the Philippines to implement [[distance education]] methods of learning for its classes, such as the use of [[educational technology]], to maximize the academic term despite the suspensions;<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hernando-Malipot |first1=Merlina |last2=San Juan |first2=Alexandria |title=Learning in the time of coronavirus |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/11/learning-in-the-time-of-coronavirus/ |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Several other public and private tertiary institutions implemented such arrangements for its classes.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Agoncillo |first1=Jodee |last2=Ramos |first2=Mariejo |last3=Valenzuela |first3=Nikka |title=Metro Manila schools cope by holding online classes |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1242106/metro-manila-schools-cope-by-holding-online-classes |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> However, following the announcement of the enhanced community quarantine in Luzon and other areas, colleges and universities suspended mandatory online classes in consideration of the welfare of its students, faculty, and staff. [[Academic administration]] offices continued to operate with a [[skeleton crew]], while other offices in colleges and universities operated through [[telecommuting]] arrangements.<ref>{{cite news |title=UP Diliman suspends online classes due to enhanced COVID-19 quarantine |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/17/20/up-diliman-suspends-online-classes-due-to-enhanced-covid-19-quarantine |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> Some schools, however, continued to hold online classes<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bagayas |first1=Samantha |title=Students urge suspension of online classes during coronavirus lockdown |url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/255504-students-urge-suspension-online-classes-coronavirus-lockdown |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=Rappler |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> and in response, several [[student group]]s appealed to CHED to suspend mandatory online classes in consideration of the logistical limitations and well-being of a majority of students.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Guno |first1=Ni\u00f1a |title=Students from 'Big 4' universities seek online class suspension from CHED |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1248397/students-from-big-4-universities-seek-online-class-suspension-from-ched |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nClasses in all levels across the country were eventually suspended due to the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |title=Situational Report No.6 of the National Task Force (NTF) for COVID-19 |url=http://www.ndrrmc.gov.ph/attachments/article/4036/sitrep_no6_re_national_task_force_for_coronavirus_disease_2019_issued_06_april_2020_4PM.pdf |accessdate=8 April 2020 |publisher=National Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Council |date=6 April 2020}}</ref> Graduation rites in Philippine schools are also either cancelled or postponed.<ref>{{cite news |title=DepEd: No graduation rites during COVID-19 crisis |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1257715/no-graduation-rites-under-covid-19-crisis |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Elections ===\nThe [[Commission on Elections (Philippines)|Commission on Elections]] (COMELEC) has suspended the nationwide voter registration on March 10 until the end of the month due to the COVID-19 pandemic. The registration period began on January 20, 2020, and is scheduled to run until September 30, 2021.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Patinio |first1=Ferdinand |title=Comelec suspends voter registration amid Covid-19 threat |url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1096013 |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |agency=Philippine News Agency |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> The suspension was later extended to last until the end of April. The issuance of voter's certification is also suspended until further notice. The next national elections scheduled in the Philippines are in [[2022 Philippine presidential election|May 2022]].<ref>{{cite news |title=COMELEC extends suspension of voter registration to April 30 |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/27/comelec-extends-suspension-voter-registration-april-30.html |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=April 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2020 Palawan partition plebiscite|plebiscite]] to ratify legislation that proposes the partition of [[Palawan]] into three smaller provinces scheduled for May 2020 may be delayed due to the COVID-19 pandemic. The province provincial legislature has called for a special session and is expected to pass a resolution allowing Governor Jose Alvarez to ask the COMELEC to postpone the plebiscite. Anti-partition advocacy group One Palawan has also called for the postponement of the plebiscite reasoning the {{Philippine peso|80 million}} ($1.6 million) budget allocated for the plebiscite could be used to fund the provincial government's efforts against COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Magdayao |first1=Aira Genesa |title=Postponement of Palawan division plebiscite sought |url=https://palawan-news.com/postponement-of-palawan-division-plebiscite-sought/ |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Palawan News Online |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Response ==\n=== Government ===\n[[File:2019-nCoV HealthAdvisory DOH Philippines.jpg|thumb|Health advisory on the coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) release by the Department of Health.]]\n\n==== Travel restrictions ====\n{{further information|Travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[Ruffy Biazon]], a member of the [[House of Representatives of the Philippines|House of Representatives]] from Muntinlupa, called on the [[Civil Aviation Authority of the Philippines]] (CAAP) on January 22 to suspend flights from Wuhan to the Philippines. [[Royal Air Charter Service]] operates direct flights from Wuhan to [[Kalibo]].<ref>{{cite news |title=DOH: It's possible Chinese boy in PH not infected with novel coronavirus |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/1/22/boy-wuhan-coronavirus-.html |accessdate=January 22, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=January 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200122151853/https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/1/22/boy-wuhan-coronavirus-.html |archive-date=January 22, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> By then, [[Visa policy of the Philippines|Philippine travel visas]] under the \"visa-upon-arrival\" (VUA) program were denied to tourists from Wuhan.<ref name=\"philStarPhilippinesDenyingVisas\">{{cite news |last1=Ramirez |first1=Robertzon |title=Philippines now denying visas to Wuhan tourists |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/01/26/1987883/philippines-now-denying-visas-wuhan-tourists |work=[[The Philippine Star]] |date=January 26, 2020 |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126133127/https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/01/26/1987883/philippines-now-denying-visas-wuhan-tourists |archive-date=January 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On January 24, the Philippine government deported 135 individuals from Wuhan who arrived in the country through the [[Kalibo International Airport]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Malasig |first1=Jeline |title=Philippine government's order to deport travelers from Wuhan: Was it too late? |url=http://www.interaksyon.com/politics-issues/2020/01/24/160692/coronavirus-wuhan-deportation-order-aklan-philippines/ |accessdate=January 27, 2020 |work=InterAksyon |date=January 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127105102/http://www.interaksyon.com/politics-issues/2020/01/24/160692/coronavirus-wuhan-deportation-order-aklan-philippines/ |archive-date=January 27, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> There were calls for a wider temporary ban on people entering the country from anywhere in China. This was supported by Senators [[Ralph Recto]], [[Bong Go]], [[Risa Hontiveros]], and [[Francis Pangilinan]] however, the DOH and the Office of the President find no urgent need for such a measure.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Luna |first1=Franco |title=Senators want 'Great Wall' vs Chinese visitors amid first Philippine novel coronavirus case |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/01/30/1989051/senators-want-great-wall-vs-chinese-visitors-amid-first-philippine-novel-coronavirus-case |accessdate=January 30, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=January 30, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130102251/https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/01/30/1989051/senators-want-great-wall-vs-chinese-visitors-amid-first-philippine-novel-coronavirus-case |archive-date=January 30, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn January 31, a [[Freedom of movement|travel ban]] on all Chinese nationals from [[Hubei]] and other affected areas in China was imposed. The VUA program for Chinese tourists and businessmen was also suspended.<ref>{{cite news |title=Duterte bans travelers from Wuhan, Hubei as coronavirus spreads |url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/250640-duterte-bans-travelers-from-wuhan-hubei-coronavirus |accessdate=January 31, 2020 |work=[[Rappler]] |date=January 31, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131074521/https://www.rappler.com/nation/250640-duterte-bans-travelers-from-wuhan-hubei-coronavirus |archive-date=January 31, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On February 2, a ban was introduced on all foreign travelers who visited China, Hong Kong, and [[Macau]] in the past 14 days;<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/2/2/Duterte-travel-ban-mainland-China-Hong-Kong-Macau.html|title=ban on mainland China, Hong Kong, Macau|first=Glee|last=Jalea|publisher=CNN|date=February 2, 2020|access-date=February 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203151241/https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/2/2/Duterte-travel-ban-mainland-China-Hong-Kong-Macau.html|archive-date=February 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Philippine citizens and holders of permanent resident visas were allowed in the country but subjected to a mandatory 14-day quarantine. The Philippine government also ordered a ban on travel to China, Hong Kong, and Macau until further notice.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/02/02/20/ph-imposes-travel-ban-on-china-as-new-coronavirus-infections-rise-globally|title=PH imposes travel ban on China as new coronavirus infections rise globally|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=February 8, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205134435/https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/02/02/20/ph-imposes-travel-ban-on-china-as-new-coronavirus-infections-rise-globally|archive-date=February 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On February 10, the ban was further extended to include [[Taiwan]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Felongco |first1=Gilbert |title=Covid-19 countermeasures trigger row between Manila and Taiwan |url=https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/philippines/covid-19-countermeasures-trigger-row-between-manila-and-taiwan-1.69669414 |accessdate=February 12, 2020 |work=Gulf News |date=February 12, 2020}}</ref> but was lifted on February 15.<ref>{{cite news |title=Taiwan lauds lifting of Philippines' coronavirus-related ban: Diplomacy works |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/world/2020/2/15/taiwan-philippines-coronavirus-travel-ban.html |accessdate=February 15, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=February 15, 2020}}</ref> On February 14, the DOH announced that a risk assessment carried out to determine if Singapore would be placed under a travel ban.<ref name=\"SCMPR\">{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3050637/coronavirus-will-singapore-be-next-philippines-travel|title=Coronavirus: will Singapore be next on Philippines' travel ban list?|first=John|last=Power|publisher=South China Morning Post|website=scmp.com|date=February 14, 2020|access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> Philippine Foreign Secretary [[Teodoro Locsin Jr.]] announced that he would not fully support any official travel bans to Singapore.<ref name=\"SCMPR\"/> On February 26, travel to South Korea was banned, except for permanent residents, Filipino leaving for study, and Overseas Filipino Workers returning for work.<ref>{{cite news |title=Philippines suspends travel to South Korea due to COVID-19 |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/727430/philippines-suspends-travel-to-south-korea-due-to-covid-19/story/ |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |work=GMA News |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Philippine Ports Authority]] had barred disembarkation by crew or passengers from vessels that have recently visited China and suspended the visitation privileges of relatives of Filipino seafarers and boarding privileges of non-government organizations providing emotional and spiritual support to seafarers.<ref>{{cite news |last1=De Leon |first1=Susan |title=PPA bans disembarkation of vessel crews from nCoV-hit China |url=https://pia.gov.ph/news/articles/1034127 |accessdate=February 10, 2020 |publisher=Philippine Information Agency |date=February 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, Locsin announced that the Philippine government would deny the entry of all foreign nationals, effective that day \"until further notice\". All Philippine embassies and consulates would suspend the issuing of its visas to all foreign nationals and invalidate all existing ones. However, Locsin clarified that visas that had already been issued to families of Filipino nationals would remain valid.<ref>{{cite news |title=Philippines suspends visa issuance as worldwide COVID-19 cases soar \u2013 Locsin |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/19/Philippines-DFA-considering-visa-issuance-suspension-Locsin-coronavirus-COVID.html |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 22, the [[Department of Transportation (Philippines)|Department of Transportation]] ordered a travel ban to all foreign nationals, with the exception of returning or repatriated overseas Filipinos, foreign spouses of Filipino citizens (and their children), and workers for international organizations and non-governmental organizations accredited in the country.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cordero |first1=Ted |title=Foreigners banned from entering Philippines starting March 22 \u2013 DOTr |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/730560/foreigners-banned-from-entering-philippines-starting-march-22-dotr/story/ |agency=GMA News |date=March 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Nationwide measures ====\n[[File:Pres Duterte IATF-EID COVID19 meeting March 12.jpg|thumb|President [[Rodrigo Duterte]] presides over a meeting with the [[Inter-Agency Task Force on Emerging Infectious Diseases]] (IATF-EID) at the [[Malaca\u00f1ang Palace]] on March 12.]]\nFollowing the confirmation of the first localized transmission on March 7, the DOH raised its alert to Code Red Sub-Level 1.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/7/coronavirus-philippines-local-transmission.html|title='Code Red': Philippines confirms 2 cases of local coronavirus transmission|first=Eimor|last=Santos|publisher=CNN Philippines|website=cnnphilippines.com|date=March 7, 2020|access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> Health Secretary [[Francisco Duque]] and Senator Bong Go, chair of the Senate Committee on Health and Demography, recommended to President Rodrigo Duterte to declare a public health emergency in the country,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cordero |first1=Ted |title=DOH recommends declaration of public health emergency after COVID-19 local transmission |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/728715/doh-recommends-declaration-of-public-health-emergency-after-covid-19-local-transmission/story/ |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> which would authorize local government units to employ their local disaster risk reduction management funds.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bong Go to recommend to Duterte declaration of state of public health emergency |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1238163/bong-go-to-recommend-to-duterte-declaration-of-state-of-public-health-emergency |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> President Duterte issued Proclamation No. 922 on March 9, formally declaring a public health emergency.<ref name=\"phe\"/>\n\nThe [[Department of Trade and Industry (Philippines)|Department of Trade and Industry]] on March 9 issued a directive ordering retailers should only allow the sale of two bottles of each type of disinfectant per person as a measure against hoarding. In line with the public health emergency declaration, the department imposed a 60-day price freeze on basic commodities.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Santos |first1=Eimor |title=DTI order: Sell only two bottles of alcohol, disinfectants per person |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/12/coronavirus-alcohol-disinfectants-2-bottles-per-person-philippines.html |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, the president signed Proclamation No. 929 declaring a state of calamity throughout the country for six months, bringing into effect the following:<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/2020/03/16/proclamation-no-929-s-2020/|title=Proclamation No. 929 s. 2020 Declaring a State of Calamity Throughout the Philippines due to Corona Virus Disease 2019|date=March 17, 2020|publisher=Official Gazette GOV.PH|access-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* price control of basic needs and commodities,\n* granting interest-free loans,\n* distribution of calamity funds,\n* authorization of importation and receipt of donations, and\n* hazard allowance for public health workers and government personnel in the fields of science and technology.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/laginghanda/dagling-paliwanag-ano-ang-state-of-calamity/|title=Dagling Paliwanag: Ano ang State of Calamity?|publisher=Official Gazette GOV.PH|access-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Philippine Health Insurance Corporation]] (PhilHealth) announced that it would provide {{Philippine peso|30-billion|link=no}} ($581-million) worth of [[advance payment]] to its accredited health facilities for health care providers to obtain the [[liquid capital]] required to efficiently respond to the crisis. PhilHealth also subsided some of its policies on its members; it waived the 45-day coverage and single period of confinement policies while extending payment deadlines until the end of April and the failing period of claims from 60 days to at least 120 days. Also, PhilHealth announced that PUIs quarantined in its accredited facilities are entitled to a {{Philippine peso|14,000}} ($270) health package, while those who tested positive for COVID-19 are entitled to a {{Philippine peso|32,000}} ($580) beneficiary package.<ref>{{cite news |title=PhilHealth to release \u20b130-B to hospitals amid fight vs. COVID-19 |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/18/PhilHealth-to-release-30-billion-advance-payment-IRM-COVID.html |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, President Duterte signed Administrative Order No. 26, granting that front line government officials and employees receive a daily hazard pay of {{Philippine peso|500}} ($9.87).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Merez |first1=Arianne |title=Duterte grants COVID-19 hazard pay to gov't frontliners during lockdown |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/23/20/duterte-grants-covid-19-hazard-pay-to-govt-frontliners-during-lockdown |accessdate=April 6, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> On April 6, President Duterte signed Administrative Order No. 28, granting the payment of a special risk allowance to public health workers in addition to their hazard pay. According to the order, public health workers attending to COVID-19 patients, PUMs, and PUIs will receive at most a quarter of their basic pay.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Merez |first1=Arianne |title=Public health frontliners get extra risk pay under Duterte order |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/06/20/public-health-frontliners-get-extra-risk-pay-under-duterte-order |accessdate=April 6, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Department of Labor and Employment (Philippines)|Department of Labor and Employment]] announced it would initiate a cash assistance program worth {{Philippine peso|2 billion}} ($39 million) for workers in both the formal and informal sectors across the country affected by government-imposed quarantines. As of March 31, the department reported that at least 25,428 formal sectors and 5,220 informal sector workers were given cash assistance of {{Philippine peso|5,000}} ($98) each.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cash aid for workers: Labor dept secures funding to start program |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/04/01/20/philippines-coronavirus-labor-secures-p2-billion-to-start-cash-aid-for-workers |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===== Bayanihan to Heal as One Act =====\n{{main|Bayanihan to Heal as One Act}}\n[[File:SPECIAL SESSION ON COVID-19.jpg|thumb|Senators during a special session to tackle the passage of the Bayanihan to Heal as One Act on March 23.]]\nFollowing the sharp increase of confirmed cases, President Duterte called on Congress to hold special sessions on March 23 to enact the Bayanihan to Heal as One Act upon his request, which would \"authorize the President to exercise powers necessary to carry out urgent measures to meet the current national emergency related to COVID-19 only for three months unless extended by Congress.\" The act would allow President Duterte to \"reallocate, realign, and reprogram\" a budget of almost {{Philippine peso|275 billion}} ($5.37 billion) from the estimated {{Philippine peso|438 billion}} ($8.55 billion) national budget approved for 2020, in response to the pandemic;<ref>{{Cite news|last=Parrocha|first=Azer|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1097429|title=Duterte seeks 'more powers,' urgent measures vs. Covid-19|date=March 22, 2020|agency=Philippine News Agency|access-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> enable him to \"temporarily take over or direct the operations\" of public utilities and privately owned health facilities and other necessary facilities \"when the public interest so requires\" for quarantine, the accommodation of health professionals, and the distribution and storage of medical relief; and \"facilitate and streamline\" the accreditation of testing kits.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Luci-Atienza |first1=Charissa |title=House approves 'Bayanihan' bill on 3rd reading in historic virtual special session; grants PRRD 'necessary' powers to handle COVID-19 crisis |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/24/house-approves-bayanihan-bill-on-3rd-reading-in-historic-virtual-special-session-grants-prrd-necessary-powers-to-handle-covid-19-crisis/ |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Philippine House of Representatives]], the bill was introduced as House Bill No. 6616 with House Speaker [[Alan Peter Cayetano]] of [[Legislative district of Pateros\u2013Taguig|Pateros\u2013Taguig]] as its principal sponsor and was defended on the floor by Deputy Speaker [[Luis Raymund Villafuerte]] of [[Camarines Sur]]'s [[Legislative districts of Camarines Sur#2nd District|2nd district]]. Executive Secretary [[Salvador Medialdea]] addressed the session, stressing that the president needed \"standby powers\" to address the emergency.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Romero |first1=Paolo |last2=Porcalla |first2=Delon |title=Congress grants Duterte covid standby powers |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/24/2002989/congress-grants-duterte-covid-standby-powers |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Some representatives questioned the nature, usage, and necessity of the \"standby powers\", claiming its susceptibility to abuse and corruption.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Luci-Atienza |first1=Charissa |title=9 solons voted against Bayanihan Act; say special powers prone to abuse, misuse |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/24/9-solons-voted-against-bayanihan-act-say-special-powers-prone-to-abuse-misuse/ |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Senate of the Philippines]], the bill was introduced as Senate Bill No. 1418 with Senate President [[Tito Sotto]] and Senator [[Pia Cayetano]] as its principal sponsors. Under the bill, Senator Cayetano said that over 18 million Filipino households [[Poverty in the Philippines|living below the poverty line]] would also receive financial incentives of around {{Philippine peso|5,000}}\u20138,000 ($97.45\u2013155.92) per month for two months.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ager |first1=Maila |title=Poor families to get up to P8,000 cash subsidy from COVID-19 bill |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1247244/poor-families-to-get-up-to-p8000-cash-subsidy-from-covid-19-bill |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> Senators amended their version of the bill to include financial compensation of around {{Philippine peso|100,000}} ($1,965.33) to be given by PhilHealth to health professionals who contracted the virus, as well as the provision of around {{Philippine peso|1 million}}-worth ($19,653.27) of financial aid to their families.<ref>{{cite news |title=Senators seek \u20b11-M death benefit; \u20b1100K aid for COVID-infected health workers |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/24/COVID-19-health-workers-1-million-death-100k-assistance-Senate-bill-power.html |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBoth versions of the bill reportedly removed the usage of the term \"emergency powers\", replacing it with \"authority\". It also removed the term \"take over of public utilities and private businesses\", limiting President Duterte's abilities at most to \"direct the operations\" of such enterprises.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Navallo |first1=Mike |title=COVID-19 CRISIS: How President Duterte's emergency powers bill morphed in 36 hours |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/24/20/covid-19-crisis-how-president-dutertes-emergency-powers-bill-morphed-in-36-hours |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The House version of the bill passed the House of Representatives in a 284\u20139 vote without abstentions,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mercado |first1=Neil Arwin |title=House OKs bill granting Duterte 'necessary' powers due to COVID-19 crisis |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1246872/house-approves-bill-declaring-national-emergency-due-to-coronavirus |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> while its Senate version unanimously passed the Senate.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ramos |first1=Christia Marie |last2=Lalu |first2=Gabriel Palico |title=Senate OKs bill granting Duterte special powers to fight COVID-19 |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1247363/senate-oks-bill-granting-duterte-special-powers-to-fight-covid-19 |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> President Duterte signed the bill into law the following day.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Valente |first1=Catherine |title=Duterte signs measure on special powers into law |url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/03/25/news/headlines/duterte-signs-measure-on-special-powers-into-law/706195/ |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=The Manila Times |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Lockdowns ====\n{{main|2020 Philippine community quarantines|2020 Luzon enhanced community quarantine}}\n[[File:COVID-19 community quarantine in the Philippines.svg|thumb|Community quarantines in the Philippines (as of April 7) {{legend|#023858ff|Provinces under enhanced community quarantine including Metro Manila}}{{legend|#2b8cbeff|Provinces under community quarantine}}\n]]\nGiven the rapidly increasing number of cases in the [[National Capital Region]], [[Legislative districts of Albay#2nd District|Albay 2nd district]] representative [[Joey Salceda]] proposed a week-long [[lockdown]] of the region to prevent the disease from spreading nationwide. Salceda specifically proposed the closure of the [[Philippine expressway network]] and public transportation accessing the region, in addition to the suspension of classes and work.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Panti |first1=Llanesca |title=Lawmaker wants weeklong NCR lockdown amid COVID-19 threat |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/728901/lawmaker-wants-weeklong-ncr-lockdown-to-prevent-spread-of-covid-19/story/ |accessdate=March 9, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> President Duterte initially rejected the proposal claiming it would \"hamper the flow of basic commodities\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lopez |first1=Virgil |title=Duterte thumbs down lockdown for Metro Manila over COVID-19 |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/729000/duterte-thumbs-down-lockdown-for-metro-manila-over-covid-19/story/?just_in |accessdate=March 9, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> Secretary Duque, however, raised the possibility of a lockdown on certain cities or towns if cases of community-based transmissions are reported, but not an entire region.<ref>{{cite news |title=DOH: 'Localized lockdown' possible amid coronavirus pandemic |url=https://www.cnn.ph/news/2020/3/10/Philippines-lockdown-coronavirus.html |accessdate=March 10, 2020 |publisher=CNN Philippines |date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n<!-- [[File:COVID-19 community quarantine in the Philippines.svg|300px|left|thumb|Community quarantine in the Philippines.]]\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Philippines coronavirus quarantines}}\n{{clear}} -->\nOn March 12, President Duterte announced a partial lockdown covering [[Metro Manila]],<ref name=manila/> that began on March 15 and will last until April 14.\n\nIn addition, President Duterte advised local government units outside of the National Capital Region to implement a community quarantine in cases where, in a given level of local government, at least two COVID-19 cases are confirmed within a lower level of its jurisdiction; for example, a [[Provinces of the Philippines|province]]-wide quarantine should be implemented if there are at least two COVID-19 cases confirmed within different [[Cities of the Philippines|cities]] or [[Municipalities of the Philippines|municipalities]] in the same province, while a city/municipality-wide quarantine should be implemented if there are at least two COVID-19 cases confirmed within different ''[[barangay]]s'' in the same city or municipality. Local government units were also authorized to utilize their quick response funds upon declaration of a [[state of emergency]].<ref name=manila>{{cite news |last1=Esguerra |first1=Darryl John |title=BREAKING: Metro Manila placed under 'community quarantine' due to COVID-19 |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1240942/breaking-metro-manila-placed-under-community-quarantine-due-to-covid-19 |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nCainta also initiated a partial lockdown on March 15, after three cases of COVID-19 were confirmed in the municipality.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/13/Cainta-mayor-to-place-town-under-quarantine-over-three-COVID-19-cases.html???&fbclid=IwAR3RiDOgRvcj3w5z-2PEDaBt6S9vQdk-teHSAVgpbLqUERsnwJMtZtIHWKI|title=Cainta mayor to place town under quarantine over 3 confirmed cases of COVID-19|website=cnn|language=en|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> [[Bohol]] Governor [[Arthur C. Yap]] announced that the province would be placed under community quarantine from March 16 to 20 and will prohibit tourists from entering during the quarantine period.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Erram |first1=Morexette Marie |title=Bohol under 5-day community quarantine to 'prepare for the worse' of COVID-19 |url=https://cebudailynews.inquirer.net/293863/bohol-under-5-day-community-quarantine-to-prepare-for-the-worse-of-covid-19 |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=Cebu Daily News |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n[[File:COVID-19 Community Quarantine Checkpoint in Cagayan.jpg|thumb|A police-manned checkpoint in [[Tuguegarao]]]]\n[[File:6817Baliuag enhanced community quarantine 20.jpg|thumb|[[Baliuag, Bulacan]] on March 21, 2020, during the enhanced community quarantine]]\nOn March 16, President Duterte imposed an enhanced community quarantine covering the entire [[Luzon]], which entails the following measures:<ref name=\"ECQ\">{{cite news |last1=Luna |first1=Franco |title=Duterte places entire Luzon under 'enhanced' community quarantine |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/16/2001320/duterte-places-entire-luzon-under-enhanced-community-quarantine |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/2020/03/16/memorandum-from-the-executive-secretary-on-community-quarantine-over-the-entire-luzon-and-further-guidelines-for-the-management-of-the-coronavirus-disease-2019-covid-19-situation/|title=Memorandum from the Executive Secretary On Community Quarantine Over the Entire Luzon and Further Guidelines for the Management of the Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) Situation|date=March 16, 2020|work=Official Gazette GOV.PH|access-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* the suspension of [[Transportation in the Philippines|mass public transportation]];\n* restricted land, air, and sea travel, in which [[Overseas Filipinos]] and foreign nationals are given a 72-hour window (until March 20) to depart the Philippines from any port of entry in Luzon, although Overseas Filipinos may enter the country at any time;\n* the imposition of strict home quarantine among all households;\n* the organization of [[telecommuting]] arrangements for the [[Executive departments of the Philippines|executive government]], with the exception of the [[Philippine National Police]], [[Armed Forces of the Philippines]], and health and emergency front line services;\n* and the closure of all private establishments, except for those providing essential goods and services and [[Business process outsourcing in the Philippines|business process outsourcing]] establishments.\n\nThe Luzon measures also cover the [[Mimaropa]] region which includes the outlying islands of Palawan, [[Marinduque]], [[Mindoro]], and Romblon.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus lockdown covers MIMAROPA, says Nograles |url=https://politics.com.ph/coronavirus-lockdown-covers-mimaropa-says-nograles/ |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=Politko |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, Cabinet Secretary [[Karlo Nograles]] announced that the Office of the President, through the [[Inter-Agency Task Force on Emerging Infectious Diseases]] (IATF-EID), had rescinded the 72-hour window for which Overseas Filipinos and foreign nationals were allowed to depart the country from Luzon. As such, outbound passengers are permitted to depart the Philippines at any time during the period of the enhanced community quarantine, but Filipino residents are still prohibited from doing so.<ref>{{cite news |title=OFWs, foreign nationals now allowed to fly out of PH |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/18/OFWs-foreign-nationals-now-allowed-to-fly-out-of-PH.html |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 7, President Duterte extended the duration of the enhanced community quarantine on Luzon until April 30, following a recommendation from the IATF.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Patag |first1=Kristine Joy |title=Duterte approves Luzon-wide community quarantine until April 30 |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/04/07/2006056/duterte-approves-luzon-wide-community-quarantine-until-april-30 |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\nLocal governments units both within and outside Luzon has also imposed their own quarantine measures.\n\n==== Repatriation ====\n{{further information|Evacuations related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n===== From mainland China =====\n[[File:Arrival of repatriated Filipinos from China 2019-nCov.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Repatriated Filipinos disembark their plane at [[Clark Air Base]], [[Pampanga]] on February 9.]]\nThe government began the repatriation of Filipino nationals in China on January 18.<ref name=\"dfabringshome\">{{cite news |title=DFA Brings Home 30 Filipinos from Wuhan City |url=https://www.dfa.gov.ph/dfa-news/dfa-releasesupdate/25888-dfa-brings-home-30-filipinos-from-wuhan-city |accessdate=February 10, 2020 |publisher=Department of Foreign Affairs |date=February 9, 2020}}</ref> Flights were organized to repatriate Filipinos in the [[Hubei]]. Upon arrival in the Philippines, individuals underwent mandatory quarantine for 14 days.<ref name=\"specialflights\">{{cite news |title=PH sending special flights to get Pinoys from Wuhan, Hubei in China |url=http://tempo.com.ph/2020/01/29/ph-sending-special-flights-to-get-pinoys-from-wuhan-hubei-in-china/ |accessdate=January 29, 2020 |work=Tempo |date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Mega Drug Abuse Treatment and Rehabilitation Center]] at [[Fort Magsaysay]] in [[Nueva Ecija]] and [[Caballo Island]] in [[Manila Bay]] are being considered as possible quarantine sites for repatriated Filipinos.<ref name=\"doheyesrehab\">{{cite news |last1=De Vera |first1=Analou |title=DOH eyes rehab center in Nueva Ecija as quarantine site for repatriated Filipinos |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/02/01/doh-eyes-rehab-center-in-nueva-ecija-as-quarantine-site-for-repatriated-filipinos/ |accessdate=February 2, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=February 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202160020/https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/02/01/doh-eyes-rehab-center-in-nueva-ecija-as-quarantine-site-for-repatriated-filipinos/ |archive-date=February 2, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> President Duterte said that the government may seize private property for conversion to quarantine sites.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Romero |first1=Alexis |title=Duterte ready to seize private buildings to quarantine nCoV patients |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/02/04/1990453/duterte-ready-seize-private-buildings-quarantine-ncov-patients |accessdate=February 7, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=February 4, 2020}}</ref> It was later decided that the Athlete's Village at the [[New Clark City Sports Hub]] which also has a clinic run by the [[Philippine General Hospital]] will be used as a quarantine site for repatriated Filipinos. [[New Clark City]] was locked down on February 6 in preparation for the arrival of the repatriated.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Navales |first1=Reynaldo |title=Communities around New Clark City assured of safety, protection |url=https://www.sunstar.com.ph/article/1843349 |accessdate=February 7, 2020 |work=Sun Star Pampanga |date=February 7, 2020}}</ref> The first batch of repatriated Filipinos arrived at the [[Clark Air Base]] via a [[Royal Air Philippines|Royal Air]] chartered flight on February 9.<ref>{{cite news |title=30 Filipinos from nCoV-stricken Wuhan arrive in Philippines |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/02/09/20/repatriated-filipinos-from-ncov-struck-wuhan-arrive-in-philippines |accessdate=February 10, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=February 9, 2020}}</ref> From the airbase, designated buses transported them to the quarantine site at the New Clark City in [[Capas, Tarlac]].<ref name=\"dfabringshome\"/>\n\nAll 30 repatriated Overseas Filipino Workers in New Clark City received a clean bill of health and released from quarantine on February 22 along with the ten-member joint DFA-DOH Health Emergency Response Team, six flight crew members, and three ground operators which assisted in the repatriation process. During the quarantine period, none of the individuals displayed any symptoms with one woman giving birth.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Crisostomo |first1=Sheila |title=30 OFWs in New Clark City released from quarantine |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/02/23/1995364/30-ofws-new-clark-city-released-quarantine |accessdate=February 23, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=February 23, 2020}}</ref> There are around 150 Filipinos who live in Wuhan alone,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Merez |first1=Arianne |title=PH reviews repatriation of Filipinos from Chinese virus epicenter |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/01/28/20/ph-reviews-repatriation-of-filipinos-from-chinese-virus-epicenter |accessdate=January 28, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=January 28, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128074336/https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/01/28/20/ph-reviews-repatriation-of-filipinos-from-chinese-virus-epicenter |archive-date=January 28, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> about 40 to 50 of whom have asked to be repatriated.<ref name=doheyesrehab/>\n\n===== From Macau =====\nOn March 7, the Philippine government announced that an airlift operation will be launched to bring home 167 Filipinos working in Macau.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Modesto |first1=Catherine |title=163 stranded Filipinos from Macau arrive home |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/7/macau-evacuees-go-home-march-7.html |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |date=March 7, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===== From international conveyance =====\n{{see also|2020 coronavirus pandemic on cruise ships}}\n[[File:PH DFA repatriation 3.jpg|thumb|250px|Officials of the Department of Foreign Affairs greets repatriates from the M/V ''Grand Princess'' at [[Clark International Airport]] on March 16.]]\nThe Philippine government announced on February 17 that they have begun the process of repatriating on board the ''[[Diamond Princess (ship)|Diamond Princess]]'' which was quarantined off the coast of Yokohama due to confirmed COVID-19 infection.<ref name=\"filipinoship\">{{cite news |title=Filipinos infected with coronavirus in ship climbs as PH plans for evacuation |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/2/17/Diamond-Princess-cruise-ship-novel-coronavirus-Philippines-cases.html |accessdate=February 17, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=February 17, 2020}}</ref> 445 Filipinos (440 being crew members and 5 being passengers) were quarantined in New Clark City.<ref name=\"crew400\">{{cite news |last1=Aquino |first1=Leslie Ann |title=400 Diamond Princess crew quarantined in New Clark City 0 |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/02/28/400-diamond-princess-crew-quarantined-in-new-clark-city/ |accessdate=March 2, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> The repatriates arrived in the Philippines via two separate flights on February 25 and 26.<ref name=\"ritm19000\"/>\n\nAfter completing a 14-day quarantine period, repatriated seafarers will be given aid by the [[Overseas Workers Welfare Administration]] (OWWA). Each will receive {{Philippine peso|10,000}} from the OWWA and {{Philippine peso|20,000}} livelihood grant will be made available to Filipino seafarers who opted to stay permanently in the Philippines.<ref name=crew400/>\n\nThirteen repatriates exhibited symptoms after arrival but all tested negative for the COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |title=All symptomatic Pinoys repatriated from cruise ship test negative for COVID-19 |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/727974/all-symptomatic-pinoys-repatriated-from-cruise-ship-test-negative-for-covid-19/story/ |accessdate=March 2, 2020 |work=GMA News |date=March 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, the [[Department of Foreign Affairs (Philippines)|Department of Foreign Affairs]] (DFA) repatriated a total of 444 Filipinos (including 438 crew members and 6 passengers) from the cruise ship ''[[Grand Princess]]'' docked in the [[Port of Oakland]] in [[California]].<ref>{{cite web |title=DFA to Bring Home Filipinos Aboard the MV Grand Princess |url=https://dfa.gov.ph/dfa-news/dfa-releasesupdate/26322-dfa-to-bring-home-filipinos-aboard-the-mv-grand-princess |publisher=[[Department of Foreign Affairs (Philippines)|Philippine Department of Foreign Affairs]] |accessdate=March 15, 2020 |date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> Repatriates arrived on March 16 at [[Clark International Airport]] and were transported to New Clark City for quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |title=Filipino evacuees from cruise ship back in PH, to undergo quarantine |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/16/Grand-Princess-cruise-ship-repatriation-coronavirus.html |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe DFA repatriated a combined total of 370 Filipinos from the ''[[Costa Luminosa]]'', ''[[MSC Grandiosa]]'', and ''[[MSC Opera]]'' cruise ships docked in Italy. The repatriated Filipinos arrived in Manila on March 29 and underwent a mandatory 14-day quarantine. All of them were reported to be asymptomatic upon arrival.<ref>{{cite news |last1=de Guzman |first1=Robie |title=370 Filipino cruise ship workers from Italy back in PH |url=https://www.untvweb.com/news/370-filipino-cruise-ship-workers-from-italy-back-in-ph/ |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=UNTV |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 31, the Philippine government repatriated more than 500 Filipino seafarers stranded offshore from [[Miami, Florida]], U.S., aboard the ''[[Costa Favolosa]]'' and ''[[Costa Magica]]'' cruise ships. Both ships departed from [[Guadeloupe]] in the Caribbean with six occupants in the former and two passengers in the latter reportedly confirmed to have tested positive for COVID-19. The seafarers were flown on two chartered [[Ethiopian Airlines]] flights, coordinated by the DOH, Department of Transportation, OWWA, Bureau of Quarantine, and the Inter-Agency Task Force for the Management of Emerging Infectious Diseases, that were reportedly delayed since March 29.<ref name=\"Virata, Alvarez\"/>\n\n==== Other measures ====\n[[File:Malacanang COVID-19 Disinfection 03.jpg|thumb|[[Malaca\u00f1ang Palace#Grand Staircase|Grand staircase]] of [[Malaca\u00f1ang Palace]], the official residence and principal workplace of the [[President of the Philippines]], being disinfected and decontaminated on March 12.]]\nThe [[Presidential Security Group]] would start implementing a \"no-touch\" policy during meetings by President Duterte with politicians, reporters, and visitors.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3074343/coronavirus-philippines-declares-public-health |title=Philippines declares public health emergency, sets 'no-touch' rule on Duterte, as coronavirus cases rise to 20; South China Morning Post |publisher=Scmp.com |date= |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeveral government officials, including President Duterte, opted to undergo a self-quarantine after interacting with individuals confirmed to have COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |title=List: Gov't officials on self-quarantine due to COVID-19 exposure |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/12/list-govt-officials-on-self-quarantine-due-to-covid-19-exposure/ |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> This includes almost half of all members of the [[Senate of the Philippines]] (three senators tested positive),<ref name=\"Zubiri\"/><ref name=\"Pimentel\"/><ref name=\"Angara\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/254257-more-senators-under-self-quarantine-due-coronavirus-threat|title=Half of senators in self-quarantine due to coronavirus threat|last=Rey|first=Aika|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> several members of the [[Cabinet of the Philippines|Cabinet]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/729345/dpwh-s-villar-bsp-s-diokno-dbm-s-avisado-undergo-self-quarantine/story/|title=Cabinet execs Villar, Diokno, Avisado, Briones undergo self-quarantine|website=GMA News Online|language=en-US|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> [[Manila]] Mayor [[Isko Moreno]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/254164-isko-moreno-self-quarantines-manila-city-hall|title=Isko Moreno self-quarantines at Manila city hall|last=Talabong|first=Rambo|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> and [[Davao City]] Mayor [[Sara Duterte]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/729544/mayor-sara-duterte-discontinues-covid-19-self-quarantine/story/|title=Mayor Sara Duterte discontinues COVID-19 self-quarantine|website=GMA News Online|language=en-US|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> Several government facilities, including the offices of the [[Asian Development Bank]], the [[Bangko Sentral ng Pilipinas]], the [[Department of Finance (Philippines)|Department of Finance]], and the [[Government Service Insurance System]] (which also hosts the Senate), as well as [[Malaca\u00f1ang Palace]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lopez |first1=Virgil |title=Malaca\u00f1ang partially closed for disinfection, says PSG official |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/729318/malacanang-partially-closed-for-disinfection-says-psg-official/story/ |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> temporarily closed for disinfection following exposure from those officials who have interacted with a COVID-19 patient.<ref>{{cite news |last1=de Vera |first1=Ben |title=DOF, BSP, GSIS, ADB closed down to disinfect vs COVID-19 |url=https://business.inquirer.net/292307/dof-bsp-gsis-adb-locked-down-to-disinfect-vs-covid-19 |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeveral government officials announced that they would donate portions of their salaries to help fund government initiatives responding to the pandemic. President Duterte said that he would donate a month of his salary, which amounts to {{Philippine peso|400,000}}, to the [[Office of Civil Defense (Philippines)|Office of Civil Defense]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Duterte donating 1 month salary for coronavirus fight: Panelo |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/05/20/duterte-donating-1-month-salary-for-coronavirus-fight-panelo |accessdate=April 6, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=April 5, 2020}}</ref> Some senators and around 200 members of the [[House of Representatives of the Philippines|Philippine House of Representatives]] would also donate their salaries for May, while most Cabinet members would donate at most 75 percent of their salaries.<ref>{{cite news |title=House members donate May pay for COVID-19 response, aim for P50 million |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/04/20/house-members-donate-may-pay-for-covid-19-response-aim-for-p50-million |accessdate=April 6, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=April 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Colcol |first1=Erwin |title=Senators silently donating salaries for COVID-19 emergency \u2014 Sotto |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/732724/senators-silently-donating-salaries-for-covid-19-emergency-sotto/story/ |accessdate=April 6, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Private firms ===\n[[File:SM Foundation PPE Covid-19 OCD donation 2.jpg|thumb|The Civil of Office Defense receives donations of medical supplies from the SM Foundation.]]\nLocal airlines [[AirAsia Philippines|AirAsia]], [[Philippine Airlines]], and [[Cebu Pacific]] suspended flights between China and its territories (Macau and Hong Kong) and the Philippines from February 2.<ref>{{cite news |title=PAL, Cebu Pacific suspend flights between Philippines, China |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/02/01/20/cebu-pacific-halts-china-flights-until-march-over-coronavirus-scare |accessdate=February 2, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=February 2, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202052524/https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/02/01/20/cebu-pacific-halts-china-flights-until-march-over-coronavirus-scare |archive-date=February 2, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Following the announcement of the Luzon-wide enhanced community quarantine, Philippine Airlines suspended all its domestic flights from March 17 until April 12.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Arayata |first1=Maria Christina |title=PAL cancels all domestic flights in Luzon from March 17 to Apr 12 |url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1096899 |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |agency=Philippine News Agency |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> On March 24, the airline announced that it would also suspend all its remaining flights from March 26 until April 14 as more countries implement travel restrictions.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mercado |first1=Neil Arwin |title=PAL stops international flights from March 26 to April 14 |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1247777/pal-stops-international-flights-from-march-26-to-april-14 |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> Flight cancellations were later extended to April 30 following the extension of the enhanced community quarantine in Luzon to that date.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cebu Pacific, PAL cancel flights until April 30 |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/04/08/20/cebu-pacific-pal-cancel-flights-until-april-30 |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMall operators [[Ayala Malls]] and [[SM Supermalls]] have enforced stricter measures at its malls to safeguard larger volumes of customers and employees. These include temperature checks at mall entrances, an increase in the availability of alcohol and hand sanitizer dispensers, and the disinfection of restrooms occurring at smaller time intervals.<ref name=\"bwonline\">{{cite news |last1=Valdez |first1=Denise |title='Hysteria' over coronavirus hurting malls, hotels |url=https://www.bworldonline.com/hysteria-over-coronavirus-hurting-malls-hotels/ |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=BusinessWorld |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Following government directives to observe [[social distancing]] measures, some mall operators including [[Megaworld Lifestyle Malls]] have implemented a \"single-seat gap\" policy in cinemas, in which moviegoers are required to sit one seat apart from each other.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mercado |first1=Neil Arwin |title=One seat apart: Some malls take steps vs coronavirus threat |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1241613/one-seat-apart-some-malls-take-steps-vs-coronavirus-threat |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> Following the MMDA's imposition of an area-wide curfew during the Metro Manila lockdown, mall operators Ayala Malls, SM Supermalls, [[Robinsons Malls]], [[Vista Malls]], and the [[Greenhills Shopping Center|Ortigas]] [[Tiendesitas|Land]] [[Capitol Commons|Malls]] initially announced that it would shorten the operating hours of its malls in the area, from 11{{nbsp}}a.m. to 7{{nbsp}}p.m., in response.<ref>{{cite news |title=Metro Manila malls to shut down early ahead of quarantine |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/03/14/20/metro-manila-quarantine-malls-to-shut-down-early-ahead-of-quarantine |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref> However, Metro Manila city governments later passed ordinances mandating the temporary closure of malls except for essential services from March 16 \"until further notice\", per the joint resolution passed by the Metro Manila Council regarding the lockdown.<ref>{{cite web |title=UPDATED: Which NCR malls are closed and which cities have curfew? See list |url=https://www.spin.ph/life/active-lifestyle/possible-mall-closures-eyed-as-ncr-goes-into-curfew-starting-tomorrow-a1374-20200314 |website=Spin.ph |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |date=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe country's largest telecommunications services, [[Globe Telecom]] and [[Smart Communications]], both announced that they would offer its subscribers free services during the pandemic; Globe would offer free unlimited Internet connection in some hospitals in Metro Manila from March 13 to April 15,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Yang |first1=Angelica |title=Globe provides free internet connection in select Metro Manila hospitals |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/scitech/technology/729599/globe-provides-free-internet-connection-in-select-metro-manila-hospitals/story/ |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> while Smart would offer [[Open access|free access]] to government websites issuing updates and advisories, as well as [[Toll-free telephone number|toll-free access]] to emergency hotlines.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Yang |first1=Angelica |title=Smart offers free access to NDRRMC, PIA websites amid COVID-19 scare |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/scitech/technology/729597/smart-offers-free-access-to-ndrrmc-pia-websites-amid-covid-19-scare/story/ |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[San Miguel Corporation]], the largest corporation in the Philippines in terms of revenue, announced that its food, fuel, and power generation facilities would continue operation to provide essential services, amid the enhanced community quarantine in Luzon. President [[Ramon S. Ang]] gave assurances of the company's capability to produce sufficient food supplies and its commitment to continue paying its employees.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.sanmiguel.com.ph/article/smc-assures-its-food-facilities-will-continue-to-operate-outlines-efforts-to-help-fight-covid-19|title=SMC ASSURES ITS FOOD FACILITIES WILL CONTINUE TO OPERATE; OUTLINES EFFORTS TO HELP FIGHT COVID-19|date=March 16, 2020|publisher=San Miguel Corporation|access-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On March 27, the corporation announced that all its [[toll road]]s in Luzon, particularly [[STAR Tollway]], [[South Luzon Expressway]], the [[Metro Manila Skyway]], [[NAIA Expressway]], and the [[Tarlac\u2013Pangasinan\u2013La Union Expressway]], would be free of charge for all medical professionals for the duration of the enhanced community quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Balinbin |first1=Arjay |title=SMC offers toll-free passage for doctors, nurses |url=https://www.bworldonline.com/smc-offers-toll-free-passage-for-doctors-nurses/ |accessdate=March 28, 2020 |work=BusinessWorld |date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Ayala Corporation]], the country's largest corporation in terms of assets, announced a {{Philippine peso|2.4-billion|link=no}} (US$46.4 million) relief package for employees of its subsidiaries; the package comprises salary continuance, rent condonation for affected tenants of the Ayala Malls, leave conversions, loan deferments, and other financial assistance measures.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dumlao-Abadilla |first1=Doris |title=Ayala unveils P2.4B COVID-19 response package |url=https://business.inquirer.net/292776/ayala-unveils-p2-4b-covid-19-response-package?utm_medium=Social&utm_source=Facebook&fbclid=IwAR3BFQZ2p1-VzzD4HkG1t06wT_nkfC7I4rSH0J5KT-TfpUentCLXJWsHzLc#Echobox=1584440149 |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the declaration of an enhanced community quarantine on Luzon, numerous [[Tertiary sector of the economy|tertiary]] and [[Quaternary sector of the economy|quaternary sector]] companies had decided to implement an extended [[grace period]] of payment deadlines for its customers.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cabuenas |first1=Jon Viktor |title=Businesses extending payment deadlines amid enhanced community quarantine vs. COVID-19 |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/money/economy/730123/businesses-extending-payment-deadlines-amid-enhanced-community-quarantine-vs-covid-19/story/?utm_source=GMANews&utm_medium=Twitter |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Alliance Global Group]] pledged to donate {{convert|1,000,000|l|USgal|abbr=|sp=us}} of disinfectant solutions, denatured from {{convert|850,000|l|USgal|abbr=|sp=us}} of 96% [[Ethanol|ethyl alcohol]] to local health facilities and other front line institutions through the DOH.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cabuenas |first1=Jon Viktor |title=Alliance Global to donate 1M liters of disinfectant alcohol to Philippine gov't |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/money/companies/730273/alliance-global-to-donate-1m-liters-of-disinfectant-alcohol-to-philippine-gov-t/story/ |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nRidesharing company [[Grab (company)|Grab]] launched a service called \"GrabBayanihan\" (''bayanihan'' is the Filipino term for [[communal work]]) to provide free, 24/7 transportation services for front line workers of the pandemic, particularly medical staff, using the company's specialized fleet of cars. Grab also deployed their [[scooter-sharing system]] to cater specifically to those front line workers for their \"short-distance commutes.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mendiola |first1=Ritchel |title=Free rides for Metro Manila health workers |url=https://www.asianjournal.com/philippines/metro-manila/free-rides-for-metro-manila-health-workers/ |accessdate=March 28, 2020 |work=Asian Journal |date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[McDonald's Philippines]] announced a {{Philippine peso|500 million}} ($9.8 million) response fund for its employees, front line workers, and its partner marginalized sector communities. The fund includes an early release of salaries of employees, a special premium pay package for employees who choose to report to work, the provision of care kits (such as face masks and alcohol), and food packages to front line workers and the marginalized sector.<ref>{{cite news |title=McDonald's Philippines issues P500-M response fund to aid employees, communities it serves |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/advertorial/life/03/21/20/mcdonalds-philippines-issues-p500-m-response-fund-to-aid-employees-communities-it-serves |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Civil society ===\n\nThe non-profit organization Marine Conservation Philippines launched an online simulator visualizing and juxtaposing the rate of the coronavirus pandemic during [[Business as usual (business)|business as usual]], a partial lockdown, and a total lockdown.<ref>{{cite news |title=Philippine NGO launches simulator of coronavirus infections |url=https://www.rappler.com/science-nature/life-health/256219-local-ngo-launches-simulator-coronavirus-infections |accessdate=April 6, 2020 |work=Rappler |date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeveral health organizations offered [[telehealth]] consultation services, with some providing it for free, in an effort to decongest health facilities and observe social distancing.<ref>{{cite news |title=LIST: Medical groups, doctors open online consultations to decongest COVID-swamped hospitals |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/lifestyle/2020/3/25/online-consultation-services-coronavirus-COVID-list-Philippines.html |accessdate=April 6, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The Philippine Mental Health Association launched free [[telepsychology]] and [[telepsychiatry]] services, called the \"PMHA Online Psychosocial Support (Ensuring Wellbeing Amidst COVID-19).\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=de los Reyes |first1=Che |title=A virtual mental health clinic in the time of COVID-19 |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/life/04/03/20/a-virtual-mental-health-clinic-in-the-time-of-covid-19 |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> The psychology department of the [[De La Salle University]] offered a similar [[online counseling]] service for front line workers, PUIs, PUMs, and other persons experiencing [[mental health]] issues during the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cerezo |first1=Anna Gabrielle |title=La Salle offers free online counseling service |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/life/04/06/20/la-salle-offers-free-online-counseling-service |accessdate=April 6, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> \n\nSome schools that have suspended its classes used its facilities as an [[emergency shelter]] for homeless individuals as local governments implement lockdowns and quarantines. The De La Salle University accommodated 79 [[street people]] in [[Manila]] into its [[Enrique M. Razon Sports Center]] following the implementation of the enhanced community quarantine in Luzon.<ref>{{cite news |title=DLSU houses 79 homeless individuals for the duration of Luzon quarantine |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/22/20/dlsu-houses-79-homeless-individuals-for-the-duration-of-luzon-quarantine |accessdate=April 6, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> Its sister school, the [[De La Salle\u2013College of Saint Benilde]], accommodated 70 more people.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Adonis |first1=Meg |title=NGO, De La Salle provide shelter to homeless Manila residents during quarantine |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1247316/ngo-de-la-salle-provide-shelter-to-homeless-manila-residents-during-quarantine |accessdate=April 6, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> Health workers from [[The Medical City]] in [[Pasig]], who could not return home as a precautionary measure against exposing their families to the virus, sought refuge at [[La Salle Green Hills]] in [[Mandaluyong]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casinas |first1=Jhon Aldrin |title=La Salle Green Hills opens doors to 'heroes' of The Medical City |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/04/03/la-salle-green-hills-opens-doors-to-heroes-of-the-medical-city/ |accessdate=April 6, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe human rights center of the [[Ateneo de Manila University]] offered free online [[legal aid]] on concerns related to the coronavirus pandemic, including curfew apprehensions and discrimination against front line workers amid the community quarantines and lockdowns.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Baron |first1=Gabriela |title=Ateneo offers free legal assistance online |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/04/06/ateneo-offers-free-legal-assistance-online/ |accessdate=April 6, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNumerous celebrities and public personalities assisted or contributed to relief efforts amid the pandemic. Basketball player [[Japeth Aguilar]],<ref>{{cite news |title=PBA: Japeth Aguilar, wife raising funds for surgical masks |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/sports/03/18/20/pba-japeth-aguilar-wife-raising-funds-for-surgical-masks |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> actress [[Anne Curtis]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Biong |first1=Ian |title=Anne Curtis donates alcohol, gloves to hospitals battling COVID-19 |url=https://entertainment.inquirer.net/369492/anne-curtis-donates-alcohol-gloves-to-hospitals-battling-covid-19 |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> comedian [[Vice Ganda]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lino |first1=Cha |title=Vice Ganda distributes medical supplies to hospitals amid COVID-19 |url=https://entertainment.inquirer.net/368996/vice-ganda-distributes-medical-supplies-to-hospitals-amid-covid-19 |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> and [[Miss Universe 2015]] [[Pia Wurtzbach]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Guno |first1=Ni\u00f1a |title=Pia Wurtzbach crowdfunds for medical frontliner masks |url=https://entertainment.inquirer.net/369867/pia-wurtzbach-crowdfunds-for-medical-frontliner-masks |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> each donated [[personal protective equipment]] to medical facilities amid its shortage. Similarly, actress [[Bea Alonzo]] helped manufacture batches of [[face shield]]s for front liners,<ref>{{cite news |title=Bea Alonzo leads charity drive for COVID 19 frontliners |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/entertainment/04/05/20/bea-alonzo-teams-up-with-charity-group-for-covid-19-frontliners-supplies |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=April 5, 2020}}</ref> while actress [[Angel Locsin]] assembled [[field hospital]]s in several hospitals across Metro Manila that would increase the capacity for COVID-19 patients, PUIs, and PUMs.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Severo |first1=Jan Milo |title=Angel Locsin leads stars in setting up air-con tents for health workers |url=https://www.philstar.com/entertainment/2020/03/24/2003136/angel-locsin-leads-stars-setting-air-con-tents-health-workers |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> Supercouple [[Dingdong Dantes]] and [[Marian Rivera]], as well as [[Miss Universe 2018]] [[Catriona Gray]], provided meals for health workers and families involved or affected by the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |title=Marian Rivera, Dingdong Dantes prepare food for frontliners |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/entertainment/04/02/20/marian-rivera-dingdong-dantes-prepare-food-for-frontliners |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=WATCH: Catriona Gray appeals for help to bring food to 1,000 families in Tondo |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/life/03/24/20/watch-catriona-gray-appeals-for-help-to-bring-food-to-1000-families-in-tondo |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> Additionally, Dantes partnered with [[JobStreet.com]] to invite unemployed and [[Underemployment|underemployed]] Filipino workers to [[telecommuting]] opportunities amid the quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Malasig |first1=Jeline |title=Here's how Filipinos can earn amid COVID-19 work suspension, according to Dingdong Dantes |url=https://www.interaksyon.com/celebrities/2020/04/03/165714/heres-how-filipinos-can-earn-amid-covid-19-work-suspension-according-to-dingdong-dantes/ |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |work=InterAksyon |date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> Olympic weightlifter [[Hidilyn Diaz]], who was set to compete at the [[2020 Summer Olympics]] prior to its postponement, instead organized a [[Olympic weightlifting|weightlifting]] seminar via [[Zoom Video Communications|Zoom]], the proceeds of which would be directed to charities involved in the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |title=Hidilyn Diaz offers online weightlifting seminar |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/sports/04/07/20/hidilyn-diaz-offers-online-weightlifting-seminar |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome musicians held [[benefit concert]]s to raise funds, but did so through [[live streaming]] services due to the quarantine. [[National Artist of the Philippines|National Artist]] [[Ryan Cayabyab]] launched a concert series entitled ''Bayanihan, Musikahan'', featuring ''[[ASAP (TV program)|ASAP]]'' artists.<ref>{{cite news |title='Bayanihan, Musikahan': Ryan Cayabyab, Filipino artists launch FB Live concert series amid coronavirus crisis |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/entertainment/03/18/20/bayanihan-musikahan-ryan-cayabyab-filipinos-artists-launch-fb-live-concert-series-amid-coronavirus-crisis |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> Folk band [[Ben&Ben]] launched an online charity concert on March 27 to raise funds for the [[National Institutes of Health (Philippines)|National Institutes of Health]] and the [[Vicente Sotto Memorial Medical Center]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Ben&Ben to hold fundraising virtual concert in response to COVID-19 pandemic |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/entertainment/03/22/20/benben-to-hold-fundraising-virtual-concert-in-response-to-covid-19-pandemic |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> Singer [[Sarah Geronimo]] and her husband, actor [[Matteo Guidicelli]], collaborated with over 100 [[ABS-CBN]] celebrities to raise nearly {{Philippine peso|237 million}} ($5 million) from an online charity concert to donate basic necessities to the local governments of Metro Manila.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Severo |first1=Jan Milo |title=Sarah Geronimo, Matteo Guidicelli's first duet, over 100 stars raise P236M for Luzon quarantine beneficiaries |url=https://www.philstar.com/entertainment/2020/03/23/2002952/sarah-geronimo-matteo-guidicellis-first-duet-over-100-stars-raise-p236m-luzon-quarantine-beneficiaries |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Religious sector ====\n[[File:Catholic Diocese of Pasig Announcement.png|right|thumbnail|An announcement from the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Pasig]] that they will suspend all public masses starting March 14.]]\nThe [[Catholic Church in the Philippines|Roman Catholic Church in the Philippines]] has issued preventive guidelines against the pandemic through the [[Catholic Bishops' Conference of the Philippines]] (CBCP). In January 2020, the CBCP issued a liturgical guideline which urges [[Mass in the Catholic Church|Mass]] attendees to \"practice ordinarily\" the receiving of [[Communion (Catholic Church)|communion]] by hand, and avoid holding hands while praying \"[[The Lord's Prayer|Our Father]]\" during Mass. As a spiritual measure against the spread of the disease, the CBCP also composed an ''oratio imperata'' (obligatory prayer) which is to be recited in mass. In February 2020, the CBCP issued a second liturgical guideline in anticipation of the [[Lent]]en season. The bishops suggested that during [[Ash Wednesday]], ashes would be sprinkled on the faithfuls' head instead of the customary marking of the forehead with a cross to minimize body contact. The CBCP also urged people to refrain from kissing or touching the cross for veneration during [[Good Friday]], particularly the celebration of the [[Passion of Jesus]]. They suggested genuflection or bowing as an alternative to the practice.<ref name=\"vatican\">{{cite news |last1=Gomes |first1=Robin |title=Philippine Church takes measures against COVID-19 during Lent |url=https://www.vaticannews.va/en/church/news/2020-02/philippine-church-covid19-measures-asia-church.html |accessdate=February 23, 2020 |work=Vatican News |date=February 21, 2020}}</ref> [[List of Catholic dioceses in the Philippines|Dioceses across the country]] has suspended the public celebration of masses.<ref>{{cite news |title=CBCP calls for tolling of bells on April 8, joining in ecumenical prayer amid COVID-19 crisis |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/07/20/cbcp-calls-for-tolling-of-bells-on-april-8-joining-in-ecumenical-prayer-amid-covid-19-crisis |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> On April 8, [[Holy Wednesday]], the CBCP organized an interfaith prayer service against the spread of the coronavirus, which was televised nationwide.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Garcia |first1=Maria Angelica |title=Church bells in Philippines simultaneously ring out vs. COVID-19 |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/733193/church-bells-in-philippines-simultaneously-ring-out-vs-covid-19/story/ |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe [[Iglesia ni Cristo]] suspended worship services in their chapels in Luzon as part of their compliance to the [[2020 Luzon enhanced community quarantine|Luzon enhanced community quarantine]]. Members are sent guides and lessons to be read by the head of the household during Thursdays and Sundays in lieu of regular worship services.<ref>{{cite news |title=Iglesia ni Cristo to hold no worship service at chapels amid COVID-19 quarantine |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/730500/iglesia-ni-cristo-to-hold-no-worship-service-at-chapels-amid-covid-19-quarantine/story/ |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=GMA News |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> Worship services were also stopped in Cebu and members are also encouraged to watch worship services through livestreaming.<ref>{{cite news |title=INC to hold livestreamed worship services |url=https://ph.news.yahoo.com/inc-hold-livestreamed-worship-services-144200643.html |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Sun Star |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] directed missionaries assigned in the Philippines who are not native to the country to move out for temporary reassignment to another country. They were ordered to self-quarantine in their new homes for 14 days.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Walch |first1=Tad |title=Church reassigning nonnative missionaries from 23 missions in the Philippines |url=https://www.deseret.com/faith/2020/3/17/21183896/philippines-korea-mongolia-mormon-missionaries-lds-coronavirus-covid19 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=Deseret News |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Jehovah's Witnesses]], through their spokesperson Dean Jacek, said that they are also doing live streaming for their congregations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bworldonline.com/virtual-religious-gatherings-amidst-covid-19/|title=Virtual religious gatherings amidst COVID-19|last=Soliman|first=Michelle Anne P.|date=March 18, 2020|website=bworldonline.com|publisher=[[BusinessWorld]] Online|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Philippine Council of Evangelical Churches]], an organization composed of Evangelical and Protestant church member organizations, announced the suspension of regular Sunday worship services and other regular activities for a month and instead held its services via internet and social media.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/13/pcec-calls-for-cancellation-of-worship-services/|title=PCEC calls for cancellation of worship services|last=Aquino|first=Leslie Ann|date=March 13, 2020|work=Manila Bulletin|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Islam in the Philippines|Islamic community in the Philippines]] has also adopted measures against COVID-19. The [[Regional Darul Ifta' of Bangsamoro]] has suspended all congregational prayers in the Bangsamoro region from March 19 to April 10, 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1097226|title=BARMM suspends all congregational prayers due to Covid-19|first=Albashir|last=Saiden|publisher=Philippine News Agency|website=pna.gov.ph|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n=== Foreign aid===\n[[File:China COVID19 test kit PH donation 8.jpg|thumb|Medical supply aid from China being received by military personnel at the [[Villamor Air Base]], March 21]]\nThe government of China and the United States has pledged support to the Philippine government response against COVID-19. China announced that it would be donating medical supplies including 100,000 testing kits, 100,000 surgical masks, 10,000 N95 masks, and 10,000 sets of personal protective equipment.<ref name=\"chinaaid\">{{cite news |last1=Del Callar |first1=Michaela |title=China to aid Philippines with 100k COVID-19 test kits |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/730289/china-to-aid-philippines-with-100k-covid-19-test-kits/story/ |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=GMA News |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> The United States through [[USAID]] also pledged $2.7 million worth of aid to help the Philippines develop adequate testing capabilities, and ensure the availability of medical supplies through USAID's \"on-the-ground partners\".<ref>{{cite news |title=US commits P139 million aid to Philippines for COVID-19 response |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/17/20/us-commits-p139-million-aid-to-philippines-for-covid-19-response |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> China's aid was received on March 21, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |title=Thousands of test kits, masks from China arrive in PH to aid COVID-19 fight |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/21/20/thousands-of-test-kits-masks-from-china-arrive-in-ph-to-aid-covid-19-fight |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 22, 2020, the Philippine foreign department said that the Philippines will be receiving a donation from Singapore. Singapore is donating 3,000 testing kits and a Polymerase Chain Reaction (PCR) machine.<ref>{{cite news |title=Singapore donates 3,000 test kits |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/22/singapore-donates-3000-test-kits/ |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> Singaporean Ambassador to the Philippines Gerard Ho led the turnover of kits to Foreign Secretary Teddy Locsin.<ref>https://www.dfa.gov.ph/dfa-news/dfa-releasesupdate/26430-secretary-locsin-receives-covid-19-test-kits-pcr-machine-from-singapore</ref>\n\nOn March 28, it was disclosed that some of the test kits made in China were only 40% accurate in testing for signs of the coronavirus on a suspected patient.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/28/20/some-test-kits-sent-from-china-only-40-percent-accurate-doh |title=Some test kits sent from China only 40 percent accurate: DOH &#124; ABS-CBN News |work=ABS-CBN News |date= |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Misinformation and hoaxes ==\n{{further|Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nAfter the initial outbreak of the COVID-19 pandemic in the Philippines, [[Conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]], [[misinformation]], and [[disinformation]] emerged online regarding the origin, scale, prevention, treatment, and various other aspects of the disease. Among these hoaxes include:\n\n*SARS-CoV-2 being a type of [[Rabies virus|rabies]] along with advice to not eat bats. The virus is in the [[coronavirus]] family and is unrelated to rabies.<ref>{{cite news |title=Philippine health chief dismisses 'ridiculous' hoax that novel coronavirus is a type of rabies |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/philippine-health-chief-dismisses-ridiculous-hoax-novel-coronavirus-type-rabies |accessdate=February 15, 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |agency=Agence France-Presse Philippines |date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n*Boiled ginger as a cure for COVID-19. There is no concrete scientific proof for this claim. Mark Pasayan, a doctor from the Philippine Society for Microbiology and Infectious Diseases says that while a cold weather may make one more susceptible to the COVID-19 infection, the intake of hot or cold food does not correlate with the prevention and treatment of the disease.<ref>{{cite news |title=Doctors refute misleading online claim that consuming boiled ginger can cure novel coronavirus infections|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/doctors-refute-misleading-online-claim-consuming-boiled-ginger-can-cure-novel-coronavirus-infections|accessdate=February 15, 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |agency=Agence France-Presse Philippines |date=February 15, 2020}}</ref>\n*In the first week of February, the government supposedly imposed a 14-day quarantine for travelers coming from 20 countries. An infographic supporting the claim was circulated purportedly from the [[Department of Interior and Local Government]] (DILG). On February 7, the DILG denied the claim. At that time the quarantine measure is only being imposed from travelers from three territories: Mainland China, Macau, and Hong Kong.<ref>{{cite news |title=DILG: 14-day quarantine on travelers from over 20 countries a hoax |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/725251/dilg-14-day-quarantine-on-travelers-from-over-20-countries-a-hoax/story/ |accessdate=February 15, 2020 |work=GMA News |date=February 7, 2020}}</ref>\n*Viral posts with various claims such as avoidance of eating ice cream and cold food, and encouraging exposure to sunlight as a means of prevention against COVID-19 purportedly from UNICEF. UNICEF Philippines has issued a statement disassociating itself from the posts peddling false and misleading information.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Malasig |first1=Jeline |title='Misinformation': UNICEF Philippines tags viral posts sharing COVID-19 info using its name |url=https://www.interaksyon.com/rumor-cop/2020/03/09/163747/misinformation-unicef-philippines-viral-posts-sharing-covid-19-info-using-its-name/ |accessdate=March 10, 2020 |work=InterAksyon |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n*The Department of Health supposedly issuing an advisory on the proliferation of fake cigarettes which is claimed to be a method of transmission of COVID-19. The government agency did not issue such advisory.<ref>{{cite news |title=False: DOH says fake cigarettes that 'spread coronavirus' have reached PH |url=https://www.rappler.com/newsbreak/fact-check/253846-fake-cigarettes-spread-coronavirus-reach-philippines |accessdate=March 10, 2020 |work=Rappler |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n*A widely circulated graphic on social media claimed that gargling warm water with salt would \"eliminate the virus.\" DOH Undersecretary Eric Domingo said that while the saline water has been a recognized home treatment for symptoms of a sore throat for many generations, there is no evidence suggesting its capability to kill the virus.<ref>{{cite news |title=FALSE: Gargling salt water 'eliminates' coronavirus |url=https://www.rappler.com/newsbreak/fact-check/254504-gargling-salt-water-eliminates-coronavirus |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |work=Rappler |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n*A supposed video spread on the internet about how bananas can cure COVID-19. This information was even advocated by the presidential Spokesperson [[Salvador Panelo]]. However, DOH Spokesperson Ma. Rosario Vergeire debunked this claim, saying that while bananas is a healthy food source, there are no conclusive evidences yet about its effectivity against coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/18/Coronavirus-banana-cure-prevention.html?fbclid=IwAR2uVtXDPFr5Pvle07sYHNsjZIzum85LfrayizVuHEXWe69gsVSDpsJqajo|title=DOH debunks claims bananas can prevent COVID-19 infection|date=March 18, 2020|work=CNN Philippines|accessdate=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*The Palace also disproved posts circulating online about the declaration of \"Total Lockdown\" nationwide and warned its peddlers of imminent arrest. At the time of the circulation, the [[2020 Luzon enhanced community quarantine|enhanced community quarantine in Luzon]] was already in effect.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Geducos|first=Argyll Cyrus|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/27/palace-denies-total-lockdown-rumors-fake-news-peddlers-face-arrest/|title=Palace denies total lockdown rumors; fake news peddlers face arrest|date=March 27, 2020|work=Manila Bulletin|access-date=March 28, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Department of Health has advised against spreading misinformation and unverified claims concerning the pandemic.<ref name=\"dohurges\">{{cite news |title=Virus 'infodemic': DOH urges Pinoys not to spread fake news on coronavirus |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/01/27/20/virus-infodemic-doh-urges-pinoys-not-to-spread-fake-news-on-coronavirus |accessdate=February 15, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=January 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Philippine National Police]] has taken action against the spread of misinformation related to the pandemic and has warned the public that misinformation purveyors could be charged for violating Presidential Decree no. 90 for \"declaring local rumor, mongering and spreading false information\". In the case of misinformation circulated online, violators could be charged for violating the Cybercrime Prevention Act which has a maximum penalty of imprisonment for 12 years.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Caliwan |first1=Christopher Lloyd |title=PNP monitors 6 'hoax posts' on nCoV threat |url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1092969 |accessdate=February 15, 2020 |agency=Philippine News Agency |date=February 5, 2020}}</ref> The Bayanihan to Heal as One Act also punishes fake news peddlers of two months jail time or fine of up to {{Philippine peso|1 million}}.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gregorio|first=Xave|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/25/Fake-news-peddlers-P1-million-fine-under-Duterte-special-powers.html|title=Jail time, up to \u20b11-M fine await peddlers of fake COVID-19 news|date=March 25, 2020|work=CNN Philippines|accessdate=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the DOH, the cremation of the body of the first confirmed COVID-19 death in the Philippines has been hampered by the proliferation of misinformation.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Punzalan |first1=Jamaine |title='Fake news' hampers cremation of Philippines' first novel coronavirus fatality |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/02/06/20/fake-news-hampers-cremation-of-philippines-first-novel-coronavirus-fatality |accessdate=February 15, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=February 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Affected regions==\n<!---Every LGU should have sources--->\n[[File:COVID-19 pandemic cases in the Philippines (affected primary LGUs).svg|thumb|300px|Map of the Philippines showing [[List of primary local government units of the Philippines|primary local government units]] with COVID-19 cases as confirmed by different agencies.]]\nThe following is the list of regions with confirmed COVID-19 cases. This includes component provinces and cities of each regions with confirmed COVID-19 cases as well. The list below may be inconsistent with the Department of Health's COVID-19 tracker due to several factors including:\n\n*All confirmed cases in a particular local government unit may be admitted in a health facility outside its jurisdiction.\n*Recent information may not be reflected in the DOH's COVID-19 tracker.\n\nHighly urbanized cities, and independent component cities are ''italicized'' except for component local government units of Metro Manila (National Capital Region).\n\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n*[[Metro Manila|National Capital Region]] (NCR)\n**[[Caloocan]]<ref name=\"Inquirer-CovidCaloocan\">{{cite news |last1=Galvez |first1=Daphne |title=Caloocan City COVID-19 watch: 10 confirmed cases, 139 PUIs, 319 PUMs |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1249314/caloocan-covid-cases |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 27, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n**[[Las Pi\u00f1as]]<ref name=\"ABSCBN-CovidLasPinas\">{{cite news |title=Las Pi\u00f1as records 1st COVID-19 case |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/12/20/las-pias-records-1st-covid-19-case |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |language=en}}</ref>\n**[[Manila]]<ref name=\"Inquirer-CovidManila\">{{cite news |last1=Esguerra |first1=Darryl John |title=City of Manila COVID-19 watch: 55 cases, 224 PUIs, death toll at 7 |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1250813/covid-19-cases-in-manila-now-55 |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 30, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n**[[Makati]]<ref name=\"PNAGovPH-CovidMar30\">{{cite news |last1=Montemayor |first1=Ma. Teresa |title=Covid-19 cases now 1,546; death toll climbs to 78 |url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1098265 |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=Philippine News Agency |date=March 30, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n**[[Malabon]]{{citati