{"title_page": "Margaret Findlay", "text_new": "'''Margaret Keitha Findlay''' (born 1916-2007) was an Australian architect.\n\n==Personal life==\nMargaret Keitha Findlay was born in [[Scottsdale, Tasmania]] in 1916. Then, in the 1930s, she and her family moved to [[New Norfolk, Tasmania]], where she attended school.\n\n==Career==\nUpon leaving school in New Norfolk, she became an apprentice for a Hobart-based architect, A.T. Johnston while studying architecture in [[Hobart Technical College]], which was affiliated with the [[Sydney Technical College]]. A year after finishing her apprenticeship, she worked for the [[Australian Newsprint Mills]] (ANM) Pty Ltd as an architectural draftswoman, and later after 15 months, when the ANM head architect left the company, she assumed full architectural responsibility of the New Norfolk \u201ctown-site\u201d project which was a residential suburb for workers' families in New Norfolk where she personally designed at least 60 residential houses for ANM staff members. During her architectural teaching, she got her Diploma in Town and Country Planning from the [[University of Sydney]] where she worked and graduated in 1951. She retained her position as the head of the department until she retired in 1970.\n\n==Legacy==\nFindlay was the first female in Tasmania to qualify as an associate of the [[Royal Australian Institute of Architects]] (RAIA). She passed the qualification in 1943, with one other Tasmanian architect, Charles Crawford. Findlay was also the first female to be a registered architect in Tasmania. In 1944, Findlay became the first female architect employed by the [[Public Works Department]] in Tasmania and by 1945, she was selected as the Instructor in Architectural Draftsmanship at the [[University of Sydney]], the first and only female of that position in the school.\n\nIn an interview with ''[[The Mercury (Hobart)|The Mercury]]'' in 1945, Findlay famously mentioned ''\u201cnever was there such an opportunity for girls to take up architecture, and this was their chance to. show the profession and the public what they could do.\u201d''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article26069604|title=Women Architects! Why Not!|work=The Mercury|location=Hobart|page=9|date=8 March 1945|accessdate=2015-05-15}}</ref> Not only she opened up opportunity for Tasmanian young architects to be RAIA associate, she also formulated an architecture educational system for Hobart Technical College that qualifies students to become associates of the institute and enrolled as a registered architect under Tasmanian law after undertaking the five-year course.\n\nFindlay also had a great interest in town planning and also mentioned that there is a great ''\"need for town planning\"''<ref name=\"20 January 1944\">{{cite web|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article26019965|title=New Norfolk Girl Tasmania's First Woman Architect|work=The Mercury|location=Hobart|page=7|date=20 January 1944|accessdate=2015-05-15}}</ref> Also in her interview with [[The Mercury (Hobart)]], Findlay showed her views about woman and architecture and a special emphasis on the planning of kitchens for example. ''\"I think women architects and house-wives should have some say in the planning of the new homes.\"''<ref name=\"20 January 1944\"/> Throughout her career, Findlay stressed the importance of domestic architecture to women\u2019s health and happiness.\n\nIn 2011, Findlay was entered on the Tasmanian Honour Roll posthumously for Women for her contribution towards Architecture in Australia.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20150518081953/http://womenshistory.net.au/2012/02/22/margaret-findlay/\n*http://www.dpac.tas.gov.au/divisions/csrt/programs_and_services/tasmanian_honour_roll_of_women/inductees/2011/findlay,_margaret_keitha\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Findlay, Margaret}}\n[[Category:1916 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:Australian women architects]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian architects]]\n[[Category:Tasmanian architects]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian women]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian women]]\n", "text_old": "'''Margaret Keitha Findlay''' (born 1916-2007) was an Australian architect.\n\n==Personal life==\nMargaret Keitha Findlay was born in [[Scottsdale, Tasmania]] in 1916. Then, in the 1930s, she and her family moved to [[New Norfolk, Tasmania]], where she attended school.\n\n==Career==\nUpon leaving school in New Norfolk, she became an apprentice for a Hobart-based architect, A.T. Johnston while studying architecture in [[Hobart Technical College]], which was affiliated with the [[Sydney Technical College]]. A year after finishing her apprenticeship, she worked for the [[Australian Newsprint Mills]] (ANM) Pty Ltd as an architectural draftswoman, and later after 15 months, when the ANM head architect left the company, she assumed full architectural responsibility of the New Norfolk \u201ctown-site\u201d project which was a residential suburb for workers' families in New Norfolk where she personally designed at least 60 residential houses for ANM staff members. During her architectural teaching, she got her Diploma in Town and Country Planning from the [[University of Sydney]] where she worked and graduated in 1951. She retained her position as the head of the department until she retired in 1970.\n\n==Legacy==\nFindlay was the first female in Tasmania to qualify as an associate of the [[Royal Australian Institute of Architects]] (RAIA). She passed the qualification in 1943, with one other Tasmanian architect, Charles Crawford. Findlay was also the first female to be a registered architect in Tasmania. In 1944, Findlay became the first female architect employed by the [[Public Works Department]] in Tasmania and by 1945, she was selected as the Instructor in Architectural Draftsmanship at the [[University of Sydney]], the first and only female of that position in the school.\n\nIn an interview with ''[[The Mercury (Hobart)|The Mercury]]'' in 1945, Findlay famously mentioned ''\u201cnever was there such an opportunity for girls to take up architecture, and this was their chance to. show the profession and the public what they could do.\u201d''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article26069604|title=Women Architects! Why Not!|work=The Mercury|location=Hobart|page=9|date=8 March 1945|accessdate=2015-05-15}}</ref> Not only she opened up opportunity for Tasmanian young architects to be RAIA associate, she also formulated an architecture educational system for Hobart Technical College that qualifies students to become associates of the institute and enrolled as a registered architect under Tasmanian law after undertaking the five-year course.\n\nFindlay also had a great interest in town planning and also mentioned that there is a great ''\"need for town planning\"''<ref name=\"20 January 1944\">{{cite web|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article26019965|title=New Norfolk Girl Tasmania's First Woman Architect|work=The Mercury|location=Hobart|page=7|date=20 January 1944|accessdate=2015-05-15}}</ref> Also in her interview with [[The Mercury (Hobart)]], Findlay showed her views about woman and architecture and a special emphasis on the planning of kitchens for example. ''\"I think women architects and house-wives should have some say in the planning of the new homes.\"''<ref name=\"20 January 1944\"/> Throughout her career, Findlay stressed the importance of domestic architecture to women\u2019s health and happiness.\n\nIn 2011, Findlay was entered on the Tasmanian Honour Roll posthumously for Women for her contribution towards Architecture in Australia.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20150518081953/http://womenshistory.net.au/2012/02/22/margaret-findlay/\n*http://www.dpac.tas.gov.au/divisions/csrt/programs_and_services/tasmanian_honour_roll_of_women/inductees/2011/findlay,_margaret_keitha\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Findlay, Margaret}}\n[[Category:1916 births]]\n[[Category:2017 deaths]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:Australian women architects]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian architects]]\n[[Category:Tasmanian architects]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian women]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian women]]\n", "name_user": "Chris.sherlock", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Margaret_Findlay"}
{"title_page": "Emmanuel (spirit)", "text_new": "{{Expand Portuguese|Emmanuel (esp\u00edrito)|date=April 2020}}\n[[File:Emmanuel.3.jpg|250px|right|thumb|Drawing of Emmanuel by Delpino Filho, 1940s]] \n'''Emmanuel''' is, according to Brazilian [[mediumship|medium]] [[Chico Xavier]], an enlightened spirit who guided him during most of his life. Xavier attributed many of his [[psychography|psychographic works]] to Emmanuel, which includes tens of books.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/folha/cotidiano/ult95u53837.shtml|title=Folha Online - Cotidiano - Confira as principais obras psicografadas de Chico Xavier - 30/06/2002|accessdate=21 February 2018|work=www1.folha.uol.com.br|language=Portuguese}}</ref> \n\nAccording to the biography ''As Vidas de Chico Xavier'' by Marcel Souto Maior, Xavier met Emmanuel for the first time in 1931 while praying on the shade of a tree by a lake.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|title=As Vidas de Chico Xavier|last=Souto Maior|first=Marcel|publisher=Leya Brasil}}</ref> Emmanuel would appear to Xavier frequently, including in many important events throughout his life, to guide him in the mission of being a mediunic writer.  \n\nEmmanuel is said to have had many incarnations on Earth (in accordance to the [[Spiritism|Spritist]] belief in [[reincarnation]]). Those included the Roman consul [[Publius Cornelius Lentulus Sura]] (114\u201362 BC), his purported great-grandson [[Publius Lentulus]], the Byzantine archbishop [[Nestorius]] (386\u2013450), the Frankish bishop [[Saint Remigius]] (437\u2013533), the Portuguese Jesuit priest [[Manuel da N\u00f3brega]] (1517\u20131570), and a recent incarnation in Brazil in the 20th century.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite book|title=Deus Conosco|last=Joviano|first=Wanda|publisher=Vinha de Luz|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{ref-list}}\n\n[[Category:Deities and spirits]]\n[[Category:Spiritism]]\n", "text_old": "{{Expand Portuguese|Emmanuel (esp\u00edrito)|date=April 2020}}\n[[File:Emmanuel.3.jpg|250px|right|thumb|Drawing of Emmanuel by Delpino Filho, 1940s]] \n'''Emmanuel''' is, according to Brazilian [[medium]] [[Chico Xavier]], an enlightened spirit who guided him during most of his life. Xavier attributed many of his [[psychography|psychographic works]] to Emmanuel, which includes tens of books.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/folha/cotidiano/ult95u53837.shtml|title=Folha Online - Cotidiano - Confira as principais obras psicografadas de Chico Xavier - 30/06/2002|accessdate=21 February 2018|work=www1.folha.uol.com.br|language=Portuguese}}</ref> \n\nAccording to the biography ''As Vidas de Chico Xavier'' by Marcel Souto Maior, Xavier met Emmanuel for the first time in 1931 while praying on the shade of a tree by a lake.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|title=As Vidas de Chico Xavier|last=Souto Maior|first=Marcel|publisher=Leya Brasil}}</ref> Emmanuel would appear to Xavier frequently, including in many important events throughout his life, to guide him in the mission of being a mediunic writer.  \n\nEmmanuel is said to have had many incarnations on Earth (in accordance to the [[Spiritism|Spritist]] belief in [[reincarnation]]). Those included the Roman consul [[Publius Cornelius Lentulus Sura]] (114\u201362 BC), his purported great-grandson [[Publius Lentulus]], the Byzantine archbishop [[Nestorius]] (386\u2013450), the Frankish bishop [[Saint Remigius]] (437\u2013533), the Portuguese Jesuit priest [[Manuel da N\u00f3brega]] (1517\u20131570), and a recent incarnation in Brazil in the 20th century.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite book|title=Deus Conosco|last=Joviano|first=Wanda|publisher=Vinha de Luz|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{ref-list}}\n\n[[Category:Deities and spirits]]\n[[Category:Spiritism]]\n", "name_user": "GoingBatty", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Repaired 1 link to disambiguation page -(You can help)-Medium", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emmanuel_(spirit)"}
{"title_page": "Kargil Review Committee", "text_new": "{{Use Indian English|date=December 2018}}\n\nThe '''Kargil Review Committee''' ('''KRC''') was set up by the [[Government of India]] on 29 July 1999, three days after the end of the [[Kargil War]]. The committee was set up \"to examine the sequence of events and make recommendations for the future\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.indiamart.com/news-analysis/kargil-subrahmanyam--6975.html|title=Kargil : Subrahmanyam Committee's Report|work=Indian News|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061019174555/http://news.indiamart.com/news-analysis/kargil-subrahmanyam--6975.html|archivedate=19 October 2006|url-status=dead|accessdate=20 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.satp.org/satporgtp/publication/idr/vol_15(2)/air_marshal_bd_jayal_retd.htm|title=The Kargil Review Committee Report A Mindset Frozen in 1962 Era|last=Jayal|first=BD|website=South Asia Terrorism Portal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171008011241/http://www.satp.org/satporgtp/publication/idr/vol_15(2)/air_marshal_bd_jayal_retd.htm|archive-date=2017-10-08|url-status=live|access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nuclearweaponarchive.org/India/KargilRCA.html|title=Executive Summary of the Kargil Committee Report|website=nuclearweaponarchive.org|access-date=2018-12-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704161325/http://nuclearweaponarchive.org/India/KargilRCA.html|archive-date=2018-07-04|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:Kargil.map.gif|thumb|Site of the conflict|alt=|150x150px]]\n[[File:The Prime Minister Shri Atal Bihari Vajpayee delivering his speech at the 12th SAARC Summit in Islamabad, Pakistan on January 4, 2004 (1) (cropped).jpg|thumb|200x200px|The report was submitted to the Prime Minister of India, [[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]], on 7 January 2000]]\nOver a hundred senior military, civil service and intelligence officials, politicians, including former prime ministers, diplomats and journalists were interviewed by the committee over a period of five months. The report was completed on 15 December 1999 and was tabled in the Parliament of India on 23 February 2000.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.indiandefencereview.com/news/downhill-from-kargil/|title=Downhill from Kargil|last=Menon|first=Air Marshal Narayan|website=Indian Defence Review|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180423235154/http://www.indiandefencereview.com/news/downhill-from-kargil/|archive-date=2018-04-23|url-status=live|access-date=2018-12-06}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Bedi|first=Rahul|date=22-28 April 2000|title=Kargil Report: More Questions Raised than Answered|journal=Economic and Political Weekly|volume=35|issue=17|pages=1429\u20131431|df=|jstor=4409195}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://frontline.thehindu.com/static/html/fl1702/17020310.htm|title=A committee and some questions: A first-person account with regard to the Kargil Review Committee Report and its implications.|last=Swami|first=Praveen|date=22 January 2000|website=Frontline|publisher=The Hindu Group|access-date=2018-12-06}}</ref> Certain parts of the final KRC report, such as the findings, have remained confidential. \n\nThe Committee found numerous flaws on multiple level of intelligence collection, operational strategies and procedural sharing of data.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|url=https://idsa.in/system/files/book/book_IntellegenceReform.pdf|title=A Case for Intelligence Reforms in India|last=Institute for Defence Studies and Analyses Task Force Report|publisher=Institute for Defence Studies and Analyses|year=2012|isbn=9789382169031|location=New Delhi|pages=25,26|access-date=2018-12-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181221041613/https://idsa.in/system/files/book/book_IntellegenceReform.pdf|archive-date=2018-12-21|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.claws.in/images/journals_doc/1400824637Report%20of%20the%20Kargil%20Review%20Committee%20%20CJ%20SSummer%202009.pdf|title=Report of the Kargil Review Committee: An Appraisal (Interview of Mr K Subrahmanyam, Chairman of the Kargil Review Committee)|last=Kanwal|first=Gurmeet|last2=Chansoria|first2=Monika|date=2009|website=Centre for Land Warfare Studies|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160711090619/http://www.claws.in/images/journals_doc/1400824637Report%20of%20the%20Kargil%20Review%20Committee%20%20CJ%20SSummer%202009.pdf|archive-date=2016-07-11|url-status=live|access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref> As per the KRC's recommendations, a Group of Ministers (GoM) and several task forces were set up to do a complete review of the Indian security system. The GoM subsequently conducted a comprehensive review of the entire security apparatus. This became the first review of its kind in independent India's history to be made public, although in the interests of national security, the government initially redacted several parts. The recommendations of the KRC report and the GoM report led to far-reaching changes in the Indian security apparatus.\n\n== Background ==\nThe Kargil Review Committee laid out the context of the report. They noted that the national security system in the country had seen very little changes since the 52-year-old framework outlined by [[Hastings Ismay, 1st Baron Ismay|Hastings Ismay]] and recommended by [[Louis Mountbatten, 1st Earl Mountbatten of Burma|Louis Mountbatten]]. In these 52&nbsp;years, India had undergone the [[Sino-Indian War]], the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1965]], and the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1971]], as well as increased nuclear danger, the [[Cold War]], persistence of the hybrid war in Kashmir for more than ten years, and a revolution in military affairs elsewhere.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.satp.org/satporgtp/publication/idr/vol_15(1)/real_admiral_satyindra_singh.html|title=The Kargil Review Committee Report: Much to Learn and Implement|last=Singh|first=Satyindra|website=South Asia Terrorism Portal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181214214045/http://www.satp.org/satporgtp/publication/idr/vol_15(1)/real_admiral_satyindra_singh.html|archive-date=2018-12-14|url-status=live|access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref>\n\nIndia tried major defence reforms following the Sino-Indian War in 1962, but these did not address national security in a holistic way. They decided to assess defence needs on a five-year basis, leading to the First Defence Plan. The [[Ministry of Defence (India)|Ministry of Defence]] and, subsequently the [[Department of Defence Production (India)|Department of Defence Production]], [[Defence Research and Development Organisation]] and services headquarters, set up planning cells and units. A [[Joint Intelligence Committee (India)|Joint Intelligence Committee]] was also formed. The Directorate General of Defence Planning Staff, composed of officers of various services, was formed to synergise defence planning under the Chiefs of Staff Committee in 1986.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.claws.in/images/journals_doc/1394685259Gurmeet%20Kanwal%20CJ%20Summer%202013.pdf|title=Defence Reforms: Managing Threats and Challenges to National Security|last=Gurmeet|first=Kanwal|date=2013|website=Centre for Land Warfare Studies|publisher=CLAWS Journal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160711030739/http://www.claws.in/images/journals_doc/1394685259Gurmeet%20Kanwal%20CJ%20Summer%202013.pdf|archive-date=2016-07-11|url-status=live|access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref>\n\n== Members ==\n[[File:Brajesh Mishra.jpg|thumb|182x182px|Brajesh Mishra, the national security advisor at the time.]]\nThe committee consisted of:\n\n* [[K. Subrahmanyam]] (chairperson), retired [[Indian Administrative Service]] officer and head of the [[National Security Advisory Board|National Security Council Advisory Board]] (NSCAB) \n*K. K. Hazari, former Vice Chief of the Army Staff\n* [[B. G. Verghese|B.G. Verghese]], member National Security Council Advisory Board\n* Satish Chandra, secretary of the [[National Security Council (India)|National Security Council Secretariat]] and member-secretary of KRC \n\n[[Brajesh Mishra]], the national security advisor at the time, assisted in the establishment of the Kargil Review Committee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://idsa.in/idsacomments/BrajeshMishrasLegacytoNationalSecurityandDiplomacy_agupta_300912|title=Brajesh Mishra's Legacy to National Security and Diplomacy {{!}} Institute for Defence Studies and Analyses|website=idsa.in|access-date=2018-12-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620153419/https://idsa.in/idsacomments/BrajeshMishrasLegacytoNationalSecurityandDiplomacy_agupta_300912|archive-date=2018-06-20|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Timeline ==\n\n* 3 May 1999: A Pakistani intrusion in Kargil is reported by local shepherds.\n* 24 July 1999: The Union cabinet of India gathers a committee to look into the Kargil War.\n* 26 July 1999: The Kargil War officially comes to an end and the Indian Army announces complete eviction of Pakistani intruders.\n* 29 July 1999: Kargil Review Committee (KRC) is set up. \n* 15 December 1999: KRC Report finalised. \n* 7 January 2000: The committee submits its report to the prime minister, [[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]], on 7 January 2000\n* 23 February 2000: KRC Report tables in Parliament.<ref name=\":0\" />\n* 17 April 2000: The government establishes a Group of Ministers (GoM) to comprehensively scrutinise the national security system in its totality and \"in particular to consider the recommendations of the Kargil Review Committee and formulate specific proposals for implementation\".<ref>Prof. A. Lakshmisagar, H. K. Javare Gowda, Krishna Kumar Birla (19 April 2001)'''.''' ''[http://rsdebate.nic.in/rsdebate56/handle/123456789/13786?viewItem=browse Rajya Sabha Official Debates: Report of the Kargil Review Committee].'' Parliament of India.</ref>\n* 26 February 2001: The GoM finalises its report.\n\n== Kargil Review Committee report ==\n\nThe Kargil Review Committee was initially given a period of three months to submit the report. The deadline was later extended to 15 December 1999, giving the committee five months instead. In the report, the committee pointed out that they would not assign any individual blame.<ref name=\":8\">Kargil Review Committee (July 2000). ''[https://www.scribd.com/doc/152396717/Kargil-Review-Committee-Report-1999 From Surprise To Reckoning: The Kargil Review Committee Report]''. New Delhi. Sage Publications. {{ISBN|9780761994664}}</ref> The report's scope was to <blockquote>review the events leading up to the Pakistani aggression in the Kargil District of Ladakh in Jammu & Kashmir; and to recommend such measures as are considered necessary to safeguard national security against such armed intrusions.</blockquote>Over a hundred senior military, civil service and intelligence officials, politicians, including former prime ministers, diplomats and journalists were interviewed.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|last=Bedi|first=Rahul|date=22-28 April 2000|title=Kargil Report: More Questions Raised than Answered|journal=Economic and Political Weekly|volume=35|issue=17|pages=1429\u20131431|df=|jstor=4409195}}</ref> Unlike previous reports of a similar nature, this report was published and made publicly available, though some parts were blanked.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hinduonnet.com/fline/fl1722/17220240.htm|title=The Kargil Story|work=The Hindu|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20011220052833/http://www.hinduonnet.com/fline/fl1722/17220240.htm|archive-date=20 December 2001|url-status=dead|accessdate=20 October 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe second and third chapters of the report are devoted to a historical background of the events leading up to the war, covering issues such as the Simla Agreement, Pakistan's attempts at internationalising the Kashmir issue, the \"Rajiv-Benazir\" interlude, Siachen, the Indo-Pak dialogue in general and the impact of the proxy war on the Indian Army. Chapter&nbsp;5 reconstructs the Kargil intrusion. In Chapter&nbsp;6, the committee outlines the role and function of intelligence agencies. Chapters&nbsp;7 and 8 discusses and analyses intelligence on the Kargil issue, as well as the army's subsequent response. Chapter&nbsp;13 and&nbsp;14 summarises the findings and offers further recommendations.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n=== Findings ===\n[[File:Pervez Musharraf - World Economic Forum Annual Meeting Davos 2008 numb2.jpg|thumb|225x225px|[[General Pervez Musharraf]]]]\nChapter&nbsp;13 of the report outlines the findings of the committee. It clearly states that the intrusion had been a surprise for the Indian government. After elaborating on the history of the \"Kargil plan\", the committee discusses the government's, army's, and media's respective responses. They then outline the intelligence findings, elaborating on the role of the [[Research and Analysis Wing]] (R&AW), [[Intelligence Bureau (India)|Intelligence Bureau]] and the military intelligence collection just prior to the war, as well as the lack of inter-agency coordination. The Kargil Review Committee found R&AW\u2018s human intelligence to be weak,<ref name=\":7\" /> but Chapter&nbsp;14 also praises the interception of telephone conversations of [[Pervez Musharraf|Pervej Musharraf]] in China. The KRC report also acknowledges the work of the [[Aviation Research Centre]] of R&AW, which produced aerial intelligence after the intrusion's detection. The report goes into detail regarding the nuclear, technological and media effects of the incident.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nThe report also mentions that the Kargil War could perhaps have been avoided if troops had been stationed there, but also notes that had troops been stationed there all year round and the conflict had still occurred, it would have resulted in huge costs \"and enabled [[Bleed India with a Thousand Cuts|Pakistan to bleed India]].\"<ref name=\":12\" />\n\n=== Recommendations ===\nThe KRC suggested a \"thorough review of the national security system in its entirety\", conducted by a credible body of experts. It also suggested that various task forces should also review specific parts of the system, including: \n\n*[[National Security Council (India)|National Security Council]]\n* Intelligence\n* Counter-terrorist operations\n* Border Management\n* Defence Budget and Modernisation\n* National Security Management and Apex Decision Making\n* India's Nuclear Policy\n* Media Relations and Information\n* Technology\n* Civil\u2013Military Liaison\n* Declaratory Policy for LOC\n\n== Group of Ministers ==\nFollowing the Kargil Review Committee report, a Group of Ministers (GoM) was set up by the Cabinet Committee on Security (CCS) on 17{{Nbsp}}April 2000 to consider the recommendations in the Kargil Review Committee. The GoM consisted of the ministers of home affairs, defence, external affairs and finance. [[Brajesh Mishra]], the [[National Security Advisor (India)|National Security Advisor]], was also assigned as a special guest to the meetings of the GoM and the [[Cabinet Secretariat (India)|Cabinet Secretariat]] provided help to the group.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vifindia.org/sites/default/files/GoM%20Report%20on%20National%20Security.pdf|title=GoM Report on National Security, Chapter 1. Appointment, Approach and Methodology.|website=[[Vivekananda International Foundation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171215090619/http://www.vifindia.org/sites/default/files/GoM%20Report%20on%20National%20Security.pdf|archive-date=2017-12-15|url-status=live|access-date=2018-12-06}}</ref>\n\nThe GoM established task forces, as suggested in the KRC report:\n\n* Task Force on Intelligence Apparatus: [[Girish Chandra Saxena|G. C. Saxena]], a retired [[Indian Police Service]] officer, the [[List of governors of Jammu and Kashmir|Jammu and Kashmir governor]] at the time and a former [[Research and Analysis Wing|RAW]] chief\n* Task Force on Internal Security: [[Narinder Nath Vohra|N. N. Vohra]], a retired Indian Administrative Service officer and [[Principal Secretary to the Prime Minister of India]], [[Defence Secretary (India)|Defence Secretary]] and [[Home Secretary (India)|Home Secretary]]\n* Task Force on Border Management: Madhav Godbole, retired Indian Administrative Service officer and former Home Secretary\n* Task Force on Management of Defence: [[Arun Singh (politician, born 1944)|Arun Singh]], advisor in the Ministry of External Affairs and former Minister of State for Defence\n\nThe GoM came out with its own report \"Reforming the National Security System\".<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://idsa.in/monograph/status-of-jointness-in-indian-security-apparatus|title=Status Of Jointness In Indian Security Apparatus {{!}} Institute for Defence Studies and Analyses|last=Rana|first=Vijai Singh|date=May 2016|website=[[Institute for Defence Studies and Analyses]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181227045824/https://idsa.in/monograph/status-of-jointness-in-indian-security-apparatus|archive-date=2018-12-27|url-status=live|access-date=2018-12-06}}</ref>  It was submitted to Prime Minister Vajpayee on 26 February 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pibarchive.nic.in/archive/releases98/lyr2001/rmay2001/23052001/r2305200110.html|title='Group of Ministers' Report on \"Reforming the National Security System\"|date=23 May 2001|website=Press Information Bureau, India|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181227040738/http://pibarchive.nic.in/archive/releases98/lyr2001/rmay2001/23052001/r2305200110.html|archive-date=2018-12-27|url-status=live|access-date=2018-12-06}}</ref>\n\n== Implementation and impact ==\nAmong the recommendations in the Kargil Review Committee report, the following have been implemented:\n\n* A thorough review of the national security system in India, which was done by the GoM \n* A full-time [[National Security Advisor (India)|National Security Advisor]] \n* Improved aerial surveillance, which has been accomplished by setting up [[RISAT|RISAT]]<nowiki/> satellites and inducting UAVs.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|title=CHAPTER V - Higher Defense Organisation in India Need for Reforms|journal = University|last=Ghosh|first=AK|date=2004-02-09|hdl = 10603/183362}}</ref>\n* A centralised communication and electronic intelligence agency, which resulted in the establishment of the [[National Technical Research Organisation]] in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indiandefencereview.com/spotlights/ntro-indias-technical-intelligence-agency/|title=NTRO: India's Technical Intelligence Agency|last=Bedi|first=RS|date=23 April 2015|website=Indian Defence Review|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180420223424/http://www.indiandefencereview.com/spotlights/ntro-indias-technical-intelligence-agency/|archive-date=2018-04-20|url-status=live|access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref>\n* A [[Defence Intelligence Agency (India)|Defence Intelligence Agency]] \n* The establishment of think tanks, which has resulted in organizations like the Centre for Joint Warfare Studies.<ref name=\":6\" />\n* The reduction of the the age profile in the army<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nThe Kargil Review Committee also recommended that the government find ways to reduce the pension expenditure, which has not yet been implemented. \n\nFrom among the recommendations in the GoM report, the following have been implemented: \n\n* The creation of the post for a [[Chief of Defence Staff (India)|Chief of Defence Staff]], which was accepted by the [[Cabinet Committee on Security]] and was implemented in December 2019. \n* The creation of additional tri-services organisations; in particular, the [[Integrated Defence Staff]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ids.nic.in/vision.php|title=Integrated Defence Staff - Vision and History|website=Integrated Defence Staff}}</ref> the [[Andaman and Nicobar Command]], the [[Nuclear Command Authority (India)|Nuclear Command Authority]], [[Strategic Forces Command]], the [[Department of Ex-servicemen Welfare]], the [[Defence Technology Council]] and the [[Defence Acquisition Council]] have been established.<ref name=\":6\" />\n* An identity card, which has been implemented as the [[Aadhaar]] card.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/aadhaar-journey-kargil-supreme-court-1349503-2018-09-26|title=Tracing the Aadhaar journey: From Kargil to Supreme Court|last=DelhiSeptember 26|first=Prabhash K. Dutta New|last2=September 26|first2=2018UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2018-12-12|last3=Ist|first3=2018 13:25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181206102528/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/aadhaar-journey-kargil-supreme-court-1349503-2018-09-26|archive-date=2018-12-06|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Aftermath ==\nFollowing the Kargil Review Committee, Group of Ministers and the task forces, other committees have been formed to follow up on the Kargil Review Committee recommendations and further assess national security. These groups include the [[Standing Committee on Defence (India)|Standing Committee on Defence]] in 2007''',''' Naresh Chandra task force<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/13-years-on-Kargil-panel-report-still-ignored/articleshow/15150628.cms|title=13 years on, Kargil panel report still ignored - Times of India|website=The Times of India|access-date=2018-12-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190106110412/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/13-years-on-Kargil-panel-report-still-ignored/articleshow/15150628.cms|archive-date=2019-01-06|url-status=live}}</ref> in 2011 and the Ravindra Gupta task force in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indiandefencereview.com/news/restructuring-defence-reforms-for-national-security/|title=Restructuring Defence Reforms for National Security|last=Kanwal|first=Gurmeet|date=31 December 2015|website=Indian Defence Review|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419161303/http://www.indiandefencereview.com/news/restructuring-defence-reforms-for-national-security/|archive-date=2018-04-19|url-status=live|access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref>\n\n=== Standing Committee on Defence review ===\nOn July&nbsp;2007, the Standing Committee on Defence and the Ministry of Defence presented a report titled \"Review of Implementation Status of Group of Ministers (GoMs) Report on Reforming National Security System in Pursuance to Kargil Review Committee Report\u2014A Special Reference to Management of Defence\" as a follow up the Kargil Review Committee report and the Group of Minister report.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://idsa.in/system/files/Standing%20Committee%20on%20Defence%2022nd%20Report%202006%202007.pdf|title=Review of Implementation Status of Group of Ministers (GoMs) Report on Reforming National Security System in Pursuance to Kargil Review Committee Report\u2014A Special Reference to Management of Defence|last=Standing Committee on Defence, Ministry of Defence, 14th Lok Sabha|date=July 2007|website=Institute for Defence Studies and Analyses|publisher=Lok Sabha Secretariat|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021043402/https://idsa.in/system/files/Standing%20Committee%20on%20Defence%2022nd%20Report%202006%202007.pdf|archive-date=21 October 2012|url-status=|access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref>\n[[File:Naresh Chandra July 2012.jpg|thumb|Naresh Chandra|alt=|150x150px]]\n\n=== Naresh Chandra task force ===\nIn 2011, the Naresh Chandra task force reviewed the recommendations of the Kargil Review Committee, assessed the implementation and accordingly suggested new changes needed related to national security.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rsis.edu.sg/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/PR140301_The_Unending_Quest_to_Reform_India_National_Security_System.pdf|title=Policy Report: The Unending Quest to Reform India National Security System|last=Joshi|first=Manoj|date=March 2014|website=S. Rajaratnam School of International Studies (RSIS) (www.rsis.edu.sg)|access-date=2018-12-06}}</ref> The task force was led by [[Naresh Chandra]] and comprised thirteen other members. The committee submitted its report on 23&nbsp;May&nbsp;2012.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nAccording to the task force many of the main recommendations of the Kargil Review Committee have not been implemented, such as recommendations related to defence procurement. The task force further suggested framing a National Security Doctrine ([[National Security Strategy (India)|National Security Strategy]]) among other things.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/diplomacy/india-pakistan-kargil-war-lessons|title=Why Is India Still Ignoring Lessons Learnt From the Kargil War?|website=The Wire|access-date=2018-12-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181221041323/https://thewire.in/diplomacy/india-pakistan-kargil-war-lessons|archive-date=2018-12-21|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* Kargil Review Committee (July 2000). ''[https://www.scribd.com/doc/152396717/Kargil-Review-Committee-Report-1999 From Surprise To Reckoning: The Kargil Review Committee Report]''. New Delhi. Sage Publications. {{ISBN|9780761994664}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20171215090619/https://www.vifindia.org/sites/default/files/GoM%20Report%20on%20National%20Security.pdf ''Report of the Group of Ministers on National Security''], Retrieved from [https://www.vifindia.org/sites/default/files/GoM%20Report%20on%20National%20Security.pdf original] from Vivekananda International Foundation on 12 December 2018.\n*Standing Committee on Defence (2006 - 2007), Ministry of Defence, 14th Lok Sabha (July 2007). ''\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20121021043402/https://idsa.in/system/files/Standing%20Committee%20on%20Defence%2022nd%20Report%202006%202007.pdf Twenty-Second Report. Review of Implementation Status of Group of Ministers (GoMs) Report on Reforming National Security System in Pursuance to Kargil Review Committee Report\u2014A Special Reference to Management of Defence]\"'' Lok Sabha Secretariat. New Delhi. Archived from the [https://idsa.in/system/files/Standing%20Committee%20on%20Defence%2022nd%20Report%202006%202007.pdf original] on 21 October 2012. Retrieved on 12 December 2018 from Institute for Defence Studies and Analyses.\n*Anit Mukherjee (March 2011), [https://idsa.in/system/files/OP_defencereform.pdf ''Failing to Deliver: Post-Crises Defence Reforms in India, 1998-2010.''] Institute for Defence Studies and Analyses (IDSA), New Delhi. {{ISBN|81-86019-88-X}}\n*(25 February 2000). [http://nuclearweaponarchive.org/India/KargilRCA.html Kargil Review Committee report, Executive Summary] Retrieved from nuclearweaponarchive.org, 12 December 2018.\n\n[[Category:Kargil War]]\n[[Category:1999 establishments in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Indian English|date=December 2018}}\n\nThe '''Kargil Review Committee''' ('''KRC''') was set up by the [[Government of India]] on 29 July 1999, three days after the end of the [[Kargil War]]. The committee was set up \"to examine the sequence of events and make recommendations for the future\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.indiamart.com/news-analysis/kargil-subrahmanyam--6975.html|title=Kargil : Subrahmanyam Committee's Report|work=Indian News|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061019174555/http://news.indiamart.com/news-analysis/kargil-subrahmanyam--6975.html|archivedate=19 October 2006|url-status=dead|accessdate=20 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.satp.org/satporgtp/publication/idr/vol_15(2)/air_marshal_bd_jayal_retd.htm|title=The Kargil Review Committee Report A Mindset Frozen in 1962 Era|last=Jayal|first=BD|website=South Asia Terrorism Portal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171008011241/http://www.satp.org/satporgtp/publication/idr/vol_15(2)/air_marshal_bd_jayal_retd.htm|archive-date=2017-10-08|url-status=live|access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nuclearweaponarchive.org/India/KargilRCA.html|title=Executive Summary of the Kargil Committee Report|website=nuclearweaponarchive.org|access-date=2018-12-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704161325/http://nuclearweaponarchive.org/India/KargilRCA.html|archive-date=2018-07-04|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:Kargil.map.gif|thumb|Site of the conflict|alt=|150x150px]]\n[[File:The Prime Minister Shri Atal Bihari Vajpayee delivering his speech at the 12th SAARC Summit in Islamabad, Pakistan on January 4, 2004 (1) (cropped).jpg|thumb|200x200px|The report was submitted to the Prime Minister of India, [[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]], on 7 January 2000]]\nOver a hundred senior military, civil service and intelligence officials, politicians, including former prime ministers, diplomats and journalists were interviewed by the committee over a period of five months. The report was completed on 15 December 1999 and was tabled in the Parliament of India on 23 February 2000.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.indiandefencereview.com/news/downhill-from-kargil/|title=Downhill from Kargil|last=Menon|first=Air Marshal Narayan|website=Indian Defence Review|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180423235154/http://www.indiandefencereview.com/news/downhill-from-kargil/|archive-date=2018-04-23|url-status=live|access-date=2018-12-06}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Bedi|first=Rahul|date=22-28 April 2000|title=Kargil Report: More Questions Raised than Answered|journal=Economic and Political Weekly|volume=35|issue=17|pages=1429\u20131431|df=|jstor=4409195}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://frontline.thehindu.com/static/html/fl1702/17020310.htm|title=A committee and some questions: A first-person account with regard to the Kargil Review Committee Report and its implications.|last=Swami|first=Praveen|date=22 January 2000|website=Frontline|publisher=The Hindu Group|access-date=2018-12-06}}</ref> Certain parts of the final KRC report, such as the findings, have remained confidential. \n\nThe Committee found numerous flaws on multiple level of intelligence collection, operational strategies and procedural sharing of data.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|url=https://idsa.in/system/files/book/book_IntellegenceReform.pdf|title=A Case for Intelligence Reforms in India|last=Institute for Defence Studies and Analyses Task Force Report|publisher=Institute for Defence Studies and Analyses|year=2012|isbn=9789382169031|location=New Delhi|pages=25,26|access-date=2018-12-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181221041613/https://idsa.in/system/files/book/book_IntellegenceReform.pdf|archive-date=2018-12-21|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.claws.in/images/journals_doc/1400824637Report%20of%20the%20Kargil%20Review%20Committee%20%20CJ%20SSummer%202009.pdf|title=Report of the Kargil Review Committee: An Appraisal (Interview of Mr K Subrahmanyam, Chairman of the Kargil Review Committee)|last=Kanwal|first=Gurmeet|last2=Chansoria|first2=Monika|date=2009|website=Centre for Land Warfare Studies|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160711090619/http://www.claws.in/images/journals_doc/1400824637Report%20of%20the%20Kargil%20Review%20Committee%20%20CJ%20SSummer%202009.pdf|archive-date=2016-07-11|url-status=live|access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref> As per the KRC's recommendations, a Group of Ministers (GoM) and several task forces were set up to do a complete review of the Indian security system. The GoM subsequently conducted a comprehensive review of the entire security apparatus. This became the first review of its kind in independent India's history to be made public, although in the interests of national security, the government initially redacted several parts. The recommendations of the KRC report and the GoM report led to far-reaching changes in the Indian security apparatus.\n\n== Background ==\nThe Kargil Review Committee laid out the context of the report. They noted that the national security system in the country had seen very little changes since the 52-year-old framework outlined by [[Hastings Ismay, 1st Baron Ismay|Hastings Ismay]] and recommended by [[Louis Mountbatten, 1st Earl Mountbatten of Burma|Louis Mountbatten]]. In these 52&nbsp;years, India had undergone the [[Sino-Indian War]], the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1965]], and the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1971]], as well as increased nuclear danger, the [[Cold War]], persistence of the hybrid war in Kashmir for more than ten years, and a revolution in military affairs elsewhere.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.satp.org/satporgtp/publication/idr/vol_15(1)/real_admiral_satyindra_singh.html|title=The Kargil Review Committee Report: Much to Learn and Implement|last=Singh|first=Satyindra|website=South Asia Terrorism Portal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181214214045/http://www.satp.org/satporgtp/publication/idr/vol_15(1)/real_admiral_satyindra_singh.html|archive-date=2018-12-14|url-status=live|access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref>\n\nIndia tried major defence reforms following the Sino-Indian War in 1962, but these did not address national security in a holistic way. They decided to assess defence needs on a five-year basis, leading to the First Defence Plan. The [[Ministry of Defence (India)|Ministry of Defence]] and, subsequently the [[Department of Defence Production (India)|Department of Defence Production]], [[Defence Research and Development Organisation]] and services headquarters, set up planning cells and units. A [[Joint Intelligence Committee (India)|Joint Intelligence Committee]] was also formed. The Directorate General of Defence Planning Staff, composed of officers of various services, was formed to synergise defence planning under the Chiefs of Staff Committee in 1986.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.claws.in/images/journals_doc/1394685259Gurmeet%20Kanwal%20CJ%20Summer%202013.pdf|title=Defence Reforms: Managing Threats and Challenges to National Security|last=Gurmeet|first=Kanwal|date=2013|website=Centre for Land Warfare Studies|publisher=CLAWS Journal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160711030739/http://www.claws.in/images/journals_doc/1394685259Gurmeet%20Kanwal%20CJ%20Summer%202013.pdf|archive-date=2016-07-11|url-status=live|access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref>\n\n== Members ==\n[[File:Brajesh Mishra.jpg|thumb|182x182px|Brajesh Mishra, the national security advisor at the time.]]\nThe committee consisted of:\n\n* [[K. Subrahmanyam]] (chairperson), retired [[Indian Administrative Service]] officer and head of the [[National Security Advisory Board|National Security Council Advisory Board]] (NSCAB) \n*K. K. Hazari, former Vice Chief of the Army Staff\n* [[B. G. Verghese|B.G. Verghese]], member National Security Council Advisory Board\n* Satish Chandra, secretary of the [[National Security Council (India)|National Security Council Secretariat]] and member-secretary of KRC \n\n[[Brajesh Mishra]], the national security advisor at the time, assisted in the establishment of the Kargil Review Committee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://idsa.in/idsacomments/BrajeshMishrasLegacytoNationalSecurityandDiplomacy_agupta_300912|title=Brajesh Mishra's Legacy to National Security and Diplomacy {{!}} Institute for Defence Studies and Analyses|website=idsa.in|access-date=2018-12-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620153419/https://idsa.in/idsacomments/BrajeshMishrasLegacytoNationalSecurityandDiplomacy_agupta_300912|archive-date=2018-06-20|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Timeline ==\n\n* 3 May 1999: A Pakistani intrusion in Kargil is reported by local shepherds.\n* 24 July 1999: The Union cabinet of India gathers a committee to look into the Kargil War.\n* 26 July 1999: The Kargil War officially comes to an end and the Indian Army announces complete eviction of Pakistani intruders.\n* 29 July 1999: Kargil Review Committee (KRC) is set up. \n* 15 December 1999: KRC Report finalised. \n* 7 January 2000: The committee submits its report to the prime minister, [[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]], on 7 January 2000\n* 23 February 2000: KRC Report tables in Parliament.<ref name=\":0\" />\n* 17 April 2000: The government establishes a Group of Ministers (GoM) to comprehensively scrutinise the national security system in its totality and \"in particular to consider the recommendations of the Kargil Review Committee and formulate specific proposals for implementation\".<ref>Prof. A. Lakshmisagar, H. K. Javare Gowda, Krishna Kumar Birla (19 April 2001)'''.''' ''[http://rsdebate.nic.in/rsdebate56/handle/123456789/13786?viewItem=browse Rajya Sabha Official Debates: Report of the Kargil Review Committee].'' Parliament of India.</ref>\n* 26 February 2001: The GoM finalises its report.\n\n== Kargil Review Committee report ==\n\nThe Kargil Review Committee was initially given a period of three months to submit the report. The deadline was later extended to 15 December 1999, giving the committee five months instead. In the report, the committee pointed out that they would not assign any individual blame.<ref name=\":8\">Kargil Review Committee (July 2000). ''[https://www.scribd.com/doc/152396717/Kargil-Review-Committee-Report-1999 From Surprise To Reckoning: The Kargil Review Committee Report]''. New Delhi. Sage Publications. {{ISBN|9780761994664}}</ref> The report's scope was to <blockquote>review the events leading up to the Pakistani aggression in the Kargil District of Ladakh in Jammu & Kashmir; and to recommend such measures as are considered necessary to safeguard national security against such armed intrusions.</blockquote>Over a hundred senior military, civil service and intelligence officials, politicians, including former prime ministers, diplomats and journalists were interviewed.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|last=Bedi|first=Rahul|date=22-28 April 2000|title=Kargil Report: More Questions Raised than Answered|journal=Economic and Political Weekly|volume=35|issue=17|pages=1429\u20131431|df=|jstor=4409195}}</ref> Unlike previous reports of a similar nature, this report was published and made publicly available, though some parts were blanked.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hinduonnet.com/fline/fl1722/17220240.htm|title=The Kargil Story|work=The Hindu|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20011220052833/http://www.hinduonnet.com/fline/fl1722/17220240.htm|archive-date=20 December 2001|url-status=dead|accessdate=20 October 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe second and third chapters of the report are devoted to a historical background of the events leading up to the war, covering issues such as the Simla Agreement, Pakistan's attempts at internationalising the Kashmir issue, the \"Rajiv-Benazir\" interlude, Siachen, the Indo-Pak dialogue in general and the impact of the proxy war on the Indian Army. Chapter&nbsp;5 reconstructs the Kargil intrusion. In Chapter&nbsp;6, the committee outlines the role and function of intelligence agencies. Chapters&nbsp;7 and 8 discusses and analyses intelligence on the Kargil issue, as well as the army's subsequent response. Chapter&nbsp;13 and&nbsp;14 summarises the findings and offers further recommendations.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n=== Findings ===\n[[File:Pervez Musharraf - World Economic Forum Annual Meeting Davos 2008 numb2.jpg|thumb|225x225px|[[General Pervez Musharraf]]]]\nChapter&nbsp;13 of the report outlines the findings of the committee. It clearly states that the intrusion had been a surprise for the Indian government. After elaborating on the history of the \"Kargil plan\", the committee discusses the government's, army's, and media's respective responses. They then outline the intelligence findings, elaborating on the role of the [[Research and Analysis Wing]] (R&AW), [[Intelligence Bureau (India)|Intelligence Bureau]] and the military intelligence collection just prior to the war, as well as the lack of inter-agency coordination. The Kargil Review Committee found R&AW\u2018s human intelligence to be weak,<ref name=\":7\" /> but Chapter&nbsp;14 also praises the interception of telephone conversations of [[Pervez Musharraf|Pervej Musharraf]] in China. The KRC report also acknowledges the work of the [[Aviation Research Centre]] of R&AW, which produced aerial intelligence after the intrusion's detection. The report goes into detail regarding the nuclear, technological and media effects of the incident.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nThe report also mentions that the Kargil War could perhaps have been avoided if troops had been stationed there, but also notes that had troops been stationed there all year round and the conflict had still occurred, it would have resulted in huge costs \"and enabled [[Bleed India with a Thousand Cuts|Pakistan to bleed India]].\"<ref name=\":12\" />\n\n=== Recommendations ===\nThe KRC suggested a \"thorough review of the national security system in its entirety\", conducted by a credible body of experts. It also suggested that various task forces should also review specific parts of the system, including: \n\n*[[National Security Council (India)|National Security Council]]\n* Intelligence\n* Counter-terrorist operations\n* Border Management\n* Defence Budget and Modernisation\n* National Security Management and Apex Decision Making\n* India's Nuclear Policy\n* Media Relations and Information\n* Technology\n* Civil\u2013Military Liaison\n* Declaratory Policy for LOC\n\n== Group of Ministers ==\nFollowing the Kargil Review Committee report, a Group of Ministers (GoM) was set up by the Cabinet Committee on Security (CCS) on 17{{Nbsp}}April 2000 to consider the recommendations in the Kargil Review Committee. The GoM consisted of the ministers of home affairs, defence, external affairs and finance. [[Brajesh Mishra]], the [[National Security Advisor (India)|National Security Advisor]], was also assigned as a special guest to the meetings of the GoM and the [[Cabinet Secretariat (India)|Cabinet Secretariat]] provided help to the group.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vifindia.org/sites/default/files/GoM%20Report%20on%20National%20Security.pdf|title=GoM Report on National Security, Chapter 1. Appointment, Approach and Methodology.|website=[[Vivekananda International Foundation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171215090619/http://www.vifindia.org/sites/default/files/GoM%20Report%20on%20National%20Security.pdf|archive-date=2017-12-15|url-status=live|access-date=2018-12-06}}</ref>\n\nThe GoM established task forces, as suggested in the KRC report:\n\n* Task Force on Intelligence Apparatus: [[Girish Chandra Saxena|G. C. Saxena]], a retired [[Indian Police Service]] officer, the [[List of governors of Jammu and Kashmir|Jammu and Kashmir governor]] at the time and a former [[Research and Analysis Wing|RAW]] chief\n* Task Force on Internal Security: [[Narinder Nath Vohra|N. N. Vohra]], a retired Indian Administrative Service officer and [[Principal Secretary to the Prime Minister of India]], [[Defence Secretary (India)|Defence Secretary]] and [[Home Secretary (India)|Home Secretary]]\n* Task Force on Border Management: Madhav Godbole, retired Indian Administrative Service officer and former Home Secretary\n* Task Force on Management of Defence: [[Arun Singh (politician, born 1944)|Arun Singh]], advisor in the Ministry of External Affairs and former Minister of State for Defence\n\nThe GoM came out with its own report \"Reforming the National Security System\".<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://idsa.in/monograph/status-of-jointness-in-indian-security-apparatus|title=Status Of Jointness In Indian Security Apparatus {{!}} Institute for Defence Studies and Analyses|last=Rana|first=Vijai Singh|date=May 2016|website=[[Institute for Defence Studies and Analyses]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181227045824/https://idsa.in/monograph/status-of-jointness-in-indian-security-apparatus|archive-date=2018-12-27|url-status=live|access-date=2018-12-06}}</ref>  It was submitted to Prime Minister Vajpayee on 26 February 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pibarchive.nic.in/archive/releases98/lyr2001/rmay2001/23052001/r2305200110.html|title='Group of Ministers' Report on \"Reforming the National Security System\"|date=23 May 2001|website=Press Information Bureau, India|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181227040738/http://pibarchive.nic.in/archive/releases98/lyr2001/rmay2001/23052001/r2305200110.html|archive-date=2018-12-27|url-status=live|access-date=2018-12-06}}</ref>\n\n== Implementation and impact ==\nAmong the recommendations in the Kargil Review Committee report, the following have been implemented:\n\n* A thorough review of the national security system in India, which was done by the GoM \n* A full-time [[National Security Advisor (India)|National Security Advisor]] \n* Improved aerial surveillance, which has been accomplished by setting up [[RISAT|RISAT]]<nowiki/> satellites and inducting UAVs.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|title=CHAPTER V - Higher Defense Organisation in India Need for Reforms|journal = University|last=Ghosh|first=AK|date=2004-02-09|hdl = 10603/183362}}</ref>\n* A centralised communication and electronic intelligence agency, which resulted in the establishment of the [[National Technical Research Organisation]] in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indiandefencereview.com/spotlights/ntro-indias-technical-intelligence-agency/|title=NTRO: India's Technical Intelligence Agency|last=Bedi|first=RS|date=23 April 2015|website=Indian Defence Review|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180420223424/http://www.indiandefencereview.com/spotlights/ntro-indias-technical-intelligence-agency/|archive-date=2018-04-20|url-status=live|access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref>\n* A [[Defence Intelligence Agency (India)|Defence Intelligence Agency]] \n* The establishment of think tanks, which has resulted in organizations like the Centre for Joint Warfare Studies.<ref name=\":6\" />\n* The reduction of the the age profile in the army<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nThe Kargil Review Committee also recommended that the government find ways to reduce the pension expenditure, which has not yet been implemented. \n\nFrom among the recommendations in the GoM report, the following have been implemented: \n\n* The creation of the post for a [[Chief of Defence Staff (India)|Chief of Defence Staff]], which was accepted by the [[Cabinet Committee on Security]] and was implemented in December 2019. \n* The creation of additional tri-services organisations; in particular, the [[Integrated Defence Staff]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ids.nic.in/vision.php|title=Integrated Defence Staff - Vision and History|website=Integrated Defence Staff}}</ref> the [[Andaman and Nicobar Command]], the [[Nuclear Command Authority (India)|Nuclear Command Authority]], [[Strategic Forces Command]], the [[Department of Ex-servicemen Welfare]], the [[Defence Technology Council]] and the [[Defence Acquisition Council]] have been established.<ref name=\":6\" />\n* An identity card, which has been implemented as the [[Aadhaar]] card.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/aadhaar-journey-kargil-supreme-court-1349503-2018-09-26|title=Tracing the Aadhaar journey: From Kargil to Supreme Court|last=DelhiSeptember 26|first=Prabhash K. Dutta New|last2=September 26|first2=2018UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2018-12-12|last3=Ist|first3=2018 13:25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181206102528/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/aadhaar-journey-kargil-supreme-court-1349503-2018-09-26|archive-date=2018-12-06|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Aftermath ==\nFollowing the Kargil Review Committee, Group of Ministers and the task forces, other committees have been formed to follow up the Kargil Review Committee recommendations and further assess national security such as the [[Standing Committee on Defence (India)|Standing Committee on Defence]] in 2007''',''' Naresh Chandra task force<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/13-years-on-Kargil-panel-report-still-ignored/articleshow/15150628.cms|title=13 years on, Kargil panel report still ignored - Times of India|website=The Times of India|access-date=2018-12-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190106110412/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/13-years-on-Kargil-panel-report-still-ignored/articleshow/15150628.cms|archive-date=2019-01-06|url-status=live}}</ref> in 2011 and the Ravindra Gupta task force in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indiandefencereview.com/news/restructuring-defence-reforms-for-national-security/|title=Restructuring Defence Reforms for National Security|last=Kanwal|first=Gurmeet|date=31 December 2015|website=Indian Defence Review|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419161303/http://www.indiandefencereview.com/news/restructuring-defence-reforms-for-national-security/|archive-date=2018-04-19|url-status=live|access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref>\n\n=== Standing Committee on Defence review ===\nOn July{{Nbsp}}2007, the Standing Committee on Defence, Ministry of Defence, presented a report titled \"Review of Implementation Status of Group of Ministers (GoMs) Report on Reforming National Security System in Pursuance to Kargil Review Committee Report\u2014A Special Reference to Management of Defence\" as a follow up the Kargil Review Committee report and the Group of Minister report.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://idsa.in/system/files/Standing%20Committee%20on%20Defence%2022nd%20Report%202006%202007.pdf|title=Review of Implementation Status of Group of Ministers (GoMs) Report on Reforming National Security System in Pursuance to Kargil Review Committee Report\u2014A Special Reference to Management of Defence|last=Standing Committee on Defence, Ministry of Defence, 14th Lok Sabha|date=July 2007|website=Institute for Defence Studies and Analyses|publisher=Lok Sabha Secretariat|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021043402/https://idsa.in/system/files/Standing%20Committee%20on%20Defence%2022nd%20Report%202006%202007.pdf|archive-date=21 October 2012|url-status=|access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref>\n[[File:Naresh Chandra July 2012.jpg|thumb|Naresh Chandra|alt=|150x150px]]\n\n=== Naresh Chandra task force ===\nThe Naresh Chandra task force (2011) reviewed the recommendations of the Kargil Review Committee, assessed the implementation and accordingly suggested new changes needed related to national security.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rsis.edu.sg/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/PR140301_The_Unending_Quest_to_Reform_India_National_Security_System.pdf|title=Policy Report: The Unending Quest to Reform India National Security System|last=Joshi|first=Manoj|date=March 2014|website=S. Rajaratnam School of International Studies (RSIS) (www.rsis.edu.sg)|access-date=2018-12-06}}</ref> The task force was led by [[Naresh Chandra]], retired [[Indian Administrative Service]] officer, former [[Cabinet Secretary (India)|Cabinet Secretary]] and [[List of ambassadors of India to the United States|ambassador to the United States]] and comprised thirteen{{Nbsp}}other members, of which included [[Gopalaswami Parthasarathy]], [[Srinivasapuram Krishnaswamy|Air Chief Marshal Srinivasapuram Krishnaswamy]] (Retd), [[Arun Prakash|Admiral Arun Prakash]] (Retd), [[V. R. Raghavan|Lt Gen V. R. Raghavan]] (Retd), [[Anil Kakodkar]], [[K. C. Verma|K C Verma]] and [[V. K. Duggal|V K Duggal]]. The committee submitted its report on 23{{Nbsp}}May{{Nbsp}}2012.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nAccording to the task force many of the main recommendations of the Kargil Review Committee have not been implemented, such as recommendations related to defence procurement. The task force further suggested framing a National Security Doctrine ([[National Security Strategy (India)|National Security Strategy]]) among other things.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/diplomacy/india-pakistan-kargil-war-lessons|title=Why Is India Still Ignoring Lessons Learnt From the Kargil War?|website=The Wire|access-date=2018-12-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181221041323/https://thewire.in/diplomacy/india-pakistan-kargil-war-lessons|archive-date=2018-12-21|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* Kargil Review Committee (July 2000). ''[https://www.scribd.com/doc/152396717/Kargil-Review-Committee-Report-1999 From Surprise To Reckoning: The Kargil Review Committee Report]''. New Delhi. Sage Publications. {{ISBN|9780761994664}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20171215090619/https://www.vifindia.org/sites/default/files/GoM%20Report%20on%20National%20Security.pdf ''Report of the Group of Ministers on National Security''], Retrieved from [https://www.vifindia.org/sites/default/files/GoM%20Report%20on%20National%20Security.pdf original] from Vivekananda International Foundation on 12 December 2018.\n*Standing Committee on Defence (2006 - 2007), Ministry of Defence, 14th Lok Sabha (July 2007). ''\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20121021043402/https://idsa.in/system/files/Standing%20Committee%20on%20Defence%2022nd%20Report%202006%202007.pdf Twenty-Second Report. Review of Implementation Status of Group of Ministers (GoMs) Report on Reforming National Security System in Pursuance to Kargil Review Committee Report\u2014A Special Reference to Management of Defence]\"'' Lok Sabha Secretariat. New Delhi. Archived from the [https://idsa.in/system/files/Standing%20Committee%20on%20Defence%2022nd%20Report%202006%202007.pdf original] on 21 October 2012. Retrieved on 12 December 2018 from Institute for Defence Studies and Analyses.\n*Anit Mukherjee (March 2011), [https://idsa.in/system/files/OP_defencereform.pdf ''Failing to Deliver: Post-Crises Defence Reforms in India, 1998-2010.''] Institute for Defence Studies and Analyses (IDSA), New Delhi. {{ISBN|81-86019-88-X}}\n*(25 February 2000). [http://nuclearweaponarchive.org/India/KargilRCA.html Kargil Review Committee report, Executive Summary] Retrieved from nuclearweaponarchive.org, 12 December 2018.\n\n[[Category:Kargil War]]\n[[Category:1999 establishments in India]]\n", "name_user": "Hiabc", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAftermath:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kargil_Review_Committee"}
{"title_page": "Kanch\u014d", "text_new": "{{italics title}}\n{{Nihongo||\u30ab\u30f3\u30c1\u30e7\u30fc|'''Kanch\u014d'''}} is a [[practical joke|prank]] performed by clasping the [[hand]]s together in the shape of an [[finger gun|imaginary gun]] and attempting to poke an unsuspecting victim's [[anus]], often while exclaiming \"Kan-CHO!\".<ref name=\"arcademania1\">{{cite book|last1=Ashcraft|first1=Brian|last2=Snow|first2=Jean|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wX8kAQAAIAAJ&q= |title=Arcade Mania!: The Turbo-charged World of Japan's Game Centers|year=2008|publisher=Kodansha International|page={{page needed|date=September 2019}}|isbn=978-4-7700-3078-8}} (noting that the prank is popular among schoolchildren)</ref> It is a common prank among children in [[East Asia]] such as Japan,<ref name=\"Tomo\">{{cite news|last=Tomochika|title=\"Kanch\u014d!\" wa ikite ita|newspaper=[[Asahi Shimbun]]|date=31 May 2008}}</ref> Korea, Thailand and China. In Korea it is called '''ddongchim''' ({{lang-ko|\ub625\uce68}})<ref name=\"Garrido\">{{cite web|last=Garrido|first=Ben|title=Stranger in a strange land|url=http://www.newsreview.com/reno/stranger-in-a-strange-land/content?oid=1361861|work=Reno News & Review|date=28 January 2010|accessdate=12 March 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Rocket\">{{cite web|script-title=ja:\u300c\u30ab\u30f3\u30c1\u30e7\u30fc\u5c11\u5e74\u306e\u50cf\u300d\u306e\u8e8d\u52d5\u611f\u304c\u30cf\u30f3\u30d1\u306a\u3044|url=http://rocketnews24.com/2011/05/06/%E3%80%8C%E3%82%AB%E3%83%B3%E3%83%81%E3%83%A7%E3%83%BC%E5%B0%91%E5%B9%B4%E3%81%AE%E5%83%8F%E3%80%8D%E3%81%AE%E8%BA%8D%E5%8B%95%E6%84%9F%E3%81%8C%E3%83%8F%E3%83%B3%E3%83%91%E3%81%AA%E3%81%84/|work=RocketNews24|date=6 May 2011|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110705110212/http://rocketnews24.com/2011/05/06/%E3%80%8C%E3%82%AB%E3%83%B3%E3%83%81%E3%83%A7%E3%83%BC%E5%B0%91%E5%B9%B4%E3%81%AE%E5%83%8F%E3%80%8D%E3%81%AE%E8%BA%8D%E5%8B%95%E6%84%9F%E3%81%8C%E3%83%8F%E3%83%B3%E3%83%91%E3%81%AA%E3%81%84/|archive-date=2011-07-05}}</ref> In China, it is popularly called '''Qi\u0101nni\u00e1n sh\u0101.\nThe word is a [[slang]] adoption of the Japanese word for {{Nihongo|[[enema]]|\u6d63\u8178|kanch\u014d}}.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/24/opinion/24iht-edkumiko.html | work=[[The New York Times]] | title=My Un-American Son | first=Kumiko | last=Makihara | date=23 July 2009 | accessdate=2010-05-07}}</ref> In accordance with widespread practice, the word is generally written in [[katakana]] when used in its slang sense, and in [[kanji]] when used for enemas in the medical sense. \n\nPopular Japanese YouTuber Filthy Frank was arrested in 2013 when he pranked school girls in Japan by \"kancho-ing\" them and severely damaging their rectums.\n\nBecause the act involves forced physical contact and can cause physical [[pain]], it could be considered a form of physical [[assault]] or [[sexual assault]], meaning the \"prankster\" could be charged with a [[crime]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.educatortalk.com/2019/04/beware-of-kancho-sexual-harassment-or.html|title=Beware of Kancho: Sexual Harassment or a Game? Naruto the Movie|last=Castillo|first=Adriana |website=Educator Talk|date=6 April 2019|access-date=2019-09-30}}{{better source|reason=It's a Blogger-powered blog|date=September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* ''[[Boong-Ga Boong-Ga]]'', a video game for the Korean and Japanese market that allows the player to engage in simulated ''kanch\u014d''.\n* [[School bullying]]\n* [[Sexual assault]]\n* [[Groping]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.kancho.org/ kancho.org] ([https://archive.is/20120803192530/http://www.kancho.org/ archive]) \u2013 a website \"dedicated to teaching the world about the fun and excitement that is Kancho.\"\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kancho}}\n[[Category:Anus]]\n[[Category:Bullying]]\n[[Category:Practical jokes]]\n[[Category:Sexual abuse]]\n", "text_old": "{{italics title}}\n{{Nihongo||\u30ab\u30f3\u30c1\u30e7\u30fc|'''Kanch\u014d'''}} is a [[practical joke|prank]] performed by clasping the [[hand]]s together in the shape of an [[finger gun|imaginary gun]] and attempting to poke an unsuspecting victim's [[anus]], often while exclaiming \"Kan-CHO!\".<ref name=\"arcademania1\">{{cite book|last1=Ashcraft|first1=Brian|last2=Snow|first2=Jean|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wX8kAQAAIAAJ&q= |title=Arcade Mania!: The Turbo-charged World of Japan's Game Centers|year=2008|publisher=Kodansha International|page={{page needed|date=September 2019}}|isbn=978-4-7700-3078-8}} (noting that the prank is popular among schoolchildren)</ref> It is a common prank among children in [[East Asia]] such as Japan,<ref name=\"Tomo\">{{cite news|last=Tomochika|title=\"Kanch\u014d!\" wa ikite ita|newspaper=[[Asahi Shimbun]]|date=31 May 2008}}</ref> Korea, Thailand and China. In Korea it is called '''ddongchim''' ({{lang-ko|\ub625\uce68}})<ref name=\"Garrido\">{{cite web|last=Garrido|first=Ben|title=Stranger in a strange land|url=http://www.newsreview.com/reno/stranger-in-a-strange-land/content?oid=1361861|work=Reno News & Review|date=28 January 2010|accessdate=12 March 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Rocket\">{{cite web|script-title=ja:\u300c\u30ab\u30f3\u30c1\u30e7\u30fc\u5c11\u5e74\u306e\u50cf\u300d\u306e\u8e8d\u52d5\u611f\u304c\u30cf\u30f3\u30d1\u306a\u3044|url=http://rocketnews24.com/2011/05/06/%E3%80%8C%E3%82%AB%E3%83%B3%E3%83%81%E3%83%A7%E3%83%BC%E5%B0%91%E5%B9%B4%E3%81%AE%E5%83%8F%E3%80%8D%E3%81%AE%E8%BA%8D%E5%8B%95%E6%84%9F%E3%81%8C%E3%83%8F%E3%83%B3%E3%83%91%E3%81%AA%E3%81%84/|work=RocketNews24|date=6 May 2011|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110705110212/http://rocketnews24.com/2011/05/06/%E3%80%8C%E3%82%AB%E3%83%B3%E3%83%81%E3%83%A7%E3%83%BC%E5%B0%91%E5%B9%B4%E3%81%AE%E5%83%8F%E3%80%8D%E3%81%AE%E8%BA%8D%E5%8B%95%E6%84%9F%E3%81%8C%E3%83%8F%E3%83%B3%E3%83%91%E3%81%AA%E3%81%84/|archive-date=2011-07-05}}</ref> In China, it is popularly called '''Qi\u0101nni\u00e1n sh\u0101.\nThe word is a [[slang]] adoption of the Japanese word for {{Nihongo|[[enema]]|\u6d63\u8178|kanch\u014d}}.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/24/opinion/24iht-edkumiko.html | work=[[The New York Times]] | title=My Un-American Son | first=Kumiko | last=Makihara | date=23 July 2009 | accessdate=2010-05-07}}</ref> In accordance with widespread practice, the word is generally written in [[katakana]] when used in its slang sense, and in [[kanji]] when used for enemas in the medical sense. \n\nBecause the act involves forced physical contact and can cause physical [[pain]], it could be considered a form of physical [[assault]] or [[sexual assault]], meaning the \"prankster\" could be charged with a [[crime]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.educatortalk.com/2019/04/beware-of-kancho-sexual-harassment-or.html|title=Beware of Kancho: Sexual Harassment or a Game? Naruto the Movie|last=Castillo|first=Adriana |website=Educator Talk|date=6 April 2019|access-date=2019-09-30}}{{better source|reason=It's a Blogger-powered blog|date=September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* ''[[Boong-Ga Boong-Ga]]'', a video game for the Korean and Japanese market that allows the player to engage in simulated ''kanch\u014d''.\n* [[School bullying]]\n* [[Sexual assault]]\n* [[Groping]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.kancho.org/ kancho.org] ([https://archive.is/20120803192530/http://www.kancho.org/ archive]) \u2013 a website \"dedicated to teaching the world about the fun and excitement that is Kancho.\"\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kancho}}\n[[Category:Anus]]\n[[Category:Bullying]]\n[[Category:Practical jokes]]\n[[Category:Sexual abuse]]\n", "name_user": "2605:6000:1b0b:455a:1539:322a:2352:440e", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kanch%C5%8D"}
